ture]]\n[[Category:Arts festivals in the Bahamas]]\n[[Category:Arts festivals in Barbados]]\n[[Category:Arts festivals in Cuba]]\n[[Category:Arts festivals in Guyana]]\n[[Category:Arts festivals in Haiti]]\n[[Category:Arts festivals in Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Arts festivals in Saint Kitts and Nevis]]\n[[Category:Arts festivals in Suriname]]\n[[Category:Arts festivals in Trinidad and Tobago]]\n[[Category:Latin American festivals]]\n", "name_user": "KittenKlub", "label": "safe", "comment": "wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caribbean_Festival_of_Arts"}
{"title_page": "WNEM-TV", "text_new": "{{short description|CBS affiliate in Bay City, Michigan}}\n{{distinguish|WNED-TV|WNEP-TV|WNET}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = WNEM-TV\n| city                     = Bay City, Michigan\n| station_logo             = [[File:WNEM Logo.png|200px]]\n----\n[[File:WNEM-DT2 Logo.png|175px]]\n| station_slogan           = ''Coverage You Can Count On''\n| station_branding         = '''5.1:''' WNEM-TV5<br>'''5.2:''' WNEM-TV5 Plus<ref name=\"tv5plus\"/>\n| digital                  = 30 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]])\n| virtual                  = 5 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| subchannels              = \n| other_chs                = \n| affiliations             = {{ubl|'''5.1:''' [[CBS]] (1995\u2013present)|'''5.2:''' [[MyNetworkTV]]|'''5.3:''' [[Cozi TV]]|'''5.4:''' [[Ion Television]]<ref name=rei/>}}\n| country                  = United States\n| founded                  =\n| airdate                  = {{start date and age|1954|2|16|p=y}}\n| enddate                  =\n| location                 = [[Bay City, Michigan|Bay City]]/[[Saginaw, Michigan|Saginaw]]/[[Flint, Michigan]]\n| callsign_meaning         = '''N'''orth'''E'''astern '''M'''ichigan Corporation<ref name=mig/>\n| former_callsigns         = \n| former_channel_numbers   = '''Analog:'''<br/>5 ([[very high frequency|VHF]], 1954\u20132009)<br>'''Digital:'''<br>22 (UHF, 2002\u20132019)\n| owner                    = [[Meredith Corporation]]\n| licensee                 = \n| sister_stations          = \n| former_affiliations      = {{ubl|'''Primary:'''|[[NBC]] (1954\u20131995)|'''Secondary:'''|[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] (1954\u20131958)|[[DuMont Television Network|DuMont]] (1954\u20131956)|[[UPN]] (1995\u20132006)<ref name=mig/><ref name=ptv/><ref name=upn/>|[[The WB]] (1995\u20132000) <ref name=\"mig\"/>}}\n| effective_radiated_power = 585 [[kilowatt|kW]]\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|303|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| class                    = [[digital terrestrial television|DT]]\n| facility_id              = 41221\n| coordinates              = {{nowrap|{{Coord|43|28|14|N|83|50|36|W|type:landmark_scale:2000}}}}\n| licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n| homepage                 = {{official website}} <!-- handled by wikidata -->\n}}\n\n'''WNEM-TV''', [[virtual channel]] 5 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]] [[Digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 30), is a dual [[CBS]]/[[MyNetworkTV]]-[[network affiliate|affiliated]] [[television station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Bay City, Michigan]], United States and serving the [[Flint, Michigan|Flint]]/[[Saginaw, Midland, and Bay City metropolitan area|Tri-Cities]] [[media market|television market]]. The station is owned by the Meredith Local Media subsidiary of [[Des Moines, Iowa]]-based [[Meredith Corporation]]. WNEM-TV's studios are located on North Franklin Street in downtown [[Saginaw, Michigan|Saginaw]],<ref name=fj/> with a second newsroom in downtown Flint. The station's transmitter is located on Becker Road in [[Robin Glen-Indiantown, Michigan|Robin Glen-Indiantown]], in [[Buena Vista Charter Township, Michigan|Buena Vista Township]], east of Saginaw. On [[cable television|cable]], WNEM-TV is available on channel 5 on most systems, except on [[Spectrum (cable service)|Charter Spectrum]], where it is carried on channel 7.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Saginaw, MI skyline as seen from the Bearinger Building.jpg|300px|thumb|left|Saginaw skyline as seen from the Bearinger Building with WNEM-TV's studios in the foreground.]]\n\n===NBC affiliate===\nOn the week before May 5, 1952, Goodwill Stations, owner of [[WJR (AM)|WJR radio]] in Detroit, announced the intent of applying for four station licenses which would operate as a regional network\u2014UHF channel 50 in Detroit, channel 11 in [[Toledo, Ohio]], channel 12 in Flint and channel 5 in Bay City.<ref>{{cite news |title=Goodwill Plans |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1952/BC-1952-05-05.pdf |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=Broadcasting * Telecasting |date=May 5, 1952 |pages=66}}</ref> WNEM-TV was founded by the '''N'''orth'''E'''astern '''M'''ichigan Corporation, hence the call letters, on February 16, 1954, as an [[NBC]] affiliate.<ref name=mig>{{cite web|title=WNEM-TV Channel 5 Bay City|url=http://www.michiguide.com/dials/tv/wnem.html|work=Station Listings|publisher=Michiguide.com|accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> Originally, its main studios were located on rented space at [[Bishop International Airport]] in Flint with auxiliary studios in its city of license, Bay City.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} In the 1960s, it moved its main studios to the transmitter site in Indiantown, after flirting with the idea of co-locating the television station on the [[WSAM]] tower in Saginaw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fybush.com/site-20170127/|title=Site of the Week 1/27/2017: Northeast Michigan, August 2016|first=Scott|last=Fybush|date=January 27, 2017}}</ref> During its first four years, WNEM-TV had a secondary affiliation with [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]<ref name=mig/> sharing programming from that network with WKNX-TV (channel 57, now [[WEYI-TV]] channel 25){{citation needed|date=August 2012}} until 1958 when [[WJRT-TV]] signed-on and took that affiliation.<ref name=mig/> WNEM-TV also aired programming from [[DuMont Television Network|DuMont]] until that network dissolved in August 1956.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\nProfessional violinist James Gerity's Gerity Broadcasting bought the station in 1961 and sold it to the Meredith Corporation<ref>{{cite news|last=White|first=Sue|title=Memories of Saginaw's 'Beautiful Music' spark WGER 102.5 FM Historical Society|url=http://www.mlive.com/entertainment/saginaw/index.ssf/2011/03/memories_of_saginaws_beautiful.html|accessdate=August 22, 2012|newspaper=The Saginaw News|date=March 6, 2011}}</ref> in 1969.<ref name=mig/> In the mid-1980s, the station moved its primary studios to their current location in downtown Saginaw. The Becker Road studios would later be used for the Buena Vista campus of [[Delta College (Michigan)|Delta College]], though the complex still houses WNEM-TV's transmitter. By the late 1980s, mirroring a trend in many other television [[media market|markets]], WNEM-TV was the dominant station in Mid-Michigan, helped by NBC's then-dominant prime-time lineup.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\n===CBS affiliate===\nOn January 16, 1995, WNEM-TV and WEYI swapped networks, and WNEM-TV became a CBS affiliate (announced June 30, 1994).<ref name=mig/><ref name=\"nyt94\">{{cite news|title=Meredith Shifts Stations to CBS|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/06/30/business/the-media-business-meredith-shifts-stations-to-cbs.html|accessdate=April 20, 2015|work=New York Times|date=June 30, 1994|page=6}}</ref> The move came as part of the larger [[1994 United States broadcast TV realignment|U.S. television network affiliation switches of 1994]] that saw CBS' longtime affiliate in [[Detroit]], [[WJBK|WJBK-TV]], switch to the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] network,<ref name=\"nyt94\"/> and CBS was unable to get [[WXYZ-TV]] (whose ABC affiliation was renewed), [[WMYD|WXON-TV]], [[WKBD]], [[WDIV]], or [[WADL (TV)|WADL]] to switch networks; CBS eventually purchased independent station WGPR-TV and transformed it into [[WWJ-TV]] in December 1994.\n\nThe day that WNEM-TV became a CBS affiliate, it also took on secondary affiliations with both [[UPN]] <ref name=ptv>{{cite web|title=UPN Network Affiliates| url=https://www.parentstv.org/PTC/networks/UPNAFFILIATES.htm |work=parentstv.org|publisher=Parents Television Council|accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"upn\">{{cite web |title=Michigan |url=//www.upn.com/affiliates/michigan.html |work=Affiliate listings |publisher=UPN |accessdate=August 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060516152053/http://www.upn.com/affiliates/michigan.html |archivedate=May 16, 2006  }}</ref> and [[The WB]] and aired programming from the two networks late at night.<ref name=\"mig\"/> The station relinquished the secondary WB affiliation in October 1999 to WEYI.<ref>{{cite web|title=WEYI-TV Channel 25 Saginaw |url=http://www.michiguide.com/dials/tv/weyi.html|work=Station Listings |publisher=michiguide.com |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> It dropped CBS' daytime [[soap opera]] ''[[Guiding Light]]'' in 1996 due to low ratings, which made it one of two CBS stations in the nation that did not carry the program for what would turn out to be its final 13 years (the other was [[KOVR]] in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], [[California]]).{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} However, by 2007 the show was aired instead on My5 at 10&nbsp;a.m., and stayed there for the rest of its run.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} WNEM now clears the entire CBS daytime lineup on their primary channel, having moved ''Guiding Light''{{'}}s replacement ''[[Let's Make a Deal]]'' over from My5 in 2012. It currently airs at 10 a.m.\n\nIn 2006, WNEM-TV entered into a news share agreement with [[WSMH]].<ref name=fj>{{cite news|last1=Hale|first1=Jane|title=Flint area watchers can find major networks, cable on tube|url=http://www.mlive.com/flintjournal/answerbook/index.ssf/2008/04/flint_area_watchers_can_find_m.html|accessdate=April 20, 2015|work=The Flint Journal|date=May 5, 2009}}</ref> On September 10, 2007, the station dropped its 9 a.m. show, ''[[The Tyra Banks Show|Tyra Banks]]'', for ''[[Better (TV series)|Better Mid Michigan]]''.<ref name=fj0>{{cite news|last1=Pullen|first1=Doug|title=On Media: Asher exits WJRT, WNEM adds news mag|url=http://blog.mlive.com/flintjournal/pullenmyblog/2007/08/on_media_asher_exits_wjrt_wnem_adds_news_mag.html |accessdate=November 18, 2014|work=The Flint Journal|publisher=Mlive Media Group|date=August 3, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:WNEM-DT2.svg|120px|thumb|left|My5 subchannel logo based on MyNetworkTV logo used from May 2008 to July 30, 2018.]]\nBy May 2008, WNEM used its MyNetworkTV affiliation to launch \"My 5\" cable channel along with some [[Detroit Pistons]] games.<ref name=fj/> My 5 was launched later on an over the air subchannel.<ref name=rei/>\n\nWNEM-TV discontinued regular programming on its analog signal, over [[Very high frequency|VHF]] channel 5, on June 12, 2009, the official date in which full-power television stations in the United States [[Digital television transition in the United States|transitioned from analog to digital broadcasts]] under federal mandate. The station's digital signal remained on its pre-transition [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] channel 22,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |title=DTV Tentative Channel Designations for the First and the Second Rounds |format=PDF |accessdate=March 24, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829004251/http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |archive-date=August 29, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-09-221A5.pdf|title=FCC.gov - Appendix B: All Full Power Television Stations by DMA, Indicating Those Terminating Analog Service on or before February 17, 2009}}</ref> using [[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]] to display the station's [[virtual channel]] as its former VHF analog channel 5. However, channel 5 analog did remain on-the-air for a short period afterward with a [[Digital television transition in the United States#Nightlighting|nightlight]] slide with phone numbers and information about the switch.{{citation needed|date=September 2012}}\n\nAs of [[April Fools' Day|April 1]], 2011, [[Xfinity|Comcast]] cable subscribers in [[Holly, Michigan]] and surrounding areas recently had WNEM-TV replaced with Detroit's [[WWJ-TV]] as the main CBS network affiliate. My5 was also replaced with [[WMYD]] as the main MyNetworkTV affiliate. While Holly is much closer to Flint than Detroit ({{convert|15|mi|km|0|disp=sqbr}} compared to {{convert|45|mi|km|0|disp=sqbr}}), it is in the far northern portion of [[Oakland County, Michigan|Oakland County]], which is technically part of the [[Template:Detroit TV|Detroit television market]].\n\nOn November 21, 2011, WNEM-TV aired allegations of sexual abuse against [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Dale Kildee]] that were criticized as politically motivated and a breach of journalistic ethics. An attorney for the station said that the broadcast was protected as it involved a public official and that no actual malice was intended.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lessenberry|first1=Jack|title=Decades-old claims against Kildee don't hold up|url=http://www.toledoblade.com/JackLessenberry/2011/11/25/Decades-old-claims-against-Kildee-don-t-hold-up.html|work=Toledo Blade|date=November 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nWSMH dropped WNEM's 10 p.m. news from their primary subchannel on April 27, 2015, while WNEM moved that program to its My5 subchannel.<ref name=bct0>{{cite news|last1=Dodson|first1=Andrew|title=WNEM TV 5 newscast on Fox 66 being replaced by WEYI 25 starting battle for 10 p.m.|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/bay-city/index.ssf/2015/03/wnem_tv_5_10_pm_newscast_movin.html|accessdate=April 20, 2015|work=Bay City Times|publisher=Mlive Media Group|date=March 26, 2015}}</ref> Also in the spring of 2015, WNEM added another subchannel with an affiliation with [[Cozi TV]].<ref name=tnc>{{cite news|title=Cozi TV Diginet Adds Eight Stations|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/83934/cozi-tv-diginet-adds-eight-stations?ref=search|accessdate=April 26, 2016|work=TV News Check|publisher=NewsCheckMedia|date=March 23, 2015}}</ref> WNEM added a fourth subchannel and affiliated it with [[Ion Television|Ion]] in April 2017.<ref name=wnem>{{cite news|title=How to find ION TV|url=http://www.wnem.com/story/35013758/how-to-find-ion-tv|accessdate=April 12, 2017|work=wnem.com|publisher=WNEM|date=March 28, 2017|language=en}}</ref> While continuing its MyNetworkTV affiliation, My5 subchannel was renamed to WNEM-TV5 PLUS on July 30, 2018.<ref name=\"tv5plus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lmgcorporate.com/wnem/news/Press%20Release-WNEM-TV5%20PLUS-final.pdf|title=WNEM My 5 TV to Become WNEM TV 5 Plus|date=July 12, 2018|accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Programming==\n===Digital channels===\nThe station's digital signal is [[multiplex (TV)|multiplexed]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Digital subchannel#United States|Channel]]\n! [[Display resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio (image)|Aspect]]\n! [[Program and System Information Protocol#What PSIP does|PSIP Short Name]]\n! Programming<ref name=rei>{{cite web|title=Digital TV Market Listing for WNEM-TV|url=http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=WNEM#station|publisher=RabbitEars.info|accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref>\n|- \n| 5.1 || [[1080i]] || rowspan=7| [[16:9]] || WNEM-HD || Main WNEM-TV programming / [[CBS]]\n|-\n| 5.2 || rowspan=4| [[480i]] || WNEM-D2 || WNEM TV5 Plus / [[MyNetworkTV]]\n|-\n| 5.3 || WNEM-D3 || [[Cozi TV]]\n|-\n| 5.4 || WNEM-D4 || [[Ion Television]]\n|-\n| 5.5 || WNEM-D5 || [[Court TV]]\n|}\nprogramming on wnem main channel including the doctors dr phill jeopardy wheel of fortune all by cbs television distribution  \non wnem dt2 dish nation celebrity page  ES tv first run jeopardy first run doctors justice with judge mablean \nprotection court  tmz access dally the real mom how i met your mother cheaters cops bobs burgers sheriffs eldorado country\naccess hollywood the game forensic files   \n===Early original programming===\nLittle to no records are held regarding the station's early programming. The few that were remembered are ''Chester the Clown'', ''Hoss 'n' Stuff'', ''Mr. Hot Dog'', \"Captain Muddy\" hosting ''[[Popeye the Sailor (animated cartoons)|Popeye]]'' cartoons, ''Adventure Patrol'' and the \"Jumping Cowboy.\"<ref name=llpa>{{cite book|last1=Hollis|first1=Tim|title=Hi There, Boys and Girls!: America's Local Children's TV Shows|date=2001|publisher=University Press of Mississippi|page=152|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6UWlOQfdQ64C&pg=PA152&lpg=PA152&dq=Frank+Cady+Bozo&source=bl&ots=7UpXsflhkA&sig=6yExfpenf-K7fwey-ygt2p3UF4s&hl=en&sa=X&ei=K1h2VIi_B6b2iQKN1IDIBg&ved=0CGgQ6AEwDQ#v=onepage&q=Frank%20Cady%20Bozo&f=false|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt launch, the station hired Chet Rogoza as an announcer and drafted as the ''Chester the Clown'' host. Chester only being a [[puppet]] controlled by Rogoza. Harold Stone joined the show as the puppet master for Mr. Shaakestail, Bard disciple dog late in the shows run, which ended in the early 1960s.<ref name=llpa/>\n\n''Hoss 'n' Stuff'' featured a puppet horse played by Jim Adams and the mailman Stuff played by Chuck Waters. Stuff would visit Hoss at the fence for a comedic interchange with Stuff being the straight man.<ref name=llpa/>\n\n''Mr. Hot Dog'' originated as an ad featuring Jim Peyton as the logo character of the restaurant chain of the same name.  Quickly, the character had its own Saturday morning program with the added puppet character of Daddy Cool with a long wiener-shaped nose.<ref name=llpa/>\n\nFrom 1958 to 1968, Chuck Waters as \"Captain Muddy\" of the S.S. Mudhole hosted the ''Popeye'' cartoons. ''Adventure Patrol'' was hosted by station manager Tom Mathews with little else known about the show. A transfer from the [[Cadillac, Michigan|Cadillac]]-[[Traverse City, Michigan|Traverse City]] market, the station had a [[Western (genre)|Western]] show featuring Kenny Roberts, the \"Jumping Cowboy.\"<ref name=llpa/>\n\n===Sports===\nWNEM-TV televises regional and national sports from [[CBS Sports]]. Local sports include games of the [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan Wolverines]] and [[Michigan State Spartans men's basketball|Michigan State Spartans]] men's [[college basketball|basketball]] teams (via the ''[[College Basketball on CBS]]'' contract), and [[Detroit Lions]] home games against [[American Football Conference|AFC]] opponents (via the ''[[NFL on CBS]]'' contract).{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} The station is also an affiliate of the [[Detroit Lions Television Network]] which airs preseason games. Since WNEM-TV's normal coverage area reaches within {{convert|75|mi|km|0}} of the Lions' home [[Ford Field]], it is part of the Lions' [[National Football League television blackout policies|blackout area]]; this applies to both preseason and regular season games.<ref>[http://www.detroitlions.com/media-center/lions-preseason-tv.html Preseason TV] Detroit Lions official site</ref> Channel 5 has also televised three home games of the local [[Ontario Hockey League]] team the [[Saginaw Spirit]]. {{When|date=September 2011}} {{citation needed|date=July 2012}} By 2007, WNEM picked up Detroit Pistons games outside of the network agreements for My5 TV.<ref name=fj/> In February 2007, WNEM picked up 17 [[Detroit Tigers]] games through [[Fox Sports Detroit]]'s Tigers regional TV network primarily for My5 TV.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pullen|first1=Doug|title=Some Tiger games to air on My 5 TV|url=http://blog.mlive.com/flintjournal/newsnow/2007/02/some_tiger_games_to_air_on_my.html|accessdate=April 20, 2015|work=The Flint Journal|publisher=Mlive Media Group|date=February 20, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===News operation===\nIn addition to its main facilities, the station operates a [[Genesee County, Michigan|Genesee County]] Bureau at the Wade Trim Building on [[Saginaw Trail|Saginaw Street]] in Downtown Flint. This had been located in [[Mundy Township, Michigan|Mundy Township]]'s Gateway Center<ref name=fj/> until October 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burden|first1=Melissa|title=Wade Trim Building open to public; more news on downtown expected next week|url=http://www.mlive.com/flintjournal/business/index.ssf/2008/10/wade_trim_building_open_to_pub.html|accessdate=April 20, 2015|work=Flint Journal|publisher=Mlive Media Group|date=October 7, 2008}}</ref> WNEM-TV operates their own [[weather radar]], known as \"First Warn 5 Pinpoint Doppler Radar\", on the eastern side of [[MBS International Airport]] which is also streamed live on its website.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}\n\nWNEM broadcasts news at 4:30, 5, 6 and 9 a.m., noon, 5, 5:30, 6 and 11 p.m.<ref name=bct>{{cite news|last1=Dodson|first1=Andrew|title=WNEM TV5 anchor Katie O'Mara takes leave of absence due to blood disease|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/bay-city/index.ssf/2015/02/wnem_tv_5_anchor_katie_omara_t.html|accessdate=February 19, 2015|work=Bay City Times|publisher=Mlive Media Group|date=February 13, 2015}}</ref> On weekends, they broadcast a morning show at 8 a.m. Saturday and a two-hour show at 7 a.m. on Sunday. Weekend evenings includes local news in the 6 p.m. hour and an 11 p.m. broadcast. While on WNEM-TV 5 Plus, its news department has an hour-long news at 10 p.m. every day of the week<ref name=bct0/> plus a 7 p.m. half-hour on weeknights.<ref>{{cite news|title=WNEM Program Schedule|url=http://www.wnem.com/category/213205/program|accessdate=January 31, 2017|work=WNEM|publisher=Meredith|date=January 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWNEM-TV produced news segments for then-sister radio station [[WJMK (AM)|WNEM]] 1250 AM; {{citation needed|date=July 2012}} this ended after that station adopted a Catholic-based format under new owners. [[WSGW (AM)|WSGW]] 790 AM in Saginaw now rebroadcasts the 6 p.m. news. WNEM-TV 5 Plus previously rebroadcast the main channel's weeknight 6 o'clock newscast at 7, but this has since been replaced by a live newscast at 7.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nIn 2006, WNEM-TV entered into a news share agreement with Fox affiliate WSMH for their existing nightly prime time broadcast at 10 on that station.<ref name=fj/> This came about after that station's owner, the [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]], shut down its ''[[News Central]]'' operation as well as WSMH's news department. Originally entitled ''TV 5 News at 10 on Fox 66'', the WNEM-TV-produced program recently added new graphics and was renamed ''Fox 66 News at 10''. On Monday nights during the newscast, the \"Fugitive Files\" segment aired.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}} On April 27, 2015, WSMH dropped WNEM's hour-long 10 p.m. news from their primary channel in favor of a new 10 p.m. show produced by the now Sinclair-managed [[WEYI]], while WNEM moved that program to its WNEM-TV 5 Plus subchannel.<ref name=bct0/>\n\nIn August 2009, the station began carrying [[obituary|obituaries]] following its weekday morning, Noon and 6 o'clock shows. This service began after local major newspapers in the region including ''[[The Bay City Times]]'', ''[[The Saginaw News]]'', and ''[[The Flint Journal]]'' reduced publication to three times a week in June 2009. At first, a free service when it was launched, WNEM-TV began charging $100 per obituary in September 2009. As of October 19, 2009, over 700 obituaries appeared on the channel and its website, obitmichigan.com.<ref>{{cite news|last=Steinberg|first=Brian|title=Local TV Garners Revenue From Obituaries|url=http://adage.com/article/media/advertising-local-tv-garners-revenue-obituaries/139747/|accessdate=August 22, 2012|newspaper=adage.com|date=October 19, 2009}}</ref> WNEM-TV became the second television in both Michigan and the United States, after WJBK, to air obituaries on a daily basis.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://www.wnem.com/}}\n*[http://obitmichigan.com/ obitmichigan.com]\n*{{TVQ|WNEM-TV}}\n*{{TV Fool|WNEM}}\n\n{{Flint-Saginaw-Bay City TV}}\n{{CBS Michigan}}\n{{MNTV Michigan}}\n{{ION Michigan}}\n{{Meredith Corporation}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wnem-Tv}}\n[[Category:CBS network affiliates]]\n[[Category:MyNetworkTV affiliates]]\n[[Category:Cozi TV affiliates]]\n[[Category:Ion Television affiliates]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1954]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Flint, Michigan|NEM-TV]]\n[[Category:Meredith Corporation television stations]]\n[[Category:1954 establishments in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Ion Television subchannel-only affiliates]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|CBS affiliate in Bay City, Michigan}}\n{{distinguish|WNED-TV|WNEP-TV|WNET}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = WNEM-TV\n| city                     = Bay City, Michigan\n| station_logo             = [[File:WNEM Logo.png|200px]]\n----\n[[File:WNEM-DT2 Logo.png|175px]]\n| station_slogan           = ''Coverage You Can Count On''\n| station_branding         = '''5.1:''' WNEM-TV5<br>'''5.2:''' WNEM-TV5 Plus<ref name=\"tv5plus\"/>\n| digital                  = 30 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]])\n| virtual                  = 5 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| subchannels              = \n| other_chs                = \n| affiliations             = {{ubl|'''5.1:''' [[CBS]] (1995\u2013present)|'''5.2:''' [[MyNetworkTV]]|'''5.3:''' [[Cozi TV]]|'''5.4:''' [[Ion Television]]<ref name=rei/>}}\n| country                  = United States\n| founded                  =\n| airdate                  = {{start date and age|1954|2|16|p=y}}\n| enddate                  =\n| location                 = [[Bay City, Michigan|Bay City]]/[[Saginaw, Michigan|Saginaw]]/[[Flint, Michigan]]\n| callsign_meaning         = '''N'''orth'''E'''astern '''M'''ichigan Corporation<ref name=mig/>\n| former_callsigns         = \n| former_channel_numbers   = '''Analog:'''<br/>5 ([[very high frequency|VHF]], 1954\u20132009)<br>'''Digital:'''<br>22 (UHF, 2002\u20132019)\n| owner                    = [[Meredith Corporation]]\n| licensee                 = \n| sister_stations          = \n| former_affiliations      = {{ubl|'''Primary:'''|[[NBC]] (1954\u20131995)|'''Secondary:'''|[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] (1954\u20131958)|[[DuMont Television Network|DuMont]] (1954\u20131956)|[[UPN]] (1995\u20132006)<ref name=mig/><ref name=ptv/><ref name=upn/>|[[The WB]] (1995\u20132000) <ref name=\"mig\"/>}}\n| effective_radiated_power = 585 [[kilowatt|kW]]\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|303|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| class                    = [[digital terrestrial television|DT]]\n| facility_id              = 41221\n| coordinates              = {{nowrap|{{Coord|43|28|14|N|83|50|36|W|type:landmark_scale:2000}}}}\n| licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n| homepage                 = {{official website}} <!-- handled by wikidata -->\n}}\n\n'''WNEM-TV''', [[virtual channel]] 5 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]] [[Digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 30), is a dual [[CBS]]/[[MyNetworkTV]]-[[network affiliate|affiliated]] [[television station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Bay City, Michigan]], United States and serving the [[Flint, Michigan|Flint]]/[[Saginaw, Midland, and Bay City metropolitan area|Tri-Cities]] [[media market|television market]]. The station is owned by the Meredith Local Media subsidiary of [[Des Moines, Iowa]]-based [[Meredith Corporation]]. WNEM-TV's studios are located on North Franklin Street in downtown [[Saginaw, Michigan|Saginaw]],<ref name=fj/> with a second newsroom in downtown Flint. The station's transmitter is located on Becker Road in [[Robin Glen-Indiantown, Michigan|Robin Glen-Indiantown]], in [[Buena Vista Charter Township, Michigan|Buena Vista Township]], east of Saginaw. On [[cable television|cable]], WNEM-TV is available on channel 5 on most systems, except on [[Spectrum (cable service)|Charter Spectrum]], where it is carried on channel 7.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Saginaw, MI skyline as seen from the Bearinger Building.jpg|300px|thumb|left|Saginaw skyline as seen from the Bearinger Building with WNEM-TV's studios in the foreground.]]\n\n===NBC affiliate===\nOn the week before May 5, 1952, Goodwill Stations, owner of [[WJR (AM)|WJR radio]] in Detroit, announced the intent of applying for four station licenses which would operate as a regional network\u2014UHF channel 50 in Detroit, channel 11 in [[Toledo, Ohio]], channel 12 in Flint and channel 5 in Bay City.<ref>{{cite news |title=Goodwill Plans |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1952/BC-1952-05-05.pdf |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=Broadcasting * Telecasting |date=May 5, 1952 |pages=66}}</ref> WNEM-TV was founded by the '''N'''orth'''E'''astern '''M'''ichigan Corporation, hence the call letters, on February 16, 1954, as an [[NBC]] affiliate.<ref name=mig>{{cite web|title=WNEM-TV Channel 5 Bay City|url=http://www.michiguide.com/dials/tv/wnem.html|work=Station Listings|publisher=Michiguide.com|accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> Originally, its main studios were located on rented space at [[Bishop International Airport]] in Flint with auxiliary studios in its city of license, Bay City.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} In the 1960s, it moved its main studios to the transmitter site in Indiantown, after flirting with the idea of co-locating the television station on the [[WSAM]] tower in Saginaw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fybush.com/site-20170127/|title=Site of the Week 1/27/2017: Northeast Michigan, August 2016|first=Scott|last=Fybush|date=January 27, 2017}}</ref> During its first four years, WNEM-TV had a secondary affiliation with [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]<ref name=mig/> sharing programming from that network with WKNX-TV (channel 57, now [[WEYI-TV]] channel 25){{citation needed|date=August 2012}} until 1958 when [[WJRT-TV]] signed-on and took that affiliation.<ref name=mig/> WNEM-TV also aired programming from [[DuMont Television Network|DuMont]] until that network dissolved in August 1956.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\nProfessional violinist James Gerity's Gerity Broadcasting bought the station in 1961 and sold it to the Meredith Corporation<ref>{{cite news|last=White|first=Sue|title=Memories of Saginaw's 'Beautiful Music' spark WGER 102.5 FM Historical Society|url=http://www.mlive.com/entertainment/saginaw/index.ssf/2011/03/memories_of_saginaws_beautiful.html|accessdate=August 22, 2012|newspaper=The Saginaw News|date=March 6, 2011}}</ref> in 1969.<ref name=mig/> In the mid-1980s, the station moved its primary studios to their current location in downtown Saginaw. The Becker Road studios would later be used for the Buena Vista campus of [[Delta College (Michigan)|Delta College]], though the complex still houses WNEM-TV's transmitter. By the late 1980s, mirroring a trend in many other television [[media market|markets]], WNEM-TV was the dominant station in Mid-Michigan, helped by NBC's then-dominant prime-time lineup.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\n===CBS affiliate===\nOn January 16, 1995, WNEM-TV and WEYI swapped networks, and WNEM-TV became a CBS affiliate (announced June 30, 1994).<ref name=mig/><ref name=\"nyt94\">{{cite news|title=Meredith Shifts Stations to CBS|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/06/30/business/the-media-business-meredith-shifts-stations-to-cbs.html|accessdate=April 20, 2015|work=New York Times|date=June 30, 1994|page=6}}</ref> The move came as part of the larger [[1994 United States broadcast TV realignment|U.S. television network affiliation switches of 1994]] that saw CBS' longtime affiliate in [[Detroit]], [[WJBK|WJBK-TV]], switch to the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] network,<ref name=\"nyt94\"/> and CBS was unable to get [[WXYZ-TV]] (whose ABC affiliation was renewed), [[WMYD|WXON-TV]], [[WKBD]], [[WDIV]], or [[WADL (TV)|WADL]] to switch networks; CBS eventually purchased independent station WGPR-TV and transformed it into [[WWJ-TV]] in December 1994.\n\nThe day that WNEM-TV became a CBS affiliate, it also took on secondary affiliations with both [[UPN]] <ref name=ptv>{{cite web|title=UPN Network Affiliates| url=https://www.parentstv.org/PTC/networks/UPNAFFILIATES.htm |work=parentstv.org|publisher=Parents Television Council|accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"upn\">{{cite web |title=Michigan |url=//www.upn.com/affiliates/michigan.html |work=Affiliate listings |publisher=UPN |accessdate=August 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060516152053/http://www.upn.com/affiliates/michigan.html |archivedate=May 16, 2006  }}</ref> and [[The WB]] and aired programming from the two networks late at night.<ref name=\"mig\"/> The station relinquished the secondary WB affiliation in October 1999 to WEYI.<ref>{{cite web|title=WEYI-TV Channel 25 Saginaw |url=http://www.michiguide.com/dials/tv/weyi.html|work=Station Listings |publisher=michiguide.com |accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref> It dropped CBS' daytime [[soap opera]] ''[[Guiding Light]]'' in 1996 due to low ratings, which made it one of two CBS stations in the nation that did not carry the program for what would turn out to be its final 13 years (the other was [[KOVR]] in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], [[California]]).{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} However, by 2007 the show was aired instead on My5 at 10&nbsp;a.m., and stayed there for the rest of its run.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} WNEM now clears the entire CBS daytime lineup on their primary channel, having moved ''Guiding Light''{{'}}s replacement ''[[Let's Make a Deal]]'' over from My5 in 2012. It currently airs at 10 a.m.\n\nIn 2006, WNEM-TV entered into a news share agreement with [[WSMH]].<ref name=fj>{{cite news|last1=Hale|first1=Jane|title=Flint area watchers can find major networks, cable on tube|url=http://www.mlive.com/flintjournal/answerbook/index.ssf/2008/04/flint_area_watchers_can_find_m.html|accessdate=April 20, 2015|work=The Flint Journal|date=May 5, 2009}}</ref> On September 10, 2007, the station dropped its 9 a.m. show, ''[[The Tyra Banks Show|Tyra Banks]]'', for ''[[Better (TV series)|Better Mid Michigan]]''.<ref name=fj0>{{cite news|last1=Pullen|first1=Doug|title=On Media: Asher exits WJRT, WNEM adds news mag|url=http://blog.mlive.com/flintjournal/pullenmyblog/2007/08/on_media_asher_exits_wjrt_wnem_adds_news_mag.html |accessdate=November 18, 2014|work=The Flint Journal|publisher=Mlive Media Group|date=August 3, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:WNEM-DT2.svg|120px|thumb|left|My5 subchannel logo based on MyNetworkTV logo used from May 2008 to July 30, 2018.]]\nBy May 2008, WNEM used its MyNetworkTV affiliation to launch \"My 5\" cable channel along with some [[Detroit Pistons]] games.<ref name=fj/> My 5 was launched later on an over the air subchannel.<ref name=rei/>\n\nWNEM-TV discontinued regular programming on its analog signal, over [[Very high frequency|VHF]] channel 5, on June 12, 2009, the official date in which full-power television stations in the United States [[Digital television transition in the United States|transitioned from analog to digital broadcasts]] under federal mandate. The station's digital signal remained on its pre-transition [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] channel 22,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |title=DTV Tentative Channel Designations for the First and the Second Rounds |format=PDF |accessdate=March 24, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829004251/http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |archive-date=August 29, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-09-221A5.pdf|title=FCC.gov - Appendix B: All Full Power Television Stations by DMA, Indicating Those Terminating Analog Service on or before February 17, 2009}}</ref> using [[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]] to display the station's [[virtual channel]] as its former VHF analog channel 5. However, channel 5 analog did remain on-the-air for a short period afterward with a [[Digital television transition in the United States#Nightlighting|nightlight]] slide with phone numbers and information about the switch.{{citation needed|date=September 2012}}\n\nAs of [[April Fools' Day|April 1]], 2011, [[Xfinity|Comcast]] cable subscribers in [[Holly, Michigan]] and surrounding areas recently had WNEM-TV replaced with Detroit's [[WWJ-TV]] as the main CBS network affiliate. My5 was also replaced with [[WMYD]] as the main MyNetworkTV affiliate. While Holly is much closer to Flint than Detroit ({{convert|15|mi|km|0|disp=sqbr}} compared to {{convert|45|mi|km|0|disp=sqbr}}), it is in the far northern portion of [[Oakland County, Michigan|Oakland County]], which is technically part of the [[Template:Detroit TV|Detroit television market]].\n\nOn November 21, 2011, WNEM-TV aired allegations of sexual abuse against [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Dale Kildee]] that were criticized as politically motivated and a breach of journalistic ethics. An attorney for the station said that the broadcast was protected as it involved a public official and that no actual malice was intended.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lessenberry|first1=Jack|title=Decades-old claims against Kildee don't hold up|url=http://www.toledoblade.com/JackLessenberry/2011/11/25/Decades-old-claims-against-Kildee-don-t-hold-up.html|work=Toledo Blade|date=November 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nWSMH dropped WNEM's 10 p.m. news from their primary subchannel on April 27, 2015, while WNEM moved that program to its My5 subchannel.<ref name=bct0>{{cite news|last1=Dodson|first1=Andrew|title=WNEM TV 5 newscast on Fox 66 being replaced by WEYI 25 starting battle for 10 p.m.|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/bay-city/index.ssf/2015/03/wnem_tv_5_10_pm_newscast_movin.html|accessdate=April 20, 2015|work=Bay City Times|publisher=Mlive Media Group|date=March 26, 2015}}</ref> Also in the spring of 2015, WNEM added another subchannel with an affiliation with [[Cozi TV]].<ref name=tnc>{{cite news|title=Cozi TV Diginet Adds Eight Stations|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/83934/cozi-tv-diginet-adds-eight-stations?ref=search|accessdate=April 26, 2016|work=TV News Check|publisher=NewsCheckMedia|date=March 23, 2015}}</ref> WNEM added a fourth subchannel and affiliated it with [[Ion Television|Ion]] in April 2017.<ref name=wnem>{{cite news|title=How to find ION TV|url=http://www.wnem.com/story/35013758/how-to-find-ion-tv|accessdate=April 12, 2017|work=wnem.com|publisher=WNEM|date=March 28, 2017|language=en}}</ref> While continuing its MyNetworkTV affiliation, My5 subchannel was renamed to WNEM-TV5 PLUS on July 30, 2018.<ref name=\"tv5plus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lmgcorporate.com/wnem/news/Press%20Release-WNEM-TV5%20PLUS-final.pdf|title=WNEM My 5 TV to Become WNEM TV 5 Plus|date=July 12, 2018|accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Programming==\n===Digital channels===\nThe station's digital signal is [[multiplex (TV)|multiplexed]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Digital subchannel#United States|Channel]]\n! [[Display resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio (image)|Aspect]]\n! [[Program and System Information Protocol#What PSIP does|PSIP Short Name]]\n! Programming<ref name=rei>{{cite web|title=Digital TV Market Listing for WNEM-TV|url=http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=WNEM#station|publisher=RabbitEars.info|accessdate=August 22, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 5.1 || [[1080i]] || rowspan=7| [[16:9]] || WNEM-HD || Main WNEM-TV programming / [[CBS]]\n|-\n| 5.2 || rowspan=4| [[480i]] || WNEM-D2 || WNEM TV5 Plus / [[MyNetworkTV]]\n|-\n| 5.3 || WNEM-D3 || [[Cozi TV]]\n|-\n| 5.4 || WNEM-D4 || [[Ion Television]]\n|-\n| 5.5 || WNEM-D5 || [[Court TV]]\n|}\n\n===Early original programming===\nLittle to no records are held regarding the station's early programming. The few that were remembered are ''Chester the Clown'', ''Hoss 'n' Stuff'', ''Mr. Hot Dog'', \"Captain Muddy\" hosting ''[[Popeye the Sailor (animated cartoons)|Popeye]]'' cartoons, ''Adventure Patrol'' and the \"Jumping Cowboy.\"<ref name=llpa>{{cite book|last1=Hollis|first1=Tim|title=Hi There, Boys and Girls!: America's Local Children's TV Shows|date=2001|publisher=University Press of Mississippi|page=152|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6UWlOQfdQ64C&pg=PA152&lpg=PA152&dq=Frank+Cady+Bozo&source=bl&ots=7UpXsflhkA&sig=6yExfpenf-K7fwey-ygt2p3UF4s&hl=en&sa=X&ei=K1h2VIi_B6b2iQKN1IDIBg&ved=0CGgQ6AEwDQ#v=onepage&q=Frank%20Cady%20Bozo&f=false|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt launch, the station hired Chet Rogoza as an announcer and drafted as the ''Chester the Clown'' host. Chester only being a [[puppet]] controlled by Rogoza. Harold Stone joined the show as the puppet master for Mr. Shaakestail, Bard disciple dog late in the shows run, which ended in the early 1960s.<ref name=llpa/>\n\n''Hoss 'n' Stuff'' featured a puppet horse played by Jim Adams and the mailman Stuff played by Chuck Waters. Stuff would visit Hoss at the fence for a comedic interchange with Stuff being the straight man.<ref name=llpa/>\n\n''Mr. Hot Dog'' originated as an ad featuring Jim Peyton as the logo character of the restaurant chain of the same name.  Quickly, the character had its own Saturday morning program with the added puppet character of Daddy Cool with a long wiener-shaped nose.<ref name=llpa/>\n\nFrom 1958 to 1968, Chuck Waters as \"Captain Muddy\" of the S.S. Mudhole hosted the ''Popeye'' cartoons. ''Adventure Patrol'' was hosted by station manager Tom Mathews with little else known about the show. A transfer from the [[Cadillac, Michigan|Cadillac]]-[[Traverse City, Michigan|Traverse City]] market, the station had a [[Western (genre)|Western]] show featuring Kenny Roberts, the \"Jumping Cowboy.\"<ref name=llpa/>\n\n===Sports===\nWNEM-TV televises regional and national sports from [[CBS Sports]]. Local sports include games of the [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan Wolverines]] and [[Michigan State Spartans men's basketball|Michigan State Spartans]] men's [[college basketball|basketball]] teams (via the ''[[College Basketball on CBS]]'' contract), and [[Detroit Lions]] home games against [[American Football Conference|AFC]] opponents (via the ''[[NFL on CBS]]'' contract).{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} The station is also an affiliate of the [[Detroit Lions Television Network]] which airs preseason games. Since WNEM-TV's normal coverage area reaches within {{convert|75|mi|km|0}} of the Lions' home [[Ford Field]], it is part of the Lions' [[National Football League television blackout policies|blackout area]]; this applies to both preseason and regular season games.<ref>[http://www.detroitlions.com/media-center/lions-preseason-tv.html Preseason TV] Detroit Lions official site</ref> Channel 5 has also televised three home games of the local [[Ontario Hockey League]] team the [[Saginaw Spirit]]. {{When|date=September 2011}} {{citation needed|date=July 2012}} By 2007, WNEM picked up Detroit Pistons games outside of the network agreements for My5 TV.<ref name=fj/> In February 2007, WNEM picked up 17 [[Detroit Tigers]] games through [[Fox Sports Detroit]]'s Tigers regional TV network primarily for My5 TV.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pullen|first1=Doug|title=Some Tiger games to air on My 5 TV|url=http://blog.mlive.com/flintjournal/newsnow/2007/02/some_tiger_games_to_air_on_my.html|accessdate=April 20, 2015|work=The Flint Journal|publisher=Mlive Media Group|date=February 20, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===News operation===\nIn addition to its main facilities, the station operates a [[Genesee County, Michigan|Genesee County]] Bureau at the Wade Trim Building on [[Saginaw Trail|Saginaw Street]] in Downtown Flint. This had been located in [[Mundy Township, Michigan|Mundy Township]]'s Gateway Center<ref name=fj/> until October 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burden|first1=Melissa|title=Wade Trim Building open to public; more news on downtown expected next week|url=http://www.mlive.com/flintjournal/business/index.ssf/2008/10/wade_trim_building_open_to_pub.html|accessdate=April 20, 2015|work=Flint Journal|publisher=Mlive Media Group|date=October 7, 2008}}</ref> WNEM-TV operates their own [[weather radar]], known as \"First Warn 5 Pinpoint Doppler Radar\", on the eastern side of [[MBS International Airport]] which is also streamed live on its website.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}\n\nWNEM broadcasts news at 4:30, 5, 6 and 9 a.m., noon, 5, 5:30, 6 and 11 p.m.<ref name=bct>{{cite news|last1=Dodson|first1=Andrew|title=WNEM TV5 anchor Katie O'Mara takes leave of absence due to blood disease|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/bay-city/index.ssf/2015/02/wnem_tv_5_anchor_katie_omara_t.html|accessdate=February 19, 2015|work=Bay City Times|publisher=Mlive Media Group|date=February 13, 2015}}</ref> On weekends, they broadcast a morning show at 8 a.m. Saturday and a two-hour show at 7 a.m. on Sunday. Weekend evenings includes local news in the 6 p.m. hour and an 11 p.m. broadcast. While on WNEM-TV 5 Plus, its news department has an hour-long news at 10 p.m. every day of the week<ref name=bct0/> plus a 7 p.m. half-hour on weeknights.<ref>{{cite news|title=WNEM Program Schedule|url=http://www.wnem.com/category/213205/program|accessdate=January 31, 2017|work=WNEM|publisher=Meredith|date=January 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWNEM-TV produced news segments for then-sister radio station [[WJMK (AM)|WNEM]] 1250 AM; {{citation needed|date=July 2012}} this ended after that station adopted a Catholic-based format under new owners. [[WSGW (AM)|WSGW]] 790 AM in Saginaw now rebroadcasts the 6 p.m. news. WNEM-TV 5 Plus previously rebroadcast the main channel's weeknight 6 o'clock newscast at 7, but this has since been replaced by a live newscast at 7.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nIn 2006, WNEM-TV entered into a news share agreement with Fox affiliate WSMH for their existing nightly prime time broadcast at 10 on that station.<ref name=fj/> This came about after that station's owner, the [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]], shut down its ''[[News Central]]'' operation as well as WSMH's news department. Originally entitled ''TV 5 News at 10 on Fox 66'', the WNEM-TV-produced program recently added new graphics and was renamed ''Fox 66 News at 10''. On Monday nights during the newscast, the \"Fugitive Files\" segment aired.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}} On April 27, 2015, WSMH dropped WNEM's hour-long 10 p.m. news from their primary channel in favor of a new 10 p.m. show produced by the now Sinclair-managed [[WEYI]], while WNEM moved that program to its WNEM-TV 5 Plus subchannel.<ref name=bct0/>\n\nIn August 2009, the station began carrying [[obituary|obituaries]] following its weekday morning, Noon and 6 o'clock shows. This service began after local major newspapers in the region including ''[[The Bay City Times]]'', ''[[The Saginaw News]]'', and ''[[The Flint Journal]]'' reduced publication to three times a week in June 2009. At first, a free service when it was launched, WNEM-TV began charging $100 per obituary in September 2009. As of October 19, 2009, over 700 obituaries appeared on the channel and its website, obitmichigan.com.<ref>{{cite news|last=Steinberg|first=Brian|title=Local TV Garners Revenue From Obituaries|url=http://adage.com/article/media/advertising-local-tv-garners-revenue-obituaries/139747/|accessdate=August 22, 2012|newspaper=adage.com|date=October 19, 2009}}</ref> WNEM-TV became the second television in both Michigan and the United States, after WJBK, to air obituaries on a daily basis.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://www.wnem.com/}}\n*[http://obitmichigan.com/ obitmichigan.com]\n*{{TVQ|WNEM-TV}}\n*{{TV Fool|WNEM}}\n\n{{Flint-Saginaw-Bay City TV}}\n{{CBS Michigan}}\n{{MNTV Michigan}}\n{{ION Michigan}}\n{{Meredith Corporation}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wnem-Tv}}\n[[Category:CBS network affiliates]]\n[[Category:MyNetworkTV affiliates]]\n[[Category:Cozi TV affiliates]]\n[[Category:Ion Television affiliates]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1954]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Flint, Michigan|NEM-TV]]\n[[Category:Meredith Corporation television stations]]\n[[Category:1954 establishments in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Ion Television subchannel-only affiliates]]\n", "name_user": "174.112.226.101", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eProgramming)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WNEM-TV"}
{"title_page": "EA Sports 08 Collection", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n|title=EA Sports 08 Collection\n|image=\n|caption=\n|developer=\n|director=\n|producer=\n|composer=\n|publisher=[[EA|Electronic Arts, Inc.]]\n|series=EA Sports Collection\n|platforms=[[Windows]]\n|released={{vgrelease|NA|September 22, 2008}}\n|genre=[[Sports game|Sports]], [[product bundling|compilation]]\n|modes=[[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n'''''EA Sports 08 Collection''''' (often abbreviated as ''08 Collection'') is a [[product bundling|compilation]] game containing the [[sports game|sports]] games by [[EA Sports]] in 2007 published by Electronic Arts, Inc.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date= |url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/ea-sports-08-collection |title=EA Sports 08 Collection (Windows) |website=[[MobyGames]] |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> on September 22, 2008. The game contains [[Madden NFL 08]], [[NHL 08]], [[Tiger Woods PGA Tour 08]], [[FIFA Soccer 08]] and [[NBA Live 08]].<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date= |url=https://www.newegg.com/ea-sports-collection-08/p/N82E16832130229 |title=EA Sports 08 Collection PC Game |website=[[Newegg]] |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> The [[ESRB]] rated the game Everyone 10+.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date= |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/ea-sports-08-collection |title=EA Sports 08 Collection for PC Details |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Packaging ==\nInside the case, there are 6 discs,<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date= |url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/windows/ea-sports-08-collection/techinfo |title=EA Sports 08 Collection Specs (Windows) |website=[[MobyGames]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> one for each game and an extra one for all of the games included manuals. There is also a manual for the compilation.<ref name=\"eBay\">{{cite web |last= |first= |date= |url=https://www.ebay.com/p/72404446 |title=EA Sports 08 Collection (PC, 2008) |website=[[eBay]] |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nThe game was met with good reception from buyers, receiving a 4.7/5 on eBay<ref name=\"eBay\" /> and 3.2/5 on Amazon.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date= |url=https://www.amazon.com/EA-Sports-08-Collection-PC/product-reviews/B001GU8ZK0 |title=EA Sports 08 Collection \u203a Customer reviews |website=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== In other media ==\n[[YouTube]] personality Scott Wozniak featured ''EA Sports 08 Collection'' in his Christmas special of 2019, titled ''It's a Bargain Bin Christmas - Scott The Woz''.<ref>{{cite web| last = Wozniak| first = Scott| url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x31rjxZCw_k| title = It's a Bargain Bin Christmas - Scott The Woz| publisher = Scott The Woz| date = December 23, 2020| accessdate = April 19, 2020}}</ref> Following the video's release, the game started being used as a background prop in all Scott The Woz episodes.<ref>{{cite web| last = Wozniak| first = Scott| url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GGiYk3tkRZY| title = Anime Games - Scott The Woz| publisher = Scott The Woz| date = February 9, 2020| accessdate = April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Sports-videogame-stub}}\n\n[[Category:2007 video games]] [[Category:EA Sports Collection games]] [[Category:Electronic Arts games]] [[Category:Windows games]] [[Category:EA Sports games]] \n [[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n|title=EA Sports 08 Collection\n|image=\n|caption=\n|developer=\n|director=\n|producer=\n|composer=\n|publisher=[[EA|Electronic Arts, Inc.]]\n|series=EA Sports Collection\n|platforms=[[Windows]]\n|released={{vgrelease|NA|September 22, 2008}}\n|genre=[[Sports game|Sports]], [[product bundling|compilation]]\n|modes=[[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n'''''EA Sports 08 Collection''''' (often abbreviated as ''08 Collection'') is a [[product bundling|compilation]] game containing the [[sports game|sports]] games by [[EA Sports]] in 2007 published by Electronic Arts, Inc.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date= |url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/ea-sports-08-collection |title=EA Sports 08 Collection (Windows) |website=[[MobyGames]] |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> on September 22, 2008. The game contains [[Madden NFL 08]], [[NHL 08]], [[Tiger Woods PGA Tour 08]], [[FIFA Soccer 08]] and [[NBA Live 08]].<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date= |url=https://www.newegg.com/ea-sports-collection-08/p/N82E16832130229 |title=EA Sports 08 Collection PC Game |website=[[Newegg]] |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> The [[ESRB]] rated the game Everyone 10+.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date= |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/ea-sports-08-collection |title=EA Sports 08 Collection for PC Details |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Packaging ==\nInside the case, there are 6 discs, one for each game and an extra one for all of the games included manuals. There is also a manual for the compilation.<ref name=\"eBay\">{{cite web |last= |first= |date= |url=https://www.ebay.com/p/72404446 |title=EA Sports 08 Collection (PC, 2008) |website=[[eBay]] |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nThe game was met with good reception from buyers, receiving a 4.7/5 on eBay<ref name=\"eBay\" /> and 3.2/5 on Amazon.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date= |url=https://www.amazon.com/EA-Sports-08-Collection-PC/product-reviews/B001GU8ZK0 |title=EA Sports 08 Collection \u203a Customer reviews |website=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== In other media ==\n[[YouTube]] personality Scott Wozniak featured ''EA Sports 08 Collection'' in his Christmas special of 2019, titled ''It's a Bargain Bin Christmas - Scott The Woz''.<ref>{{cite web| last = Wozniak| first = Scott| url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x31rjxZCw_k| title = It's a Bargain Bin Christmas - Scott The Woz| publisher = Scott The Woz| date = December 23, 2020| accessdate = April 19, 2020}}</ref> Following the video's release, the game started being used as a background prop in all Scott The Woz episodes.<ref>{{cite web| last = Wozniak| first = Scott| url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GGiYk3tkRZY| title = Anime Games - Scott The Woz| publisher = Scott The Woz| date = February 9, 2020| accessdate = April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Sports-videogame-stub}}\n\n[[Category:2007 video games]] [[Category:EA Sports Collection games]] [[Category:Electronic Arts games]] [[Category:Windows games]] [[Category:EA Sports games]] \n [[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n", "name_user": "IanTEB", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EA_Sports_08_Collection"}
{"title_page": "Karel Ndjoba", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Karel Christopher Ndjoba\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=yes|1961|07|28}} \n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2014|11|16|1961|07|28}} \n| birth_place   =  [[Namibia]] <br /> <small> (then [[South-West Africa]], [[Union of South Africa|South Africa]])\n| death_place   = [[Germany]]\n| placeofburial = [[Windhoek]]\n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      = \n| birth_name    = \n| allegiance    = {{NAM}}\n| branch        = [[SWATF]]</br>[[Namibian Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1978-2014\n| rank          = [[Brigadier General]]\n| servicenumber = <!--Do not use data from primary sources such as service records.-->\n| unit          = \n| commands      = {{plainlist |\n*Chief of Staff: Personnel\n\n}}\n| battles       = \n| battles_label = \n| awards        = {{plainlist |\n*\n}}\n| memorials     =\n| spouse        = <!-- Add spouse if reliably sourced --> \n| relations     =\n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n| website       = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module        = \n}}\n\n[[Brigadier General]] '''Karel Christopher Ndjoba''' was a Namibian military officer who's last appointment was as [[Defence Attache]] to Germany. His father [[Cornelius Tuhafeni Ndjoba]] was chief minister of the [[Ovamboland]] bantustan.\n\n===SWATF career===\nNdjoba's Military career began in [[SWATF]] the military arm of South Africa's Administration of Namibia in 1978, he served in [[101 Battalion (South Africa)|101 battalion]]. Due to his leadership qualities he was selected for Officer training become one of the first black officers in the battalion. He later became a company commander in 101 Battalion.\n\n===NDF Career ===\nNdjoba joined the [[Namibian Defence Force]] as a pioneer, at Independence on 21 March 1990 Ndjoba was part of the first SWATF  and PLAN combined battalion on parade with the new national colors<ref>https://www.namibiansun.com/news/general-ndjoba-dies-in-g</ref>. General Ndjoba served extensively in the Joint operations directorate of the Namibian Defence force were in 2002 he was promoted to [[Colonel]] and appointed as Senior Staff Officer Operations. He also served as a Brigade second in command in DRC during the [[Second Congo War]] . He served as a part of directing Staff at the SADC Regional PeaceKeeping Centre in [[Zimbabwe]] and was part of the interim  Planning Element for the SADC Standby Force at SADC Secretariat in Botswana<ref>{{cite journal |last=Tomas|first=MF |title=NDF mourns Brig Gen Ndjoba |journal=NDF Journal |volume=6 |date=December 2014|page=20}}</ref>.\nHe was promoted to Brigadier General  in 2009 and appointed as NDF Chief of Staff Personnel at Defence HeadQuarters<ref>https://www.ghanamma.com/2011/06/29/ndf-rejects-non-payment-claims/</ref>.  He also served as chairman of the ISDSC Working Group on Human Resources,<ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/sadc-defence-forces-urged-to-increase-collaboration/</ref>. He was Then appointed as Defence Attache to Germany in 2014.He passed away on 16 November 2014<ref>http://www.namibia-botschaft.de/regierungs-mitteilungen/627-the-passing-brigadier-general-karel-christopher-ndjoba.html</ref>\n\n===Qualifications===\n*Masters of Arts in Security and Strategic Studies\n*Senior Command and Staff Course-[[Canadian Army Command and Staff College |Canadian Land Forces Command and Staff College]]\n\n===Military Decorations===\n*NDF Commendation Medal(Gold).\n*NDF Commendation Medal(Silver).\n*Army Ten Years Service Medal\n* SADC Brigade Service Medal\n*\n*\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ndjoba, Karel}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n\n[[Category:Namibian military personnel]]\n\n\n{{Namibia-mil-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Karel Christopher Ndjoba\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=yes|1961|07|28}} \n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2014|11|16|1961|07|28}} \n| birth_place   =  [[Namibia]] <br /> <small> (then [[South-West Africa]], [[Union of South Africa|South Africa]])\n| death_place   = [[Germany]]\n| placeofburial = [[Windhoek]]\n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      = \n| birth_name    = \n| allegiance    = {{NAM}}\n| branch        = Namibian Army\n| serviceyears  = \n| rank          = [[Brigadier General]]\n| servicenumber = <!--Do not use data from primary sources such as service records.-->\n| unit          = \n| commands      = {{plainlist |\n*Chief of Staff: Personnel\n\n}}\n| battles       = \n| battles_label = \n| awards        = {{plainlist |\n*\n}}\n| memorials     =\n| spouse        = <!-- Add spouse if reliably sourced --> \n| relations     =\n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n| website       = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module        = \n}}\n\n[[Brigadier General]] '''Karel Christopher Ndjoba''' was a Namibian military officer who's last appointment was as [[Defence Attache]] to Germany. His father [[Cornelius Tuhafeni Ndjoba]] was chief minister of the [[Ovamboland]] bantustan.\n\n===SWATF career===\nNdjoba's Military career began in [[SWATF]] the military arm of South Africa's Administration of Namibia in 1978, he served in [[101 Battalion (South Africa)|101 battalion]]. Due to his leadership qualities he was selected for Officer training become one of the first black officers in the battalion. He later became a company commander in 101 Battalion.\n\n===NDF Career ===\nNdjoba joined the [[Namibian Defence Force]] as a pioneer, at Independence on 21 March 1990 Ndjoba was part of the first SWATF  and PLAN combined battalion on parade with the new national colors<ref>https://www.namibiansun.com/news/general-ndjoba-dies-in-g</ref>. General Ndjoba served extensively in the Joint operations directorate of the Namibian Defence force were in 2002 he was promoted to [[Colonel]] and appointed as Senior Staff Officer Operations. He also served as a Brigade second in command in DRC during the [[Second Congo War]] . He served as a part of directing Staff at the SADC Regional PeaceKeeping Centre in [[Zimbabwe]] and was part of the interim  Planning Element for the SADC Standby Force at SADC Secretariat in Botswana<ref>{{cite journal |last=Tomas|first=MF |title=NDF mourns Brig Gen Ndjoba |journal=NDF Journal |volume=6 |date=December 2014|page=20}}</ref>.\nHe was promoted to Brigadier General  in 2009 and appointed as NDF Chief of Staff Personnel at Defence HeadQuarters<ref>https://www.ghanamma.com/2011/06/29/ndf-rejects-non-payment-claims/</ref>.  He also served as chairman of the ISDSC Working Group on Human Resources,<ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/sadc-defence-forces-urged-to-increase-collaboration/</ref>. He was Then appointed as Defence Attache to Germany in 2014.He passed away on 16 November 2014<ref>http://www.namibia-botschaft.de/regierungs-mitteilungen/627-the-passing-brigadier-general-karel-christopher-ndjoba.html</ref>\n\n===Qualifications===\n*Masters of Arts in Security and Strategic Studies\n*Senior Command and Staff Course-[[Canadian Army Command and Staff College |Canadian Land Forces Command and Staff College]]\n\n===Military Decorations===\n*NDF Commendation Medal(Gold).\n*NDF Commendation Medal(Silver).\n*Army Ten Years Service Medal\n* SADC Brigade Service Medal\n*\n*\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ndjoba, Karel}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n\n[[Category:Namibian military personnel]]\n\n\n{{Namibia-mil-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ViceAdmiral", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karel_Ndjoba"}
{"title_page": "Robert Lauder of the Bass", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2018}}\n{{For|the 16th century land magnate|Robert Lauder (land magnate)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n\n'''Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass''' (before 1440 \u2013 c. January 1508) was a Scottish knight, [[armiger]], and Governor of the Castle at [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]]. He was also a member of the old Scottish Parliament.<ref>Young, James, ''Historical References to the Scottish Family of Lauder'' (Glasgow, 1884), p. 90</ref> The Lauders held the feudal barony of [[The Bass]] (the caput of which was its castle), [[East Lothian]], [[Edrington Castle]] and lands in the parish of [[Mordington]], Berwickshire, [[Tyninghame]] in Haddingtonshire, and numerous other estates and properties elsewhere in [[Scotland]].\n\n== Robert of Edrington ==\n\nLauder was the eldest son and heir of Robert Lauder of the Bass (d.1495) by his first spouse Jonet,<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 1471: 1045</ref> daughter of [[Alexander Home, 1st Lord Home|Sir Alexander Home]]<ref>Dunlop, A.I., MacLauchlan, David, Cowan, Ian, editors, ''Calendar of Scottish Supplications to Rome 1433\u20131447'', vol. 4 (Glasgow Press, 1983), no. 885: 219</ref>\n\nPrior to his father's death, Lauder was usually designated \"of [[Edrington]]\" in Berwickshire.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 25 April 1450: 343</ref> After his purchase of the lands of [[Biel, East Lothian|Biell]], in East Lothian he was designated 'of Biel'.\n\nIn 1462 [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]] was recovered by the Scots and Lauder was put in charge of [[Berwick Castle]], until he was succeeded in 1474 by [[David Lindsay, 1st Duke of Montrose|David, Earl of Crawford]]. In 1464 Lauder was paid \u00a320 for repairs to the castle.<ref>Scott, John, ''Berwick-upon-Tweed, The History of the Town and Guild'', London, 1888</ref>\n\nA notorial instrument dated 13 May 1465 narrates:<blockquote>[this] Robert Lauder, son and apparent heir of Sir Robert Lauder of Edrington, asserted that David Lauder of Popil ([[East Lothian]]) had given sasine and heritable possession to his eldest son James Lauder and Jonete his spouse, their heirs etc., of a certain piece of land at Popil, to the prejudice of the first-mentioned Robert, who solemnly protested that the said sasine should neither be valid nor prejudice his right in the land, and for greater security, he, by throwing of earth and stone outside the house belonging to the piece of land, and by breaking a plate with his foot, broke and annulled the said sasine and so possession by James Lauder and his wife. Done at Popil at 7 a.m. on 13th May 1465 before Henry Ogil of Popil, James Ogil his eldest son, and others.</blockquote>\n\n\"Robert de Laweder de Edryngtoun\" is the first witness to a Retour of Service, dated 7 April 1467, of Margaret Sinclair as one of the heirs of her grandfather John Sinclair in the lands of Kimmerghame, Berwickshire.<ref>Historic Manuscripts Commission, ''Manuscripts of Colonel David Milne-Home of Wedderburn Castle, N.B.'', London, 1902: 258</ref> Although he was not yet in formal possession of the Edrington estate (see next entry below) he appears to be regularly using the designation, as eldest son, 'of Edrington'.\n\n==Invested in Edrington==\n\nIn a charter of 1471, [[James III of Scotland]] confirmed to Robert Lauder, son and heir apparent of Robert Lauder of Edrington and the Bass, the lands of Edrington and Coalstell with the fishings of Edermouth (or mouth of the [[Whiteadder Water]]) plus the mill there (at Edrington) which Robert the father personally resigned to Robert junior and his male heirs failing which those relations bearing the Lauder arms.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 1471: 1045</ref>\n\nIn a further charter signed at [[Edinburgh]] on 26 June 1474 and confirmed there on 27 July 1475, James III confirmed a feu charter of Robert Lauder junior, Lord of Edringtoun, and superior of West Nisbet, to David Creichtoun of Cranstoun and his heirs, of the lands of West Nisbet in the barony of [[Pencaitland]], East Lothian, which John de Colquhoun of Luss has resigned into the said Robert Lauder junior's hands. Witnesses included Robert Lauder of Bass, father of said Robert junior, and a William Lauder.<ref>''The Great Seal'', 1477: 1202/1299</ref>\n\n==Governor of Berwick castle==\n\nKing [[James III of Scotland]] again appointed Robert Lauder of Edrington as custodian and governor of the castle at [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]] for 5 years, with a retainer of 200 merks per annum.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 20 January 1477: 1276</ref>\n\nIn 1477 Robert was one of those entrusted by James III to escort the dowry of Princess [[Cecily of York]] for her planned marriage to [[James IV of Scotland|James, Duke of Rothesay]]. Cecily was the third daughter of [[Edward IV of England]] and [[Elizabeth Woodville]].\n\nBain records that on 2 February 1477: \"James King of Scotland signifies to the bearers of the instalment of the Princess Cecilia's dower due at [[Candlemas]]s, that he has sent Alexander, Lord Hume, Robert of Lawdir of Edrington son and heir apparent to Robert of Lawdir of the Bass, and Adam of Blackadder of that Ilk, with the [[Lord Lyon King of Arms]], to conduct them to Edinburgh.\"\n\nA charter of 1477 to Alexander Inglis of tenements of land in Hide Hill etc., in [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]], lists those who own neighbouring properties, which include \"Robert Lauder of Bass junior\".<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 3 March 1477: 1281</ref>\n\n===Other mentions===\n\nA Retour of Special Service was held at [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]] on 20 May 1477 serving Thomas Broun (of lawful age) as son and heir to John Broun (who has been dead three months), in a carucate of land with pertinents on the north side of Flemington, (near [[Eyemouth]], Berwickshire), valued at four merks annually and held in chief of the Laird of [[Restalrig]] [near Edinburgh] and Flemington for service of ward and relief, such services being given as neighbouring tenants in these lands are accustomed to give. Retour given by Henry Congiltoun, Sheriff depute of Berwick. Amongst the jury was Robert Lawder of Edrington, Thomas Edingtoun of that Ilk, Thomas Lumsden of that Ilk, William Douglas, Archibald Manderston, John Skougall and William Lauder.\n\nHe witnessed a charter at the castle of [[Dunbar]] on 18 December 1475 as \"Robert Lauder of Edrington\".<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 27 July 1479: 1428</ref> On 2 April 1486, a \"Robert Lawedar\" was one of the witnesses to document signed on the High Altar at [[Holyrood Abbey]]. As the leading witness was William Hall, Vicar of [[Bara, East Lothian|Baro]], it is probable that this Robert is of the Bass family. Another witness was an Alexander Home.\n\nIn 1489 [[James IV of Scotland]] granted a charter to Lauder of the lands of Beil, Johnscleuch in the [[Lammermuir Hills]], and \"le Clyntis\", with their towers and mills etc., in the Barony of Dunbar, formerly owned by Hugo de Dunbar & Beil, with the lands and mill of Mersington, Berwickshire, which Hugo de Dunbar of Bele also resigned. The charter mentions Robert's wife Isabel Hay.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 12 September 1489: 1894</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Exchequer Rolls]]'' record Robert Lauder of Edrington in possession of the lands of Glensax in Yarrow, [[Selkirkshire]] in 1489/1490/1491.\n\n== Papal petition ==\n\nA Petition to [[Pope Innocent VIII]] signed in the presence of Henry Congleton and others in January 1491, craved absolution for numerous people during the 'recent troubles' in Scotland and the [[Battle of Sauchieburn]] (11 June 1488). Lauder was named as son and heir of the Lord of Bass and Baron of [[Stenton]]. Others include Kentigern Hepburn of Waughtoun, Patrick Skowgale, Alexander Sidserf, William Sinclair, David Renton of Billie & [[Lamberton, Berwickshire|Lamberton]], Alexander Home, Archibald Dunbar, William Manderston, Gavin Home, and John Sommerville.<ref>''Historic Manuscripts Commission, Manuscripts of Colonel David Milne Home of Wedderburn Castle'' (London, 1902), 263\u20134.</ref>\n\nOn 4 August 1494 in a court held at Stenton, before John Swinton of that Ilk, depute and lieutenant of John, [[Lord Glamis]], and Robert Lord l'Isle, King's Justiciars generally constituted from the south side of the Forth; Robert Lauder of Bass showed a charter or writ of resignation by the deceased Gilbery Duchry mentioning that Gilbert resigned the land or tenement of Duchry (in the [[Lammermuir Hills]]), in the tenement of Stentoun, in the hands of Walter, Stewart of Scotland, superior thereof. Robert Lauder of Beil, son and apparent heir of the said Robert, asserted that a charter by his father to him of the mains of [[Stenton]] and three-quarters of the town and territory made no reservation of the lands of Duchry. The witnesses were Robert Laweder, son and apparent heir of Robert Lauder of Beill, James Cockburn of [[Clerkington]], William Hepburn of [[Athelstaneford]], Alexander Sydserf of that Ilk, James Ogill, David Ogill, and others.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Death of father==\n\nRobert Lauder was granted sasine of Stenton, Garvald, and The Bass in 1495,<ref>''Exchequer Rolls''</ref> and the lands of Symprin and Ladypart, near Lauder. This would normally occur upon the death of the head of the family.\n\nA charter registered (but almost certainly signed much earlier) on 1 February 1497 records \"Robert Lauder of Bass and Lord of Auldkathi to Robert Lauder his eldest son and Ysobella [sic] Hay his spouse, and their survivor of them, and their heirs male to be procreated of their bodies, of the lands of Auldkathi lying in the barony of Kynnele ([[Kinnoull]]) and sheriffdom of (Lin)Lithgow. Witnesses were William Hay of Menzen, William Hay of Tallo, Hugh of Dunbar, Gavin Lumsden, Thomas and Peter Wood and James Sinclair.\" The footnote states that the granter's seal is in fair condition.<ref>''Calendar of Writs preserved at Yester House'', Scottish Record Society: 240</ref>\n\n==Visit of James IV==\n\nIn 1497 King James IV visited the Bass\".<ref>John J. Reid, ''Proceedings of the Society of Antiquaries'', 1885.</ref> The boatmen who conveyed him from [[Dunbar]] were paid 14 shillings.<ref>Phillimore, R.P., ''North Berwick, Gullane, Aberlady and East Linton District'' (North Berwick, 1913), p. 50.</ref> Robert was knighted after January 1497 but before July 1498, so probably on the occasion of the King's visit to the Bass.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Legal transactions==\n\nOn 10 July 1498, he raised an action as assignee to the deceased David Dunbar of Bele [Beil], heir of the deceased Alexander Dunbar of Biel, against Mungo Home, son and heir of the deceased John Home of Whiterig, [[Berwickshire]], and Margaret Hume his mother, for postponing and delaying to resign the 12 merk lands of the west end of Mersington, Berwickshire, with pertinents, \"land on the west half of the burne\" and keeping the charters and muniments thereof. The defenders did not appear. The Lords discern them to conform to the reversion produced, and assign 15 January next to the pursuer to prove the value of damages and violated profits and duties.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn July 1501 there was a dispute between Jonet, prioress of the Convent of [[Haddington, East Lothian|Haddington]], (represented by David Balfour of Caraldstone) and Robert Lauder of the Bass, knight, regarding the lands and chapellany of [[Garvald, East Lothian|Garvald]], East Lothian, and also damage made to Lauder's house at [[White Castle, East Lothian|Whitecastle]] (or Nunraw) near Haddington. At the second hearing Robert was present in person. The case was referred to [[Patrick Hepburn, 1st Earl of Bothwell]], for his consideration and adjourned until 15 October 1501.<ref>James Clyde, ''Acta Dominorum Concilii'' (Edinburgh, 1943), nos 230, 233 and 326.</ref>\n\nThe King confirmed a charter signed on [[the Bass]] on 12 July 1502 of Gavin Dunbar of Wester Spott to Robert Lawdir of Bass of the lands of Wester Spott, Gryndanehede and The Newkis in [[Haddingtonshire]], reserving the usual [[liferent]]s for the granter. Witnesses included Alexander Sydserf of that Ilk, Henry Congiltoun of that Ilk, and Kentigern Hepburn of Lufnes [and Waughtoun].<ref>''Register of the Great Seal'', 1502, number 2659.</ref>\n\nSubsequent to that, on 3 January 1503/1504, Gavin Dunbar of Wester Spott renounced his liferent interest in those properties, the renunciation 'done in the burgh of Edinburgh, in the tenement of Mr.Richard Lawson of Hierriggs, in his close thereof.'  Letters of Procuratory were signed at Beil on 6 August 1504, by Robert Lawder addressed to James IV informing him that he (Robert) had appointed Richard Lawson of Hieriggs, [[Lord Justice Clerk]], James Henderson and Richard Bothwell, John Homyll and David Anderson, as procurators, for resigning his lands of Wester Spott, Gryndenhede, and 'le Snyke,' with pertinents, into the hands of the King as superior.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nPatrick Scougal of that Ilk had a tack [lease] of a quarter of the lands of [[Auldhame]], near [[North Berwick]], from George Home of Spott, with an agreement that it would later be feued to him. Agreed and signed at Beil on 26 September 1504, with Sir Robert Lawedir of the Bass one of the witnesses.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nLauder owned property on the [[Royal Mile|High Street]] of [[Edinburgh]], mentioned in a letter of reversion dated 16 April 1505 by Mr John of Murray, burgess of Edinburgh to William of Todrig, burgess of Edinburgh, of an annual rent of 40s Scots out of the houses and land called \"the paintit chalmer\" with the pertinents lying in the said burgh on the north side of the King's Street between the lands of Sir William Lindsay on the east part and the land of the Archbishop of Glasgow on the west part and the land of William Halkerstoune [Haxton] on the south part and the land of Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass on the north part.<ref>National Archives of Scotland GD32/21/3.</ref>\n\n== Pilgrimage ==\n\nIn 1506 Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass went on a pilgrimage to pray at the shrine of St.John of [[Amiens]], accompanied by a large retinue of family and friends.\n\nOn 10 May 1506, at [[Edinburgh]], \"A Lettre of Licence [was] maid to Robert Lawder of the Bass, knycht, his men, servandis, and inhabitantis his landis, Robert Lawder, his son and apperand aire, John Swyntoun of that ilk, Johne Swytoun, his son and apperand aire, Robert Lawder of the Tower of Lawder, Alexander Cockburn of Newhall, Gilbert Wauchop in Howstoun, Alexander Sideserff of that Ilk, George Lile of Stonypath (nr. [[Garvald, East Lothian|Garvald]]), David Lawder of Popill, Johne Forestare of Gammilschelis, Henry Congiltoun of that ilk, Thomas Wod of the Grange, William Gibson and Peter Wod in Akansid, and als all the saidis Robertis and thare tennandis, familiaris, servandis, procuratoris, attornais, factouris and intromettouris, and all and sundri his and thare gudis, rentis, possessionis, annuellis, fermez, etc., for the passing of the said Robert to Sanct Johne of Ameas [Amiens], in his pilgrimage, and uther partis bezond sey in his erandis: And Als respittis him and all the persounis above written, thair tennandis, etc., for all actiounis concernyn the kingis grace, etc., to ceis fra the day of the date hereof quhill his hamecummyn and forty dayis thairefter: And attour exempand the said Robert and all the persouns abone writtin fra the compering to ony parliamentis, justice-airis, chawmerlane-aires schireff courtis and ony uther courtis for ony maner of actiouns concernyn the kingis grace enduring the tyme forsaid.\"<ref>''Register of the Privy Seal of Scotland: 1488\u20131529'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1908), number 1257, pp. 181-2.</ref>\nIt seems clear that those named in this License have feus of certain properties from Sir Robert.{{cn|date=April 2020}} Certainly Popill, and Newhall [Lothians], were owned by the lairds of Bass. What is also clear is that the Robert Lauder at [[Lauder]] Tower, Berwickshire, is not the son and heir of Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass, but a separate entity.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nA Letter of Licence was given to Lauder to [give?] 'analy' [annually?] four merks worth of land of aul [old] extent of his lands of Ladypart, lying in the bailiary of Lawderdale, sheriffdom of Berwick, to what person or persons he pleases. Dated at Edinburgh 27 October 1506.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn 1 February 1508 Sasine was granted to his son, also Robert, of [[the Bass]] and other holdings.<ref>''Exchequer Rolls of Scotland''.</ref> It is assumed Sir Robert died shortly before this date.\n\n== Marriage and descendants ==\n\nRobert Lauder married sometime before 1489 Isabella Hay, daughter of [[John Hay, 1st Lord Hay of Yester]]. She was a descendant of [[Robert I of Scotland|Robert The Bruce]], and a great-great granddaughter of [[Robert III of Scotland|Robert III]].\n\nOf their children:\n* Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass (d. 1517/18).\n* William Lauder, from whom descend the [[Belhaven, Scotland|Belhaven]] and West Barns branch of this family<ref>Lawder, C.A.B.,''The Lawders of the Bass & their descendants'' (Belfast, 1914).</ref><ref>Fleming, D. Hay, and Beveridge, James, ''Register of the Privy Seal of Scotland: 1542\u20131548'', vol 3 (Edinburgh, 1936), no. 1063: 167</ref> including [[Sir Robert Lauder of Beilmouth]].\n* Agnes Lauder, married Alexander Cockburn of Newhall.<ref>Cockburn-Hood, Thomas H, ''House of Cockburn'' (Edinburgh, 1888), p. 264.</ref>\n* Elizabeth Lauder, married before October 1506, David Renton of Billie, & Lamberton.<ref>''Historic Manuscripts Commission, Manuscripts of Colonel David Milne Home of Wedderburn Castle'' (London, 1902), no.500: 227</ref>\n* Margaret, married (1) before September 1498, Kentigern Hepburn of Waughton and Lufness (d. July 1519),<ref>Hepburn, Edward, ''Genealogical Notes of the Hepburn Family'' (1925), 32.</ref> (2) 23 January 1521 (date of Papal Dispensation) Alexander Hume of [[Polwarth, Scottish Borders|Polwarth]], Berwickshire, who died May 1532 when she was still living.<ref>''The Humes of Polwarth'' (Edinburgh, 1894), pp. 179\u2013180</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n* ''Protocol Book of James Young'', [[Scottish Record Society]], Edinburgh, numbers 726, 1392, and 1468.\n* ''Exchequer Rolls: 1488\u20131496'', edited by George Burnett, vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1887),  , pps: 652, 679, 770\u20131, & 738.\n* ''Calendar of Documents relating to Scotland: 1357\u20131509'', edited by Joseph Bain, volume 4 (Edinburgh, 1888), number 1445.\n* ''The Grange of St.Giles'', by J.Stewart Smith, (Edinburgh, 1898).\n* ''Calendar of the Laing Charters, AD 854-1837'', edited by the Rev.John Anderson, (Edinburgh, 1899), numbers 64 (p.&nbsp;250), 196 (p.&nbsp;50), and p.&nbsp;153.\n* ''The Register of the Privy Seal of Scotland: 1488\u20131529,'', vol. 1,  edited by M. Livingstone, (Edinburgh, 1908), number 1349, p.&nbsp;192.\n* ''The Berwick & East Lothian Coasts'', by Ian C. Hannah, (London, 1913), p.&nbsp;29).\n* ''Acts of the Lords of Council in Civil Causes, 1496 \u2013 1501'', volume II, page 261.\n* ''Burke's Peerage, Baronetage and Knightage'', edited by Peter Townend, 105th edition, (London, 1970), p.&nbsp;2687.\n* ''The Lauders of the Bass'', by G. M. S. Lauder-Frost, in ''East Lothian Life'', Autumn 1996, issue 22, {{ISSN|1361-7818}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lauder, Robert, Of The Bass}}\n[[Category:15th-century births]]\n[[Category:1508 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish knights]]\n[[Category:People from East Lothian]]\n[[Category:Scottish soldiers]]\n[[Category:Members of the pre-1707 Parliament of Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2018}}\n{{For|the 16th century land magnate|Robert Lauder (land magnate)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n\n'''Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass''' (before 1440 \u2013 c. January 1508) was a Scottish knight, [[armiger]], and Governor of the Castle at [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]]. He was also a member of the old Scottish Parliament.<ref>Young, James, ''Historical References to the Scottish Family of Lauder'' (Glasgow, 1884), p. 90</ref> The Lauders held the feudal barony of [[The Bass]] (the caput of which was its castle), [[East Lothian]], [[Edrington Castle]] and lands in the parish of [[Mordington]], Berwickshire, [[Tyninghame]] in Haddingtonshire, and numerous other estates and properties elsewhere in [[Scotland]].\n\n== Robert of Edrington ==\n\nLauder was the eldest son and heir of Robert Lauder of the Bass (d.1495) by his first spouse Jonet,<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 1471: 1045</ref> daughter of [[Alexander Home, 1st Lord Home|Sir Alexander Home]]<ref>Dunlop, A.I., MacLauchlan, David, Cowan, Ian, editors, ''Calendar of Scottish Supplications to Rome 1433\u20131447'', vol. 4 (Glasgow Press, 1983), no. 885: 219</ref>\n\nPrior to his father's death, Lauder was usually designated \"of [[Edrington]]\" in Berwickshire.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 25 April 1450: 343</ref> After his purchase of the lands of [[Biel, East Lothian|Biell]], in East Lothian he was designated 'of Biel'.\n\nIn 1462 [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]] was recovered by the Scots and Lauder was put in charge of [[Berwick Castle]], until he was succeeded in 1474 by [[David Lindsay, 1st Duke of Montrose|David, Earl of Crawford]]. In 1464 Lauder was paid \u00a320 for repairs to the castle.<ref>Scott, John, ''Berwick-upon-Tweed, The History of the Town and Guild'', London, 1888</ref>\n\nA notorial instrument dated 13 May 1465 narrates:<blockquote>[this] Robert Lauder, son and apparent heir of Sir Robert Lauder of Edrington, asserted that David Lauder of Popil ([[East Lothian]]) had given sasine and heritable possession to his eldest son James Lauder and Jonete his spouse, their heirs etc., of a certain piece of land at Popil, to the prejudice of the first-mentioned Robert, who solemnly protested that the said sasine should neither be valid nor prejudice his right in the land, and for greater security, he, by throwing of earth and stone outside the house belonging to the piece of land, and by breaking a plate with his foot, broke and annulled the said sasine and so possession by James Lauder and his wife. Done at Popil at 7 a.m. on 13th May 1465 before Henry Ogil of Popil, James Ogil his eldest son, and others.</blockquote>\n\n\"Robert de Laweder de Edryngtoun\" is the first witness to a Retour of Service, dated 7 April 1467, of Margaret Sinclair as one of the heirs of her grandfather John Sinclair in the lands of Kimmerghame, Berwickshire.<ref>Historic Manuscripts Commission, ''Manuscripts of Colonel David Milne-Home of Wedderburn Castle, N.B.'', London, 1902: 258</ref> Although he was not yet in formal possession of the Edrington estate (see next entry below) he appears to be regularly using the designation, as eldest son, 'of Edrington'.\n\n==Invested in Edrington==\n\nIn a charter of 1471, [[James III of Scotland]] confirmed to Robert Lauder, son and heir apparent of Robert Lauder of Edrington and the Bass, the lands of Edrington and Coalstell with the fishings of Edermouth (or mouth of the [[Whiteadder Water]]) plus the mill there (at Edrington) which Robert the father personally resigned to Robert junior and his male heirs failing which those relations bearing the Lauder arms.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 1471: 1045</ref>\n\nIn a further charter signed at [[Edinburgh]] on 26 June 1474 and confirmed there on 27 July 1475, James III confirmed a feu charter of Robert Lauder junior, Lord of Edringtoun, and superior of West Nisbet, to David Creichtoun of Cranstoun and his heirs, of the lands of West Nisbet in the barony of [[Pencaitland]], East Lothian, which John de Colquhoun of Luss has resigned into the said Robert Lauder junior's hands. Witnesses included Robert Lauder of Bass, father of said Robert junior, and a William Lauder.<ref>''The Great Seal'', 1477: 1202/1299</ref>\n\n==Governor of Berwick castle==\n\nKing [[James III of Scotland]] again appointed Robert Lauder of Edrington as custodian and governor of the castle at [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]] for 5 years, with a retainer of 200 merks per annum.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 20 January 1477: 1276</ref>\n\nIn 1477 Robert was one of those entrusted by James III to escort the dowry of Princess [[Cecily of York]] for her planned marriage to [[James IV of Scotland|James, Duke of Rothesay]]. Cecily was the third daughter of [[Edward IV of England]] and [[Elizabeth Woodville]].\n\nBain records that on 2 February 1477: \"James King of Scotland signifies to the bearers of the instalment of the Princess Cecilia's dower due at [[Candlemas]]s, that he has sent Alexander, Lord Hume, Robert of Lawdir of Edrington son and heir apparent to Robert of Lawdir of the Bass, and Adam of Blackadder of that Ilk, with the [[Lord Lyon King of Arms]], to conduct them to Edinburgh.\"\n\nA charter of 1477 to Alexander Inglis of tenements of land in Hide Hill etc., in [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]], lists those who own neighbouring properties, which include \"Robert Lauder of Bass junior\".<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 3 March 1477: 1281</ref>\n\n===Other mentions===\n\nA Retour of Special Service was held at [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]] on 20 May 1477 serving Thomas Broun (of lawful age) as son and heir to John Broun (who has been dead three months), in a carucate of land with pertinents on the north side of Flemington, (near [[Eyemouth]], Berwickshire), valued at four merks annually and held in chief of the Laird of [[Restalrig]] [near Edinburgh] and Flemington for service of ward and relief, such services being given as neighbouring tenants in these lands are accustomed to give. Retour given by Henry Congiltoun, Sheriff depute of Berwick. Amongst the jury was Robert Lawder of Edrington, Thomas Edingtoun of that Ilk, Thomas Lumsden of that Ilk, William Douglas, Archibald Manderston, John Skougall and William Lauder.\n\nHe witnessed a charter at the castle of [[Dunbar]] on 18 December 1475 as \"Robert Lauder of Edrington\".<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 27 July 1479: 1428</ref> On 2 April 1486, a \"Robert Lawedar\" was one of the witnesses to document signed on the High Altar at [[Holyrood Abbey]]. As the leading witness was William Hall, Vicar of [[Bara, East Lothian|Baro]], it is probable that this Robert is of the Bass family. Another witness was an Alexander Home.\n\nIn 1489 [[James IV of Scotland]] granted a charter to Lauder of the lands of Beil, Johnscleuch in the [[Lammermuir Hills]], and \"le Clyntis\", with their towers and mills etc., in the Barony of Dunbar, formerly owned by Hugo de Dunbar & Beil, with the lands and mill of Mersington, Berwickshire, which Hugo de Dunbar of Bele also resigned. The charter mentions Robert's wife Isabel Hay.<ref>''The Great Seal of Scotland'', 12 September 1489: 1894</ref>\n\nThe''[[Exchequer Rolls]]'' record Robert Lauder of Edrington in possession of the lands of Glensax in Yarrow, [[Selkirkshire]] in 1489/1490/1491.\n\n== Papal petition ==\n\nA Petition to [[Pope Innocent VIII]] signed in the presence of Henry Congleton and others in January 1491, craved absolution for numerous people during the 'recent troubles' in Scotland and the [[Battle of Sauchieburn]] (11 June 1488). Lauder was named as son and heir of the Lord of Bass and Baron of [[Stenton]]. Others include Kentigern Hepburn of Waughtoun, Patrick Skowgale, Alexander Sidserf, William Sinclair, David Renton of Billie & [[Lamberton, Berwickshire|Lamberton]], Alexander Home, Archibald Dunbar, William Manderston, Gavin Home, and John Sommerville.<ref>''Historic Manuscripts Commission, Manuscripts of Colonel David Milne Home of Wedderburn Castle'' (London, 1902), 263\u20134.</ref>\n\nOn 4 August 1494 in a court held at Stenton, before John Swinton of that Ilk, depute and lieutenant of John, [[Lord Glamis]], and Robert Lord l'Isle, King's Justiciars generally constituted from the south side of the Forth; Robert Lauder of Bass showed a charter or writ of resignation by the deceased Gilbery Duchry mentioning that Gilbert resigned the land or tenement of Duchry (in the [[Lammermuir Hills]]), in the tenement of Stentoun, in the hands of Walter, Stewart of Scotland, superior thereof. Robert Lauder of Beil, son and apparent heir of the said Robert, asserted that a charter by his father to him of the mains of [[Stenton]] and three-quarters of the town and territory made no reservation of the lands of Duchry. The witnesses were Robert Laweder, son and apparent heir of Robert Lauder of Beill, James Cockburn of [[Clerkington]], William Hepburn of [[Athelstaneford]], Alexander Sydserf of that Ilk, James Ogill, David Ogill, and others.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Death of father==\n\nRobert Lauder was granted sasine of Stenton, Garvald, and The Bass in 1495,<ref>''Exchequer Rolls''</ref> and the lands of Symprin and Ladypart, near Lauder. This would normally occur upon the death of the head of the family.\n\nA charter registered (but almost certainly signed much earlier) on 1 February 1497 records \"Robert Lauder of Bass and Lord of Auldkathi to Robert Lauder his eldest son and Ysobella [sic] Hay his spouse, and their survivor of them, and their heirs male to be procreated of their bodies, of the lands of Auldkathi lying in the barony of Kynnele ([[Kinnoull]]) and sheriffdom of (Lin)Lithgow. Witnesses were William Hay of Menzen, William Hay of Tallo, Hugh of Dunbar, Gavin Lumsden, Thomas and Peter Wood and James Sinclair.\" The footnote states that the granter's seal is in fair condition.<ref>''Calendar of Writs preserved at Yester House'', Scottish Record Society: 240</ref>\n\n==Visit of James IV==\n\nIn 1497 King James IV visited the Bass\".<ref>John J. Reid, ''Proceedings of the Society of Antiquaries'', 1885.</ref> The boatmen who conveyed him from [[Dunbar]] were paid 14 shillings.<ref>Phillimore, R.P., ''North Berwick, Gullane, Aberlady and East Linton District'' (North Berwick, 1913), p. 50.</ref> Robert was knighted after January 1497 but before July 1498, so probably on the occasion of the King's visit to the Bass.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Legal transactions==\n\nOn 10 July 1498, he raised an action as assignee to the deceased David Dunbar of Bele [Beil], heir of the deceased Alexander Dunbar of Biel, against Mungo Home, son and heir of the deceased John Home of Whiterig, [[Berwickshire]], and Margaret Hume his mother, for postponing and delaying to resign the 12 merk lands of the west end of Mersington, Berwickshire, with pertinents, \"land on the west half of the burne\" and keeping the charters and muniments thereof. The defenders did not appear. The Lords discern them to conform to the reversion produced, and assign 15 January next to the pursuer to prove the value of damages and violated profits and duties.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn July 1501 there was a dispute between Jonet, prioress of the Convent of [[Haddington, East Lothian|Haddington]], (represented by David Balfour of Caraldstone) and Robert Lauder of the Bass, knight, regarding the lands and chapellany of [[Garvald, East Lothian|Garvald]], East Lothian, and also damage made to Lauder's house at [[White Castle, East Lothian|Whitecastle]] (or Nunraw) near Haddington. At the second hearing Robert was present in person. The case was referred to [[Patrick Hepburn, 1st Earl of Bothwell]], for his consideration and adjourned until 15 October 1501.<ref>James Clyde, ''Acta Dominorum Concilii'' (Edinburgh, 1943), nos 230, 233 and 326.</ref>\n\nThe King confirmed a charter signed on [[the Bass]] on 12 July 1502 of Gavin Dunbar of Wester Spott to Robert Lawdir of Bass of the lands of Wester Spott, Gryndanehede and The Newkis in [[Haddingtonshire]], reserving the usual [[liferent]]s for the granter. Witnesses included Alexander Sydserf of that Ilk, Henry Congiltoun of that Ilk, and Kentigern Hepburn of Lufnes [and Waughtoun].<ref>''Register of the Great Seal'', 1502, number 2659.</ref>\n\nSubsequent to that, on 3 January 1503/1504, Gavin Dunbar of Wester Spott renounced his liferent interest in those properties, the renunciation 'done in the burgh of Edinburgh, in the tenement of Mr.Richard Lawson of Hierriggs, in his close thereof.'  Letters of Procuratory were signed at Beil on 6 August 1504, by Robert Lawder addressed to James IV informing him that he (Robert) had appointed Richard Lawson of Hieriggs, [[Lord Justice Clerk]], James Henderson and Richard Bothwell, John Homyll and David Anderson, as procurators, for resigning his lands of Wester Spott, Gryndenhede, and 'le Snyke,' with pertinents, into the hands of the King as superior.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nPatrick Scougal of that Ilk had a tack [lease] of a quarter of the lands of [[Auldhame]], near [[North Berwick]], from George Home of Spott, with an agreement that it would later be feued to him. Agreed and signed at Beil on 26 September 1504, with Sir Robert Lawedir of the Bass one of the witnesses.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nLauder owned property on the [[Royal Mile|High Street]] of [[Edinburgh]], mentioned in a letter of reversion dated 16 April 1505 by Mr John of Murray, burgess of Edinburgh to William of Todrig, burgess of Edinburgh, of an annual rent of 40s Scots out of the houses and land called \"the paintit chalmer\" with the pertinents lying in the said burgh on the north side of the King's Street between the lands of Sir William Lindsay on the east part and the land of the Archbishop of Glasgow on the west part and the land of William Halkerstoune [Haxton] on the south part and the land of Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass on the north part.<ref>National Archives of Scotland GD32/21/3.</ref>\n\n== Pilgrimage ==\n\nIn 1506 Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass went on a pilgrimage to pray at the shrine of St.John of [[Amiens]], accompanied by a large retinue of family and friends.\n\nOn 10 May 1506, at [[Edinburgh]], \"A Lettre of Licence [was] maid to Robert Lawder of the Bass, knycht, his men, servandis, and inhabitantis his landis, Robert Lawder, his son and apperand aire, John Swyntoun of that ilk, Johne Swytoun, his son and apperand aire, Robert Lawder of the Tower of Lawder, Alexander Cockburn of Newhall, Gilbert Wauchop in Howstoun, Alexander Sideserff of that Ilk, George Lile of Stonypath (nr. [[Garvald, East Lothian|Garvald]]), David Lawder of Popill, Johne Forestare of Gammilschelis, Henry Congiltoun of that ilk, Thomas Wod of the Grange, William Gibson and Peter Wod in Akansid, and als all the saidis Robertis and thare tennandis, familiaris, servandis, procuratoris, attornais, factouris and intromettouris, and all and sundri his and thare gudis, rentis, possessionis, annuellis, fermez, etc., for the passing of the said Robert to Sanct Johne of Ameas [Amiens], in his pilgrimage, and uther partis bezond sey in his erandis: And Als respittis him and all the persounis above written, thair tennandis, etc., for all actiounis concernyn the kingis grace, etc., to ceis fra the day of the date hereof quhill his hamecummyn and forty dayis thairefter: And attour exempand the said Robert and all the persouns abone writtin fra the compering to ony parliamentis, justice-airis, chawmerlane-aires schireff courtis and ony uther courtis for ony maner of actiouns concernyn the kingis grace enduring the tyme forsaid.\"<ref>''Register of the Privy Seal of Scotland: 1488\u20131529'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1908), number 1257, pp. 181-2.</ref>\nIt seems clear that those named in this License have feus of certain properties from Sir Robert.{{cn|date=April 2020}} Certainly Popill, and Newhall [Lothians], were owned by the lairds of Bass. What is also clear is that the Robert Lauder at [[Lauder]] Tower, Berwickshire, is not the son and heir of Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass, but a separate entity.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nA Letter of Licence was given to Lauder to [give?] 'analy' [annually?] four merks worth of land of aul [old] extent of his lands of Ladypart, lying in the bailiary of Lawderdale, sheriffdom of Berwick, to what person or persons he pleases. Dated at Edinburgh 27 October 1506.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn 1 February 1508 Sasine was granted to his son, also Robert, of [[the Bass]] and other holdings.<ref>''Exchequer Rolls of Scotland''.</ref> It is assumed Sir Robert died shortly before this date.\n\n== Marriage and descendants ==\n\nRobert Lauder married sometime before 1489 Isabella Hay, daughter of [[John Hay, 1st Lord Hay of Yester]]. She was a descendant of [[Robert I of Scotland|Robert The Bruce]], and a great-great granddaughter of [[Robert III of Scotland|Robert III]].\n\nOf their children:\n* Sir Robert Lauder of the Bass (d. 1517/18).\n* William Lauder, from whom descend the [[Belhaven, Scotland|Belhaven]] and West Barns branch of this family<ref>Lawder, C.A.B.,''The Lawders of the Bass & their descendants'' (Belfast, 1914).</ref><ref>Fleming, D. Hay, and Beveridge, James, ''Register of the Privy Seal of Scotland: 1542\u20131548'', vol 3 (Edinburgh, 1936), no. 1063: 167</ref> including [[Sir Robert Lauder of Beilmouth]].\n* Agnes Lauder, married Alexander Cockburn of Newhall.<ref>Cockburn-Hood, Thomas H, ''House of Cockburn'' (Edinburgh, 1888), p. 264.</ref>\n* Elizabeth Lauder, married before October 1506, David Renton of Billie, & Lamberton.<ref>''Historic Manuscripts Commission, Manuscripts of Colonel David Milne Home of Wedderburn Castle'' (London, 1902), no.500: 227</ref>\n* Margaret, married (1) before September 1498, Kentigern Hepburn of Waughton and Lufness (d. July 1519),<ref>Hepburn, Edward, ''Genealogical Notes of the Hepburn Family'' (1925), 32.</ref> (2) 23 January 1521 (date of Papal Dispensation) Alexander Hume of [[Polwarth, Scottish Borders|Polwarth]], Berwickshire, who died May 1532 when she was still living.<ref>''The Humes of Polwarth'' (Edinburgh, 1894), pp. 179\u2013180</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n* ''Protocol Book of James Young'', [[Scottish Record Society]], Edinburgh, numbers 726, 1392, and 1468.\n* ''Exchequer Rolls: 1488\u20131496'', edited by George Burnett, vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1887),  , pps: 652, 679, 770\u20131, & 738.\n* ''Calendar of Documents relating to Scotland: 1357\u20131509'', edited by Joseph Bain, volume 4 (Edinburgh, 1888), number 1445.\n* ''The Grange of St.Giles'', by J.Stewart Smith, (Edinburgh, 1898).\n* ''Calendar of the Laing Charters, AD 854-1837'', edited by the Rev.John Anderson, (Edinburgh, 1899), numbers 64 (p.&nbsp;250), 196 (p.&nbsp;50), and p.&nbsp;153.\n* ''The Register of the Privy Seal of Scotland: 1488\u20131529,'', vol. 1,  edited by M. Livingstone, (Edinburgh, 1908), number 1349, p.&nbsp;192.\n* ''The Berwick & East Lothian Coasts'', by Ian C. Hannah, (London, 1913), p.&nbsp;29).\n* ''Acts of the Lords of Council in Civil Causes, 1496 \u2013 1501'', volume II, page 261.\n* ''Burke's Peerage, Baronetage and Knightage'', edited by Peter Townend, 105th edition, (London, 1970), p.&nbsp;2687.\n* ''The Lauders of the Bass'', by G. M. S. Lauder-Frost, in ''East Lothian Life'', Autumn 1996, issue 22, {{ISSN|1361-7818}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lauder, Robert, Of The Bass}}\n[[Category:15th-century births]]\n[[Category:1508 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish knights]]\n[[Category:People from East Lothian]]\n[[Category:Scottish soldiers]]\n[[Category:Members of the pre-1707 Parliament of Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther mentions:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Lauder_of_the_Bass"}
{"title_page": "Human impact on marine life", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Global cumulative human impact on the ocean.png|thumb|upright=1.8| {{center|Global cumulative human impact on the ocean <ref name=Halpern2019>Halpern, B.S., Frazier, M., Afflerbach, J. et&nbsp;al. (2019) \"Recent pace of change in human impact on the world\u2019s ocean.\" ''Nature Scientific Reports'', '''9''': 11609. {{doi|10.1038/s41598-019-47201-9}}</ref><ref>Halpern, B.S., Walbridge, S., Selkoe, K.A., Kappel, C.V., Micheli, F., D'agrosa, C., Bruno, J.F., Casey, K.S., Ebert, C., Fox, H.E. and Fujita, R. (2008) \"A global map of human impact on marine ecosystems\". ''Science'', '''319'''(5865): 948\u2013952. {{doi|10.1126/science.1149345}}</ref>}}]]\n{{marine life sidebar}}\n\nHuman activities affect [[marine life]] and [[marine habitat]]s through [[overfishing]], [[habitat loss]], the introduction of [[invasive species]], [[Marine pollution|ocean pollution]], [[ocean acidification]] and [[ocean warming]]. These impact [[marine ecosystem]]s and [[Marine food web|food webs]] and may result in consequences as yet unrecognised for the [[biodiversity]] and continuation of marine life forms.<ref>[https://www.geomar.de/en/research/human-impacts-on-marine-ecosystems/ Human impacts on marine ecosystems] GEOMAR Helmholtz Centre for Ocean Research. Retrieved 22 October 2019.</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[IPCC]] (2019), since 1950 \"many marine species across various groups have undergone shifts in geographical range and seasonal activities in response to ocean warming, sea ice change and biogeochemical changes, such as oxygen loss, to their habitats.\"<ref>{{Cite report| title = Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate (SROCC) |work=IPCC| access-date = 25 March 2020 |date = 25 September 2019| url = https://www.ipcc.ch/report/srocc |pages=2 }}</ref>\n\nIt has been estimated only 13% of the ocean area remains as [[wilderness]], mostly in open ocean areas rather than along the coast.<ref>Jones, K.R., Klein, C.J., Halpern, B.S., Venter, O., Grantham, H., Kuempel, C.D., Shumway, N., Friedlander, A.M., Possingham, H.P. and Watson, J.E. (2018) \"The location and protection status of Earth\u2019s diminishing marine wilderness\". ''Current Biology'', '''28'''(15): 2506\u20132512. {{doi|10.1016/j.cub.2018.06.010}}</ref>\n\n==Overfishing==\n[[File:Fishing down the food web.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5| {{center|[[Fishing down the foodweb]]<br />Overfishing of high trophic fish like [[tuna]] can result in<br />them being replaced by low trophic organisms, like [[jellyfish]]}}]]\n{{see also|Overfishing|Environmental impact of fishing}}\n\n[[Overfishing]] is occurring in one third of world fish stocks, according to a 2018 report by the [[Food and Agriculture Organization]] of the United Nations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fao.org/state-of-fisheries-aquaculture/en/|title=SOFIA 2018 - State of Fisheries and Aquaculture in the world 2018|last=fao.org|work=www.fao.org|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> In addition, industry observers believe [[illegal, unreported and unregulated fishing]] occurs in most fisheries, and accounts for up to 30% of total catches in some important fisheries.<ref>World Wildlife Fund. \"[http://www.panda.org/about_wwf/what_we_do/marine/problems/problems_fishing/illegal_fishing/index.cfm Fishing problems: Illegal fishing]\" {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411060604/http://www.panda.org/about_wwf/what_we_do/marine/problems/problems_fishing/illegal_fishing/index.cfm |date=2008-04-11 }}</ref> In a phenomenon called [[fishing down the foodweb]], the [[mean trophic level]] of world fisheries has declined because of [[overfishing]] high [[trophic level]] fish.<ref>Pauly, Daniel and Watson, Reg (2009) [http://www.seaaroundus.org/researcher//dpauly/PDF/2009/Books%26Chapters/SpatialDynamicsOfFisheries.pdf \"Spatial Dynamics of Marine Fisheries\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611044204/http://www.seaaroundus.org/researcher/dpauly/PDF/2009/Books%26Chapters/SpatialDynamicsOfFisheries.pdf |date=2012-06-11 }} ''In:'' Simon A. Levin (ed.) ''The Princeton Guide to Ecology''. Pages 501\u2013509.</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n |align = left\n |width = 388px\n |title = \n |quote = \"It is almost as though we use our military to fight the animals in the ocean. We are gradually winning this war to exterminate them.\"\n |author = \u2013 [[Daniel Pauly]], pioneer on human impacts on global fisheries\n |source = <ref>{{cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tf1EgeHDxpA|title=Fisheries on the brink\n |authorlink=Daniel Pauly|last=Pauly|first=Daniel|type=YouTube video|accessdate=2012-05-01}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Habitat loss==\n[[File:Cumulative human impacts on marine ecosystems.png|thumb|upright=1.5| Relationship between annual trend and current cumulative impacts for different marine ecosystems.<ref name=Halpern2019 />]]\n\n[[Coastal ecosystem]]s are being particularly damaged by humans.<ref name=Waycott2009>Waycott, M., Duarte, C.M., Carruthers, T.J., Orth, R.J., Dennison, W.C., Olyarnik, S., Calladine, A., Fourqurean, J.W., Heck, K.L., Hughes, A.R. and Kendrick, G.A. (2009) [https://www.pnas.org/content/106/30/12377.full \"Accelerating loss of seagrasses across the globe threatens coastal ecosystems\".] ''Proceedings of the national academy of sciences'', '''106'''(30): 12377\u201312381. {{doi|10.1073/pnas.0905620106}}</ref> [[Habitat loss]] is occurring in seagrass meadows, mangrove forests, coral reefs and kelp forests, all of which are in global decline due to human disturbances.\n\n[[Coral reef]]s are among the more productive and diverse ecosystems on the planet, but one fifth of them have been lost in recent years due to anthropogenic disturbances.<ref name=Wilkinson>Wilkinson, Clive (2008) [http://www.icriforum.org/sites/default/files/Status%20Coral%20%20Reefs%20of%20World%202008%20%20Executive%20Summary_0.pdf Status of Coral Reefs of the World: Executive Summary]. Global Coral Reef Monitoring Network.</ref>  Coral reefs are [[microbial]]ly driven ecosystems that rely on [[marine microorganism]]s to retain and recycle nutrients in order to thrive in [[oligotrophic]] waters. However these same microorganisms can also trigger feedback loops that intensify declines in coral reefs, with cascading effects across [[Marine biogeochemical cycles| biogeochemical cycles]] and [[marine food web]]s. A better understanding is needed of the complex microbial interactions within coral reefs if reef conservation is to have a chance of success in the future.<ref>Vanwonterghem, I. and Webster, N.S. (2020) \"Coral reef microorganisms in a changing climate\". ''Iscience'', '''23'''(4). {{doi|10.1016/j.isci.2020.100972}}.</ref>\n\n[[Seagrass meadow]]s have lost {{convert|30000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} during recent decades. Seagrass [[ecosystem service]]s, currently worth about $US1.9 trillion per year, include [[nutrient cycling]], the provision of food and habitats for many marine animals, including the endangered [[dugong]]s, [[manatee]] and [[green turtle]]s, and major facilitations for [[coral reef fish]].<ref name=Waycott2009 />\n\nOne fifth of the world's [[mangrove forest]]s have also been lost since 1980.<ref name=\"nature.org\">{{cite web|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100717013054/http://www.nature.org/pressroom/press/press4573.html|archive-date= 2010-07-17|url=http://www.nature.org/pressroom/press/press4573.html |title= 2010a. \"\"World Atlas of Mangroves\" Highlights the Importance of and Threats to Mangroves: Mangroves among World's Most Valuable Ecosystems.\" Press release. Arlington, Virginia |publisher=The Nature Conservancy|accessdate=2014-01-25|url-status= dead}}</ref> The most pressing threat to [[kelp forest]]s may be the overfishing of coastal ecosystems, which by removing higher trophic levels facilitates their shift to depauperate [[urchin barren]]s.<ref name=\"Sala1998\">Sala, E., C.F. Bourdouresque and M. Harmelin-Vivien. 1998. Fishing, trophic cascades, and the structure of algal assemblages: evaluation of an old but untested paradigm. Oikos 82: 425-439.</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Invasive species==\n[[File:Ship pumping ballast water.jpg|thumb|A cargo ship pumps ballast water over the side.]]\n\nAn [[invasive species]] is a species not native to a particular location which can spread to a degree that causes damage to the environment, human economy or human health.<ref>{{Citation|title=Ecosystem Consequences of Biological Invasions |author=Joan G. Ehrenfeld |journal=Annual Review of Ecology, Evolution, and Systematics |year=2010 |volume=41 |pages=59\u201380 |doi=10.1146/annurev-ecolsys-102209-144650 }}</ref> In 2008, Molnar et&nbsp;al. documented the pathways of hundreds of marine invasive species and found shipping was the dominant mechanism for the transfer of invasive species in the ocean. The two main maritime mechanisms of transporting marine organisms to other ocean environments are via [[hull fouling]] and the transfer of [[ballast water]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Molnar|first=Jennifer L|last2=Gamboa|first2=Rebecca L|last3=Revenga|first3=Carmen|last4=Spalding|first4=Mark D|date=2008|title=Assessing the global threat of invasive species to marine biodiversity|journal=Frontiers in Ecology and the Environment|volume=6|issue=9|pages=485\u2013492|doi=10.1890/070064|issn=1540-9295}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Comb jelly.tif|thumb|left| {{center|''Mnemiopsis leidyi''}}]]\n\n[[Ballast water]] taken up at sea and released in port is a major source of unwanted exotic marine life. The [[invasive species|invasive]] freshwater zebra mussels, native to the Black, Caspian, and Azov seas, were probably transported to the Great Lakes via ballast water from a transoceanic vessel.<ref>[http://www.wsg.washington.edu/mas/pdfs/leastwanted.pdf Aquatic invasive species. A Guide to Least-Wanted Aquatic Organisms of the Pacific Northwest] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725040002/http://www.wsg.washington.edu/mas/pdfs/leastwanted.pdf |date=25 July 2008}}. 2001. University of Washington</ref> Meinesz believes that one of the worst cases of a single invasive species causing harm to an ecosystem can be attributed to a seemingly harmless [[jellyfish]]. ''[[Mnemiopsis leidyi]]'', a species of comb jellyfish that spread so it now inhabits estuaries in many parts of the world, was first introduced in 1982, and thought to have been transported to the [[Black Sea]] in a ship's ballast water. The population of the jellyfish grew exponentially and, by 1988, it was wreaking havoc upon the local [[fishing industry]]. \"The [[anchovy]] catch fell from 204,000 tons in 1984 to 200 tons in 1993; [[sprat]] from 24,600 tons in 1984 to 12,000 tons in 1993; horse [[mackerel]] from 4,000 tons in 1984 to zero in 1993.\"<ref name=\"Meinesz\">Meinesz, A. (2003) [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/algae/impact.html Deep Sea Invasion: The Impact of Invasive Species] PBS: NOVA. Retrieved 26 November 2009</ref> Now that the jellyfish have exhausted the [[zooplankton]], including fish larvae, their numbers have fallen dramatically, yet they continue to maintain a stranglehold on the [[ecosystem]].\n\n[[Invasive species]] can take over once occupied areas, facilitate the spread of new diseases, introduce new [[genetics|genetic]] material, alter underwater seascapes, and jeopardize the ability of [[native species]] to obtain food. Invasive species are responsible for about $138&nbsp;billion annually in lost revenue and management costs in the US alone.<ref name=pimental>{{cite journal |doi= 10.1016/j.ecolecon.2004.10.002 |title= Update on the environmental and economic costs associated with alien-invasive species in the United States |journal= Ecological Economics |volume= 52 |issue= 3 |pages= 273\u2013288 |year= 2005 |last1= Pimentel |first1= D. |last2= Zuniga |first2= R. |last3= Morrison |first3= D.}}</ref>\n\n==Marine pollution==\n[[Marine pollution]] results from the entry into the ocean of [[industrial waste|industrial]], [[Agricultural pollution|agricultural]], and [[municipal solid waste|residential]] [[wastes]].<ref>{{cite web |title= What is the biggest source of pollution in the ocean?|url= http://oceanservice.noaa.gov/facts/pollution.html|website= oceanservice.noaa.gov|accessdate= 2015-11-22|author= US Department of Commerce, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref> Pathways for this pollution include agricultural [[surface runoff|runoff]] into rivers and wind-blown [[debris]] and dust. The [[Asian brown cloud]], a layer of air pollution that covers much of South Asia and the Indian Ocean for several months every year, also hangs over the Bay of Bengal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/NaturalHazards/shownh.php3?img_id=13341 |title=EO Natural Hazards: Smog over the Bay of Bengal |website=NASA Earth Observatory |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026204458/http://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/NaturalHazards/shownh.php3?img_id=13341 |archive-date=26 October 2007 |access-date=21 January 2007}}</ref> Because of this cloud, satellites attempting to track ocean acidification and other ocean health indicators in the Bay have difficulty obtaining accurate measurements.<ref>[https://www.firstpost.com/tech/science/ocean-acidification-in-bay-of-bengal-is-now-being-monitored-by-global-satellite-network-7787131.html Ocean acidification in Bay of Bengal is now being monitored] ''[[Firstpost]]'', 16 December 2019.</ref>\n\n===Nutrient pollution===\n[[Nutrient pollution]] is a primary cause of [[eutrophication]] of surface waters, in which excess nutrients, usually [[nitrate]]s or [[phosphate]]s, stimulate algae growth.\n\n===Toxic chemicals===\n{{see also|xenobiotic}}\n\nToxic chemicals can adhere to tiny particles which are then taken up by [[plankton]] and [[benthos|benthic animals]], most of which are either [[deposit feeder]]s or [[filter feeder]]s. In this way, toxins are [[biomagnification|concentrated upward]] within ocean [[food chain]]s. Many particles combine chemically in a manner which depletes oxygen, causing [[estuary|estuaries]] to become [[hypoxia (environmental)|anoxic]]. [[Pesticide]]s and [[toxic metal]]s are similarly incorporated into marine food webs, harming the biological health of marine life. Many [[compound feed|animal feeds]] have a high [[fish meal]] or [[fish hydrolysate]] content. In this way, marine toxins are transferred back to farmed land animals, and then to humans.\n\n[[Phytoplankton]] concentrations have increased over the last century in coastal waters, and more recently have declined in the open ocean. Increases in nutrient runoff from land may explain the increases in coastal phytoplankton, while warming surface temperatures in the open ocean may have strengthened stratification in the water column, reducing the flow of nutrients from the deep that open ocean phytoplankton find useful.<ref>Boyce, D.G. and [[Boris Worm|Worm, B.]] (2015) \"Patterns and ecological implications of historical marine phytoplankton change\". ''Marine Ecology Progress Series'', '''534''':251\u2013272. {{doi|10.3354/meps11411}}</ref>\n\n===Plastic pollution===\n<!--In 2015, between 93 and 236 thousand metric tons of [[Plastic pollution|plastic]] were estimated to be in the world\u2019s oceans.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1088/1748-9326/10/12/124006 |title=A global inventory of small floating plastic debris |journal=Environmental Research Letters |volume=10 |issue=12 |pages=124006 |year=2015 |last1=Van Sebille |first1=Erik |last2=Wilcox |first2=Chris |last3=Lebreton |first3=Laurent |last4=Maximenko |first4=Nikolai |last5=Hardesty |first5=Britta Denise |last6=Van Franeker |first6=Jan A. |last7=Eriksen |first7=Marcus |last8=Siegel |first8=David |last9=Galgani |first9=Francois |last10=Law |first10=Kara Lavender }}</ref> --> \nEstimates suggest something like 9 million tonnes of plastic is added to the ocean every year. This plastic may need 450 years or more to biograde. Once in the ocean, plastics are shredded by marine [[amphipod]]s into [[microplastics]]. There are now beaches where 15 percent of the sand are grains of microplastic. In the oceans themselves, microplastics float in surface waters amongst the plankton where they are ingested by plankton eaters.<ref>Parker, Laura (2018) [https://www.nationalgeographic.com/magazine/2018/06/plastic-planet-waste-pollution-trash-crisis/ \"We made plastic. We depend on it. Now we're drowning in it\".] ''National Geographic''.</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=180px style=float:left;>\nFile:Microplastics in sediment from the Rhine.jpg| Microplastics among sand and glass spheres in sediment from the [[Rhine]]. The white bar represents 1&nbsp;mm.\nFile:Pacific-garbage-patch-map 2010 noaamdp.jpg| Vast [[Great Pacific garbage patch|plastic garbage patches]] have accumulated at the centre of [[ocean gyre]]s.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://marinedebris.noaa.gov/movement/great-pacific-garbage-patch |title=Great Pacific Garbage Patch |website= Marine Debris Division \u2013 Office of Response and Restoration |publisher=NOAA |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140417124654/https://marinedebris.noaa.gov/movement/great-pacific-garbage-patch |archivedate=17 April 2014 |df=dmy-all|date=2013-07-11 }}</ref>\nFile:Ocean plasic count density.gif| Model results for the count density of small planktonic plastic particles.<ref>Eriksen, M., Lebreton, L.C., Carson, H.S., Thiel, M., Moore, C.J., Borerro, J.C., Galgani, F., Ryan, P.G. and Reisser, J. (2014) [http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0111913 \"Plastic pollution in the world's oceans: more than 5 trillion plastic pieces weighing over 250,000 tons afloat at sea\"]. ''PLOS ONE'', '''9''' (12): e111913. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0111913.g002}}</ref><br /> Red: more dense &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Green: less dense\n</gallery>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Noise pollution===\n{{See also|Marine pollution#Underwater noise|Marine mammals and sonar}}\n\nUnderwater noise pollution due to human activities is also prevalent in the sea.<ref name=Williams2015>Williams, R., Wright, A.J., Ashe, E., Blight, L.K., Bruintjes, R., Canessa, R., Clark, C.W., Cullis-Suzuki, S., Dakin, D.T., Erbe, C. and Hammond, P.S. (2015) [https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S096456911500160X \"Impacts of anthropogenic noise on marine life: Publication patterns, new discoveries, and future directions in research and management\".] ''Ocean & Coastal Management'', '''115''': 17\u201324. {{doi|10.1016/j.ocecoaman.2015.05.021}}</ref> Cargo ships generate high levels of noise due to propellers and diesel engines.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Radiated noise characteristics of a modern cargo ship|journal=The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America |volume=107| issue=1| pages=118\u2013129 |doi=10.1121/1.428344 |pmid=10641625 |year=2000 | last1=Arveson | first1=Paul T|last2=Vendittis |first2=David J |bibcode=2000ASAJ..107..118A }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Measurements of radiated underwater noise from modern merchant ships relevant to noise impacts on marine mammals |journal=The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America | volume=129 |issue=4 |page=2368| doi=10.1121/1.3587665 | year=2011 | last1=McKenna | first1=Megan F | last2=Ross | first2=Donald| last3=Wiggins |first3=Sean M |last4=Hildebrand |first4=John A |bibcode=2011ASAJ..129.2368M }}</ref> This noise pollution significantly raises the low-frequency ambient noise levels above those caused by wind.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Acoustic Ambient Noise in the Ocean: Spectra and Sources|journal=The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America |volume=34 |issue=12 |pages=1936\u20131956 |doi=10.1121/1.1909155 |year=1962 |last=Wenz |first= Gordon M |bibcode=1962ASAJ...34.1936W }}</ref> Animals such as whales that depend on sound for communication can be affected adversely.  Even marine invertebrates, such as crabs (''[[Carcinus maenas]]''), have been shown to be negatively affected by ship noise.<ref name=DeepSNcrabs>{{cite web |author=McClain, Craig |title=Loud Noise Makes Crabs Even More Crabby |publisher=Deep Sea News |url=http://deepseanews.com/2013/04/load-noise-makes-crabs-edgy/ |accessdate=2013-04-04 |date=2013-04-03 }}</ref><ref name=\"WaleSimpson2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Wale|first1=M. A.|last2=Simpson|first2=S. D.|last3=Radford|first3=A. N.|title=Size-dependent physiological responses of shore crabs to single and repeated playback of ship noise|journal=Biology Letters|volume=9|issue=2|year=2013|pages=20121194|issn=1744-9561|doi=10.1098/rsbl.2012.1194|pmid=23445945|pmc=3639773}}</ref>\n\n==Ocean acidification==\n[[File:WOA05 GLODAP del pH AYool.png|thumb|right|upright=1.5| Estimated change in sea water [[pH]] caused by human created [[carbon dioxide|{{chem|CO|2}}]] from the start of the industrial revolution to the end of the twentieth century]]\n{{see also|Ocean acidification#Possible impacts}}\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | image1    = Coccolithus pelagicus.jpg\n | width1    = 168\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = {{center|[[Coccolithophore]]}}\n | image2    = Red sea urchin 3.jpg\n | width2    = 182\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = {{center|[[Sea urchin]]}}\n | footer            = Increases in acidity makes it difficult for microorganisms like coccolithophores, and [[shellfish]] like sea urchins, to build their carbonate shells\n | footer_align      = center\n}}\n\n[[Ocean acidification]] is the increasing acidification of the oceans, caused mainly by the uptake of [[carbon dioxide]] from the [[Earth's atmosphere|atmosphere]].<ref name=\"cald03\">{{Cite journal |last=Caldeira |first=K. |author2=Wickett, M. E. |year=2003 |title=Anthropogenic carbon and ocean pH |journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |volume=425 |issue=6956 |pages=365 |doi=10.1038/425365a |pmid=14508477 |bibcode=2001AGUFMOS11C0385C |ref=harv|url= https://zenodo.org/record/1233227}}</ref> The rise in atmospheric carbon dioxide due to the burning of fossil fuels leads to more  carbon dioxide dissolving in the ocean. When carbon dioxide dissolves in water it forms hydrogen and carbonate ions. This in turn increases the [[ocean acidification|acidity of the ocean]] and makes survival increasingly harder for microorganisms, shellfish and other marine organisms that depend on [[calcium carbonate]] to form their shells.<ref>{{harv|Trujillo|Thurman|2008|p=151}}{{full citation needed|date=December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIncreasing acidity also has potential for other harm to marine organisms, such as depressing metabolic rates and immune responses in some organisms, and causing [[coral bleaching]].<ref name=\"bleaching\">{{cite journal |first=KRN |last=Anthony |display-authors=et al |title=Ocean acidification causes bleaching and productivity loss in coral reef builders |journal= Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |year=2008 |pages=17442\u201317446 |doi=10.1073/pnas.0804478105 |pmid=18988740 |volume=105 |issue=45 |bibcode=2008PNAS..10517442A |pmc=2580748}}</ref> Ocean acidification has increased 26% since the beginning of the industrial era.<ref>IPCC (2019) Summary for Policymakers. In: [https://report.ipcc.ch/srocc/pdf/SROCC_FinalDraft_FullReport.pdf ''IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate''], Chapter 1, page 14. [H.O. P\u00f6rtner, D.C. Roberts, V. Masson-Delmotte, P. Zhai, M. Tignor, E. Poloczanska, K. Mintenbeck, M. Nicolai, A. Okem, J. Petzold, B. Rama, N. Weyer (eds.)]. Final draft: 24 September 2019.</ref> It has been compared to [[anthropogenic climate change]] and called the \"evil twin of [[global warming]]\"<ref name=\"HPost\">{{cite web |work=[[Huffington Post]] |date=9 July 2012 |title=Ocean Acidification Is Climate Change's 'Equally Evil Twin,' NOAA Chief Says |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/09/ocean-acidification-reefs-climate-change_n_1658081.html |accessdate=2012-07-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120712003629/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/09/ocean-acidification-reefs-climate-change_n_1658081.html |archivedate=12 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and \"the other {{CO2}} problem\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Doney|first=S.C.|last2=Fabry|first2=V.J.|last3=Feely|first3=R.A.|last4=Kleypas|first4=J.A.|year=2009|title=Ocean Acidification: The Other {{CO2}} Problem|journal=Annual Review of Marine Science|volume=1 |issue= |pages=169\u2013192 |pmid= 21141034 |bibcode= 2009ARMS....1..169D| url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/3df7/eebe38b6c8cbc6e4bca5035a339d832a570c.pdf?_ga=2.224706074.1056012774.1577577758-308431455.1577577758|doi= 10.1146/annurev.marine.010908.163834}}</ref>\n\nAragonite is a form of calcium carbonate many marine animals use to build carbonate skeletons and shells. The lower the aragonite [[Ocean acidification#Saturation state|saturation level]], the more difficult it is for the organisms to build and maintain their skeletons and shells. The map below shows changes in the aragonite saturation level of ocean surface waters between 1880 and 2012.<ref>{{cite web| title=Changes in Aragonite Saturation of the World's Oceans, 1880\u20132015| url=https://www.epa.gov/climate-indicators/climate-change-indicators-ocean-acidity|author=Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution| date=August 2016| website= }}<br />{{cite journal|last=Feely|first=R.A.|first2=S.C.|last2=Doney|first3=S.R.|last3=Cooley|year=2009|title=Ocean acidification: Present conditions and future changes in a high-{{CO2}} world|url=https://darchive.mblwhoilibrary.org/bitstream/handle/1912/3180/22-4_feely.pdf?sequence=1|work=Oceanography|volume=22|issue=4|pages=36\u201347|doi=10.5670/oceanog.2009.95|hdl=1912/3180|via=Woods Hole Open Access Server}}<br />{{cite web| title=Climate Change Indicators in the United States, 2012, 2nd ed: Ocean Acidity: Figure 2. Changes in Aragonite Saturation of the World's Oceans, 1880-2012  | publisher=US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) | url=http://www.epa.gov/climatechange/science/indicators/oceans/acidity.html#fragment-2 }}</ref>\n\nTo pick one example, [[pteropod]]s are a group of widely distributed swimming [[sea snail]]s. For pteropods to create shells they require [[aragonite]] which is produced through carbonate ions and dissolved calcium. Pteropods are severely affected because increasing acidification levels have steadily decreased the amount of water supersaturated with carbonate which is needed for the aragonite creation.<ref name=\"biogeosciences\">{{cite web | url=http://www.biogeosciences.net/8/919/2011/bg-8-919-2011.pdf | title=Impact of ocean acidification and elevated temperatures on early juveniles of the polar shelled pteropod Limacina helicina : mortality, shell degradation, and shell growth | publisher=Biogeosciences | work=Report |date=15 April 2011 | accessdate=14 November 2013 |author1=Lischka, S. |author2=B\u00fcdenbender J. |author3=Boxhammer T. |author4=Riebesell U. | pages=919\u2013932}}</ref>\n\nWhen the shell of a pteropod was immersed in water with a pH level the ocean is projected to reach by the year 2100, the shell almost completely dissolved within six weeks.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Limacina helicina shell dissolution as an indicator of declining habitat suitability owing to ocean acidification in the California Current Ecosystem|journal = Proc. R. Soc. B|date = 2014|issn = 0962-8452|pmc = 4024287|pmid = 24789895|pages = 20140123|volume = 281|issue = 1785|doi = 10.1098/rspb.2014.0123|first = N.|last = Bednar\u0161ek|first2 = R. A.|last2 = Feely|first3 = J. C. P.|last3 = Reum|first4 = B.|last4 = Peterson|first5 = J.|last5 = Menkel|first6 = S. R.|last6 = Alin|first7 = B.|last7 = Hales}}</ref> Likewise [[coral]]s,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=D'Olivo|first=Juan P.|last2=Ellwood|first2=George|last3=DeCarlo|first3=Thomas M.|last4=McCulloch|first4=Malcolm T.|date=2019-11-15|title=Deconvolving the long-term impacts of ocean acidification and warming on coral biomineralisation|journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters|volume=526|pages=115785|doi=10.1016/j.epsl.2019.115785|issn=0012-821X|doi-access=free}}</ref> [[coralline algae]],<ref name=\"kuffner\">{{Cite journal | last=Kuffner | first=I. B. |author2=Andersson, A. J.|author3=Jokiel, P. L.|author4=Rodgers, K. S. |author5=Mackenzie, F. T. | year=2007 | title=Decreased abundance of crustose coralline algae due to ocean acidification | journal=[[Nature Geoscience]] | volume=1 |issue=2 |pages=114\u2013117 |doi=10.1038/ngeo100 |bibcode=2008NatGe...1..114K | ref=harv| url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/7e00dfd0d003c947045bf58aef07c024adc409e6 }}</ref> coccolithophores,<ref name=\"delille05\">{{Cite journal | last=Delille | first=B.|author2=Harlay, J.|author3=Zondervan, I.|author4= Jacquet, S.|author5=Chou, L.|author6=Wollast, R.|author7=Bellerby, R.G.J.|author8= Frankignoulle, M.|author9=Borges, A.V.|author10=Riebesell, U. |author11=Gattuso, J.-P. | year=2005 | title=Response of primary production and calcification to changes of p{{co2}} during experimental blooms of the coccolithophorid ''Emiliania huxleyi'' | url=http://www.obs-vlfr.fr/~gattuso/jpg_papers_list.php | journal=Global Biogeochemical Cycles | volume=19 |doi=10.1029/2004GB002318 | pages=GB2023 | bibcode=2005GBioC..19.2023D | issue=2 | ref=harv}}</ref> [[foraminifera]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Phillips |first=Graham |author2=Chris Branagan |title=Ocean Acidification \u2013 The BIG global warming story |date=2007 |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |url=http://www.abc.net.au/catalyst/stories/s2029333.htm |work =ABC TV Science: Catalyst |accessdate=2007-09-18  }}</ref> as well as [[shellfish]] generally,<ref name=\"gaz07\">{{Cite journal |last=Gazeau |first=F. |author2=Quiblier, C. |author3=Jansen, J. M. |author4=Gattuso, J.-P. |author5= Middelburg, J. J. |author6=Heip, C. H. R. |year=2007 |title=Impact of elevated {{chem|CO|2}} on shellfish calcification |url=http://www.obs-vlfr.fr/~gattuso/jpg_papers_list.php |journal=[[Geophysical Research Letters]] |volume=34 |issue=7 |pages=L07603 |doi=10.1029/2006GL028554 |bibcode=2007GeoRL..3407603G |ref=harv|hdl=20.500.11755/a8941c6a-6d0b-43d5-ba0d-157a7aa05668 }}</ref> all experience reduced calcification or enhanced dissolution as an effect of ocean acidification.\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=170px style=\"float:left;\">\nFile:Changes in aragonite saturation of the world's oceans, 1880-2012 (US EPA).png|{{center|Decreases in aragonite saturation make it more difficult for marine organisms like pteropods to build [[Seashell|calcium shells]]}}\nFile:Effect of Ocean Acidification on Calcification.svg|Shells of pteropods dissolve in increasingly acidic conditions caused by increased amounts of atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub>\n</gallery>\n\n[[File:Impacts of ocean acidification (NOAA EVL).webm|thumb|355px| Video summarizing impacts of ocean acidification \u2013 Source: [[NOAA]]]]\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | image1    = Fis01026 (27555118153).jpg\n | width1    = 170\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = {{center|Unhealthy pteropod showing effects of ocean acidification}}\n | image2    = FMIB 52630 Ophiopholis aculeata.jpeg\n | width2    = 230\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = {{center|Ocean acidification causes brittle stars to lose muscle mass}}\n | footer            = &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; [[Pteropod]]s and [[brittle star]]s form the base of Arctic food webs\n | footer_align      = center\n}}\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n[[Pteropoda|Pteropods]] and [[brittle star]]s together form the base of the Arctic [[food web]]s and both are seriously damaged by acidification. Pteropods shells dissolve with increasing acidification and brittle stars lose muscle mass when re-growing appendages.<ref>{{cite web|title=Effects of Ocean Acidification on Marine Species & Ecosystems|url=http://oceana.org/en/our-work/climate-energy/ocean-acidification/learn-act/effects-of-ocean-acidification-on-marine-species-ecosystems|work=Report|publisher=OCEANA|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> Additionally the brittle star's eggs die within a few days when exposed to expected conditions resulting from Arctic acidification.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cicero.uio.no/webnews/index_e.aspx?id=11909 | title=Comprehensive study of Arctic Ocean acidification | publisher=CICERO | work=Study | accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref> Acidification threatens to destroy Arctic food webs from the base up. Arctic waters are changing rapidly and are advanced in the process of becoming undersaturated with aragonite.<ref name=\"biogeosciences\" /> Arctic food webs are considered simple, meaning there are few steps in the food chain from small organisms to larger predators. For example, pteropods are \"a key prey item of a number of higher predators \u2013 larger plankton, fish, seabirds, whales\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Antarctic marine wildlife is under threat, study finds|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/20461646|publisher=BBC Nature|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Silicates==\nThe rise in agriculture of the past 400 years has increased the exposure rocks and soils, which has resulted in increased rates of silicate weathering. In turn, the leaching of [[Amorphous solid|amorphous]] silica stocks from soils has also increased, delivering higher concentrations of dissolved silica in rivers.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite journal|last=Gaillardet |first=J.|last2=Dupr\u00e9|first2=B. |last3=Louvat |first3=P.|last4=All\u00e8gre |first4=C.J. |date=July 1999 |title=Global silicate weathering and CO2 consumption rates deduced from the chemistry of large rivers|journal=Chemical Geology|volume=159|issue=1\u20134|pages=3\u201330|doi=10.1016/s0009-2541(99)00031-5|issn=0009-2541|bibcode=1999ChGeo.159....3G}}</ref> Conversely, increased damming has led to a reduction in silica supply to the ocean due to uptake by freshwater diatoms behind dams. The dominance of non-siliceous [[phytoplankton]] due to anthropogenic nitrogen and phosphorus loading and enhanced silica [[dissolution (chemistry)|dissolution]] in warmer waters has the potential to limit silicon ocean sediment export in the future.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn 2019 a group of scientists suggested acidification is reducing [[diatom]] silica production in the [[Southern Ocean]].<ref>[https://phys.org/news/2019-08-threat-ocean-acidification-emerges-southern.html New threat from ocean acidification emerges in the Southern Ocean], ''Phys.org'', 26 August 2019.</ref><ref>Petrou, K., Baker, K.G., Nielsen, D.A. et&nbsp;al.  (2019) \"Acidification diminishes diatom silica production in the Southern Ocean\". ''Nature: Climate Change'', '''9''': 781\u2013786. {{doi|10.1038/s41558-019-0557-y}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 170\n | footer            = Changes in [[Orthosilicic acid#Oceanic silicic acid|ocean silicic acid]] can make it difficult for the [[marine microorganism]]s that construct silica shells\n | footer_align      = center\n | footer_background = \n | background color  = \n | image1    = Stephanopyxis grunowii.jpg\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = {{center|[[Diatom]]}}\n | image2    = Calocycloma sp. - Radiolarian (32163186535).jpg\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = {{center|[[Radiolarian]]}}\n}}\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=190px style=\"float:right;\">\nFile:WOA09 sea-surf H4SIO4 AYool.png| Concentration of [[silicic acid]] in the upper [[pelagic zone]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nodc.noaa.gov/OC5/WOA09/pr_woa09.html|title=World Ocean Atlas 2009|first=US Department of Commerce, NOAA National Centers for Environmental|last=Information|date=|website=www.nodc.noaa.gov|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref> showing high levels in the Southern Ocean\nFile:Marine Silica Cycle.png| Generalized [[Silica cycle#Marine silica cycling|marine silica cycle]], adapted from [[:fr:Paul Tr\u00e9guer|Treguer]] et&nbsp;al., 1995<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tr\u00e9guer|first=Paul|last2=Nelson|first2=David M.|last3=Bennekom|first3=Aleido J. Van|last4=DeMaster|first4=David J.|last5=Leynaert|first5=Aude|last6=Qu\u00e9guiner|first6=Bernard|date=1995-04-21|title=The Silica Balance in the World Ocean: A Reestimate|journal=Science|language=en|volume=268|issue=5209|pages=375\u2013379|doi=10.1126/science.268.5209.375|issn=0036-8075|pmid=17746543|bibcode=1995Sci...268..375T}}</ref>\n</gallery>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Nitrogen\u2013carbon interactions==\n[[File:Nitrogen\u2013carbon\u2013climate interactions.jpg|thumb|upright=2| Nitrogen\u2013carbon\u2013climate interactions. Shown are the main interacting drivers during the Anthropocene. Signs indicate an increase (+) or a decrease (\u2212) in the factor shown; (?) indicate an unknown impact. Colors of the arrow indicate direct anthropogenic impacts (red) or natural interactions (blue, many of which also modified by human influence). Strength of the interaction is expressed by the arrow thickness.<ref>Cardini, U., Bednarz, V.N., Foster, R.A. and Wild, C. (2014) \"Benthic N2 fixation in coral reefs and the potential effects of human\u2010induced environmental change\". ''Ecology and evolution'', '''4'''(9): 1706\u20131727. {{doi|10.1002/ece3.1050}} [[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License].</ref><ref>Adapted from: Gruber, N., and J. N. Galloway (2008) \"An Earth\u2010system perspective of the global nitrogen cycle\". ''Nature'', 451:293\u2013296. {{doi|10.1038/nature06592}}.</ref>]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Ocean warming==\n[[File:Global Temperature Anomaly 1880-2010 (Fig.A).gif|thumb|upright=1.5| {{center|Global mean land-ocean temperature change from 1880 to 2011, relative to the 1951\u20131980 mean.<br />Source: [http://data.giss.nasa.gov/gistemp/ NASA GISS]}}]]\n{{see also|Effects of global warming on oceans|Ocean heat content}}\n\nMost heat energy from global warming goes into the ocean, and not into the atmosphere or warming up the land.<ref name=IPCC2007 /><ref name=ss /> Scientists realized over 30 years ago the ocean was a key fingerprint of human impact on [[climate change]] and \"the best opportunity for major improvement in our understanding of climate sensitivity is probably monitoring of internal ocean temperature\".<ref>Hansen, J., Fung, I., Lacis, A., Rind, D., Lebedeff, S., Ruedy, R., Russell, G. and Stone, P. (1988) \"Global climate changes as forecast by Goddard Institute for Space Studies three\u2010dimensional model\". ''Journal of geophysical research: Atmospheres'', '''93'''(D8): 9341\u20139364. {{doi|10.1029/JD093iD08p09341}}</ref>\n\nMarine organisms are moving to cooler parts of the ocean as global warming proceeds. For example, a group of 105 marine fish and invertebrate species were monitored along the US Northeast coast and in the eastern Bering Sea. During the period from 1982 to 2015, the average center of biomass for the group shifted northward about 10 miles as well moving about 20 feet deeper.<ref>Data source: NOAA and Rutgers University (2016) [https://oceanadapt.rutgers.edu/ ''OceanAdapt'']</ref><ref name=Pinsky2013>Pinsky, M.L., Worm, B., Fogarty, M.J., Sarmiento, J.L. and Levin, S.A. (2013) \"Marine taxa track local climate velocities\". ''Science'', '''341'''(6151): 1239\u20131242. {{doi|10.1126/science.1239352}}</ref>\n\n[[File:WhereIsTheHeatOfGlobalWarming.jpg|left|thumb| {{center|Most heat energy from global warming goes into the ocean <ref name=IPCC2007>IPCC (2007) [https://archive.ipcc.ch/publications_and_data/ar4/wg1/en/ch5s5-2-2.html Ocean Heat Content] Fourth Assessment Report.</ref>}}]]\n[[File:GlobalWarmingOceanHeatContent.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5| Global heat accumulation data, from Nuccitelli et al. (2012) <ref>Nuccitelli, D., Way, R., Painting, R., Church, J. and Cook, J. (2012) [https://skepticalscience.com/docs/Comment_on_DK12.pdf \"Comment on 'Ocean heat content and Earth\u02bcs radiation imbalance. II. Relation to climate shifts'\"]. ''Physics Letters A'', '''376'''(45): 3466\u20133468. {{doi|10.1016/j.physleta.2012.10.010}}</ref><ref name=ss>[https://skepticalscience.com/graphics.php?g=65 Nuccitelli et al 2012 Total Heat Content] ''Skeptical Science''. Accessed 30 December 2019.</ref>]]\n\nThere is evidence increasing ocean temperatures are taking a toll on marine ecosystem. For example, a study on [[phytoplankton]] changes in the [[Indian Ocean]] indicates a decline of up to 20% in marine phytoplankton during the past six decades.<ref name=\"onlinelibrary.wiley.com\">{{cite journal |last1=Roxy |first1=M.K. |title=A reduction in marine primary productivity driven by rapid warming over the tropical Indian Ocean | year = 2016 | journal = Geophysical Research Letters | volume = 43 | issue = 2 |pages=826\u2013833 | ref = {{Harvid|Roxy|2016}} | doi=10.1002/2015GL066979|bibcode=2016GeoRL..43..826R |url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01259414/file/Roxy_2016_A_reduction_in.pdf }}</ref> During summer, the western Indian Ocean is home to one of the largest concentrations of marine phytoplankton blooms in the world. Increased warming in the Indian Ocean enhances ocean stratification, which prevents nutrient mixing in the [[euphotic zone]] where ample light is available for photosynthesis. Thus, primary production is constrained and the region's entire food web is disrupted. If rapid warming continues, the Indian Ocean could transform into an ecological desert and cease being productive.<ref name=\"onlinelibrary.wiley.com\"/>\n\n{{clear right}}\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=130px style=\"float:right;\">\nFile:Antarctic krill (Euphausia superba).jpg| Ocean warming is changing the distribution of the keystone species [[Antarctic krill]] <ref name=pewtrusts2019 /><ref name=Rogers2019 />\nFile:Trematomus bernacchii.jpg| In the Antarctic, limited-range shallow-water species, like this [[emerald rockcod]], are under threat.<ref name=pewtrusts2019>[https://www.pewtrusts.org/en/research-and-analysis/articles/2019/10/25/climate-change-could-threaten-many-antarctic-marine-species Climate Change Could Threaten Many Antarctic Marine Species] ''Pew'', 25 October 2019.</ref><ref name=Rogers2019>Rogers, A.D., Frinault, B.A.V., Barnes, D.K.A., Bindoff, N.L., Downie, R., Ducklow, H.W., Friedlaender, A.S., Hart, T., Hill, S.L., Hofmann, E.E. and Linse, K. (2019) \"Antarctic futures: an assessment of climate-driven changes in ecosystem structure, function, and service provisioning in the Southern Ocean\". ''Annual review of marine science'', '''12''': 87\u2013120. {{doi|10.1146/annurev-marine-010419-011028}}</ref>\n</gallery>\n\nThe [[Antarctic oscillation]] (also called the ''Southern Annular Mode'') is a belt of [[Westerlies|westerly winds]] or low pressure surrounding [[Antarctica]] which moves north or south according to which phase it is in.<ref>Australian Bureau of Meteorology - The Southern Annular Mode. Accessed 25/10/2013. http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/enso/history/ln-2010-12/SAM-what.shtml</ref> In its positive phase, the westerly wind belt that drives the [[Antarctic Circumpolar Current]] intensifies and contracts towards [[Antarctica]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Thompson|first=David W. J.|last2=Solomon|first2=Susan|last3=Kushner|first3=Paul J.|last4=England|first4=Matthew H.|last5=Grise|first5=Kevin M.|last6=Karoly|first6=David J.|date=2011-10-23|title=Signatures of the Antarctic ozone hole in Southern Hemisphere surface climate change|journal=Nature Geoscience|language=En|volume=4|issue=11|pages=741\u2013749|doi=10.1038/ngeo1296|issn=1752-0894}}</ref> while its negative phase the belt moves towards the Equator. Winds associated with the Antarctic oscillation cause oceanic [[upwelling]] of warm circumpolar deep water along the Antarctic continental shelf.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hayakawa|first=Hideaki|last2=Shibuya|first2=Kazuo|last3=Aoyama|first3=Yuichi|last4=Nogi|first4=Yoshifumi|last5=Doi|first5=Koichiro|date=2012|title=Ocean bottom pressure variability in the Antarctic Divergence Zone off L\u00fctzow-Holm Bay, East Antarctica|journal=Deep Sea Research Part I: Oceanographic Research Papers|volume=60|pages=22\u201331|doi=10.1016/j.dsr.2011.09.005|issn=0967-0637}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Spence|first=Paul|last2=Griffies|first2=Stephen M.|last3=England|first3=Matthew H.|last4=Hogg|first4=Andrew McC.|last5=Saenko|first5=Oleg A.|last6=Jourdain|first6=Nicolas C.|date=2014-07-12|title=Rapid subsurface warming and circulation changes of Antarctic coastal waters by poleward shifting winds|journal=Geophysical Research Letters|language=en|volume=41|issue=13|pages=4601\u20134610|doi=10.1002/2014gl060613|issn=0094-8276|url=https://openresearch-repository.anu.edu.au/bitstream/1885/56321/2/01_Spence_Rapid_subsurface_warming_and_2014.pdf|hdl=1885/56321}}</ref> This has been linked to [[ice shelf]] [[basal melt]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Greene|first=Chad A.|last2=Blankenship|first2=Donald D.|last3=Gwyther|first3=David E.|last4=Silvano|first4=Alessandro|last5=Wijk|first5=Esmee van|date=2017-11-01|title=Wind causes Totten Ice Shelf melt and acceleration|journal=Science Advances|language=en|volume=3|issue=11|pages=e1701681|doi=10.1126/sciadv.1701681|pmid=29109976|issn=2375-2548|pmc=5665591}}</ref> representing a possible wind-driven mechanism that could destabilize large portions of the Antarctic Ice Sheet.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Anderson|first=R. F.|last2=Ali|first2=S.|last3=Bradtmiller|first3=L. I.|last4=Nielsen|first4=S. H. H.|last5=Fleisher|first5=M. Q.|last6=Anderson|first6=B. E.|last7=Burckle|first7=L. H.|date=2009-03-13|title=Wind-Driven Upwelling in the Southern Ocean and the Deglacial Rise in Atmospheric CO2|journal=Science|language=en|volume=323|issue=5920|pages=1443\u20131448|doi=10.1126/science.1167441|issn=0036-8075|pmid=19286547}}</ref> The Antarctic oscillation is currently in the most extreme positive phase that has occurred for over a thousand years. Recently this positive phase has been further intensifying, and this has been attributed to increasing [[greenhouse gas]] levels and later stratospheric ozone depletion.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/paleo-search/study/16197|accessdate = 5 January 2020|title = 1000-year Southern Annular Mode Reconstruction|publisher = NOAA: [[National Climatic Data Center]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Abram |first=Nerilie|url=http://www.nature.com/nclimate/journal/v4/n7/full/nclimate2235.html |title=Evolution of the Southern Annular Mode during the past millennium |work=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |date=2014-05-11 |accessdate=2014-09-13 }}</ref> These large-scale alterations in the physical environment are \"driving change through all levels of Antarctic marine food webs\".<ref name=pewtrusts2019 /><ref name=Rogers2019 /> Ocean warming is also changing the distribution of [[Antarctic krill]].<ref name=pewtrusts2019 /><ref name=Rogers2019 /> Antarctic krill is the [[keystone species]] of the [[Antarctic]] ecosystem beyond the coastal shelf, and is an important food source for [[marine mammal]]s and [[Sea bird|birds]].<ref>{{cite book |editor1=Guido di Prisco |editor2=Cinzia Verde |series=Adaptation and Evolution in Marine Environments |volume=1 |title=The Impacts of Global Change on Biodiversity |publisher=Springer Science & Business Media |year=2012 |isbn=9783642273513 |chapter=Sea-ice interactions with polar fish: focus on the Antarctic silverfish life history |author=Mario Vacchi |author2=Philippe Koubbi |author3=Laura Ghigliotti |author4=Eva Pisano |pages=51\u201373<!-- at p. 63 --> |doi=10.1007/978-3-642-27352-0_4}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\nThe [[IPCC]] (2019) says marine organisms are being affected globally by ocean warming with direct impacts on human communities, fisheries, and food production.<ref>{{Cite report| series = Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate (SROCC) |title=Chapter 5: Changing Ocean, Marine Ecosystems, and Dependent Communities|work=IPCC| access-date = 25 March 2020 |date = 25 September 2019| url = https://report.ipcc.ch/srocc/pdf/SROCC_FinalDraft_Chapter5.pdf |format=PDF |pages=5\u20136}}</ref> It is likely there will be a 15% decrease in the number of marine animals and a decrease of 21% to 24% in fisheries catches by the end of the 21st century because of climate change.<ref>{{Cite web| title = 'We're All in Big Trouble': Climate Panel Sees a Dire Future |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] via the Associated Press | access-date = 25 March 2020 |date = 25 September 2019| url = https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2019/09/25/science/ap-us-sci-climate-report.html?partner=IFTTT}}</ref>\n\n==Rising sea levels==\n[[File:Sea level change 1993 to 2018.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5| Between 1993 and 2018, the mean sea level has risen across most of the world ocean (blue colors).<ref>Lindsey, Rebecca (2019) [https://www.climate.gov/news-features/understanding-climate/climate-change-global-sea-level Climate Change: Global Sea Level] ''NOAA Climate'', 19 November 2019.</ref>]]\n\nCoastal ecosystems are facing further changes because of [[rising sea level]]s. Some ecosystems can move inland with the high-water mark, but others are prevented from migrating due to natural or artificial barriers. This coastal narrowing, called [[wiktionary:coastal squeeze|coastal squeeze]] if human-made barriers are involved, can result in the [[loss of habitat]]s such as [[mudflat]]s and [[marsh]]es.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://datazone.birdlife.org/sea-level-rise-poses-a-major-threat-to-coastal-ecosystems-and-the-biota-they-support|title=Sea level rise poses a major threat to coastal ecosystems and the biota they support|date=2015|website=birdlife.org|publisher=Birdlife International}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pontee |first1=Nigel |title=Defining coastal squeeze: A discussion |journal=Ocean & Coastal Management |date=November 2013 |volume=84 |pages=204\u2013207 |doi=10.1016/j.ocecoaman.2013.07.010 }}</ref> [[Mangroves]] and [[tidal marsh]]es adjust to rising sea levels by building vertically using accumulated [[sediment]] and [[organic matter]]. If sea level rise is too rapid, they will not be able to keep up and will instead be submerged.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Krauss |first1=Ken W. |last2=McKee |first2=Karen L. |last3=Lovelock |first3=Catherine E. |last4=Cahoon |first4=Donald R. |last5=Saintilan |first5=Neil |last6=Reef |first6=Ruth |last7=Chen |first7=Luzhen |title=How mangrove forests adjust to rising sea level |journal=New Phytologist |date=April 2014 |volume=202 |issue=1 |pages=19\u201334 |doi=10.1111/nph.12605 |pmid=24251960 |url=https://digitalcommons.unl.edu/usgsstaffpub/986 }}</ref> \n\n[[File:Sea Level Change 1880 to 2015.png|thumb|left| {{center|Sea level change, 1880 to 2015 <ref>[http://www.cmar.csiro.au/sealevel/sl_data_cmar.html CSIRO 2015 update] to data originally published in: Church, J.A., and N.J. White (2011) \"Sea-level rise from the late 19th to the early 21st century\". ''Surv. Geophys.'', '''32''': 585\u2013602.</ref><ref>NOAA Laboratory for Satellite Altimetry (2016) [https://www.star.nesdis.noaa.gov/sod/lsa/SeaLevelRise/LSA_SLR_timeseries_global.php Global sea level time series]. Accessed: June 2016.</ref>}}]]\n\nCoral, important for bird and fish life, also needs to grow vertically to remain close to the sea surface in order to get enough energy from sunlight. So far it has been able to keep up, but might not be able to do so in the future.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Climate Change 2014: Impacts, Adaptation, and Vulnerability.|last=Wong|first=Poh Poh|last2=Losado|first2=I.J.|last3=Gattuso|first3=J.-P.|last4=Hinkel|first4=Jochen|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2014|isbn=|location=New York|pages=|chapter=Coastal Systems and Low-Lying Areas|chapter-url=http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/assessment-report/ar5/wg2/WGIIAR5-Chap5_FINAL.pdf}}</ref> These ecosystems protect against storm surges, waves and tsunamis. Losing them makes the effects of sea level rise worse.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Crosby |first1=Sarah C. |last2=Sax |first2=Dov F. |last3=Palmer |first3=Megan E. |last4=Booth |first4=Harriet S. |last5=Deegan |first5=Linda A. |last6=Bertness |first6=Mark D. |last7=Leslie |first7=Heather M. |title=Salt marsh persistence is threatened by predicted sea-level rise |journal=Estuarine, Coastal and Shelf Science |date=November 2016 |volume=181 |pages=93\u201399 |doi=10.1016/j.ecss.2016.08.018 |bibcode=2016ECSS..181...93C |doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nature.org/media/oceansandcoasts/mangroves-for-coastal-defence.pdf|title=Mangroves for coastal defence. Guidelines for coastal managers & policy makers|author1=Spalding M.|author2=McIvor A.|date=2014|publisher=[[Wetlands International]] and [[The Nature Conservancy]]|author3=Tonneijck F.H.|author4=Tol S.|author5=van Eijk P.}}</ref> Human activities, such as dam building, can prevent natural adaptation processes by restricting sediment supplies to wetlands, resulting in the loss of [[tidal marsh]]es.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Weston |first1=Nathaniel B. |title=Declining Sediments and Rising Seas: an Unfortunate Convergence for Tidal Wetlands |journal=Estuaries and Coasts |date=16 July 2013 |volume=37 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201323 |doi=10.1007/s12237-013-9654-8 }}</ref>  When seawater moves inland, the [[coastal flooding]] can cause problems with existing terrestrial ecosystems, such as contaminating their soils.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/global-warming/sea-level-rise/|title=Sea Level Rise|date=January 13, 2017|website=National Geographic}}</ref> The [[Bramble Cay melomys]] is the first known land mammal to go extinct as a result of sea level rise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/news/2016/06/extinct-bramble-cay-melomys|title=Extinct: Bramble Cay melomys|last=Smith|first=Lauren|date=2016-06-15|website=Australian Geographic|access-date=2016-06-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/environment/climate-change/our-little-brown-rat-first-climate-change-caused-mammal-extinction-20190219-p50yry.html|title='Our little brown rat': first climate change-caused mammal extinction|last=Hannam|first=Peter|date=2019-02-19|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Ocean circulation and salinity==\n[[File:Overturning circulation of the global ocean.jpg|thumb|360px| {{center|[[Thermohaline circulation]], the ocean conveyor belt}}]]\n[[File:Aquarius flat 2048x1024.ogv|thumb|360px| {{center|Surface salinity changes measured by the [[Aquarius (SAC-D instrument)|NASA Aquarius]] satellite instrument from December 2011 to December 2012<br />Blue: low salinity &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Red: high salinity}}]]\n\nOcean salinity is a measure of how much dissolved [[Sea salt|salt]] is in the ocean. The salts come from erosion and transport of dissolved salts from the land. The surface salinity of the ocean is a key variable in the climate system when studying the global [[water cycle]], [[ocean\u2013atmosphere exchange]]s and [[ocean circulation]], all vital components transporting heat, momentum, carbon and nutrients around the world.<ref name=ESA>[https://phys.org/news/2019-12-salinity-reveal-impact-climate-variability.html New maps of salinity reveal the impact of climate variability on oceans] European Space Agency, 2 December 2019, ''PHYS.ORG''.</ref> Cold water is more dense than warm water and salty water is more dense than freshwater. This means the density of ocean water changes as its temperature and salinity changes. These changes in density are the main source of the power that drives the ocean circulation.<ref name=ESA />\n\nSurface ocean salinity measurements taken since the 1950s indicate an intensification of the global water cycle with high saline areas becoming more saline and low saline areas becoming more less saline.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/27/world/study-hints-at-greater-threat-of-extreme-weather.html |title=Study Indicates a Greater Threat of Extreme Weather |first=Justin |last=Gillis |date=April 26, 2012 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=2012-04-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426225622/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/27/world/study-hints-at-greater-threat-of-extreme-weather.html |archivedate=2012-04-26 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/aquarius/news/data-first-year.html |title=NASA's Aquarius Sees Salty Shifts |last=Vinas |first=Maria-Jose |date=June 6, 2013 |publisher=NASA |access-date=2018-01-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516200108/https://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/aquarius/news/data-first-year.html |archivedate=2017-05-16}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Ocean deoxygenation==\n[[File:Nitrogen cycle OMZ.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|{{center|[[Nitrogen cycle]] and the [[oxygen minimum zone]]}}]]\n\n[[Ocean deoxygenation]] is an additional stressor on marine life. Ocean deoxygenation is the expansion of [[oxygen minimum zone]]s in the oceans as a consequence of [[carbon emissions|burning fossil fuels]]. The change has been fairly rapid and poses a threat to fish and other types of marine life, as well as to people who depend on marine life for nutrition or livelihood.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/jan/04/oceans-suffocating-dead-zones-oxygen-starved Oceans suffocating as huge dead zones quadruple since 1950, scientists warn] The Guardian, 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/ocean-s-oxygen-starts-running-low/ Ocean's Oxygen Starts Running Low]</ref><ref>[https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/2015GB005310 Finding forced trends in oceanic oxygen]</ref><ref>[https://www.carbonbrief.org/guest-post-how-global-warming-is-causing-ocean-oxygen-levels-to-fall How global warming is causing ocean oxygen levels to fall]</ref> Ocean deoxygenation poses implications for [[Primary production|ocean productivity]], nutrient cycling, [[carbon cycling]], and [[marine habitats]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/dec/07/oceans-losing-oxygen-at-unprecedented-rate-experts-warn|title=Oceans losing oxygen at unprecedented rate, experts warn|last=Harvey|first=Fiona|date=2019-12-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>Laffoley, D. and Baxter, J. M. (eds.) (2019) [https://www.iucn.org/content/ocean-deoxygenation-everyones-problem Ocean deoxygenation : everyone\u2019s problem], IUCN Report.</ref>\n\nOcean warming exacerbates ocean deoxygenation and further stresses marine organisms, limiting nutrient availability by increasing [[ocean stratification]] through density and solubility effects while at the same time increasing metabolic demand.<ref>Bednar\u0161ek, N., Harvey, C.J., Kaplan, I.C., Feely, R.A. and Mo\u017eina, J. (2016) \"Pteropods on the edge: Cumulative effects of ocean acidification, warming, and deoxygenation\". ''Progress in Oceanography'', '''145''': 1\u201324. {{doi|10.1016/j.pocean.2016.04.002}}</ref><ref>Keeling, Ralph F., and Hernan E. Garcia (2002) \"The change in oceanic O2 inventory associated with recent global warming.\" ''Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences'', '''99'''(12): 7848\u20137853. {{doi|10.1073/pnas.122154899}}</ref> According to the IPCC 2019 [[Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate]], the viability of species is being disrupted throughout the [[ocean food web]] due to changes in ocean chemistry. As the ocean warms, [[Mixed layer|mixing between water layers]] decreases, resulting in less oxygen and nutrients being available for [[marine life]].<ref>{{Cite press release |series=Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate (SROCC) |title=Press Release |work=IPCC| access-date = 25 March 2020 |date = 25 September 2019| url = https://www.ipcc.ch/site/assets/uploads/sites/3/2019/09/SROCC_PressRelease_EN.pdf |format=PDF |pages=3}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Multiple stressors==\n[[File:Ecological Processes Coral Reefs.jpg|thumb|360px| {{center|Multiple stressors acting on [[Environmental issues with coral reefs|coral reefs]] <ref>Pendleton, L.H., Hoegh-Guldberg, O., Langdon, C. and Comte, A. (2016) \"Multiple stressors and ecological complexity require a new approach to coral reef research\". ''Frontiers in Marine Science'', '''3''': 36. {{doi|10.3389/fmars.2016.00036}}</ref>}}]]\n\nIf more than one stressor is present the effects can be amplified.<ref>Breitburg, D.L. and Riedel, G.F. (2005) [https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=J-2JcCC_Yn0C&pg=PA167&dq=%22Multiple+stressors+in+marine+systems%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjHmarigfbmAhXF6nMBHY-kAE0Q6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=%22Multiple%20stressors%20in%20marine%20systems%22&f=false \"Multiple stressors in marine systems\"]. In: M. E. Soul\u00e9, ''Marine conservation biology: the science of maintaining the sea's biodiversity'', Island Press, pages 167\u2013182. {{ISBN|9781597267717}}</ref><ref>Bopp, L., Resplandy, L., Orr, J.C., Doney, S.C., Dunne, J.P., Gehlen, M., Halloran, P., Heinze, C., Ilyina, T., Seferian, R. and Tjiputra, J. (2013) \"Multiple stressors of ocean ecosystems in the 21st century: projections with CMIP5 models\". ''Biogeosciences'', '''10''': 6225\u20136245. {{doi|10.5194/bg-10-6225-2013}}</ref> For example, the combination of ocean acidification and an elevation of ocean temperature can have a compounded effect on marine life far exceeding the individual harmful impact of either.<ref>Kroeker, et al. (June  2013) \"Impacts of ocean acidification on marine organisms: quantifying sensitivities and interaction with warming.\" Glob Chang Biol. 19(6): 1884\u20131896</ref><ref name=Harvey2013>Harvey B.P., Gwynn\u2010Jones D. and Moore P.J. (2013) \"Meta\u2010analysis reveals complex marine biological responses to the interactive effects of ocean acidification and warming\". ''Ecology and evolution'', '''3'''(4): 1016\u20131030. {{doi|10.1002/ece3.516}}</ref><ref>Nagelkerken Global alteration of ocean ecosystem functioning due to increasing human CO2 emissions, PNAS vol. 112 no. 43, 2015</ref>\n\nThe direction and magnitude of the effects of ocean acidification, warming and deoxygenation on the ocean has been quantified by [[meta-analyses]],<ref name=Harvey2013 /><ref>Gruber, Nicolas. \"Warming up, turning sour, losing breath: ocean biogeochemistry under global change.\" Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London A: Mathematical, Physical and Engineering Sciences 369.1943 (2011): 1980\u20131996.</ref><ref>Anthony, et al. (May 2011) \"Ocean acidification and warming will lower coral reef resilience.\" Global Change biology, Volume 17, Issue 5, Pages 1798\u20131808</ref> and has been further tested by [[mesocosm]] studies. The mesocosm studies simulated the interaction of these stressors and found a catastrophic effect on the marine food web, namely, that the increases in consumption from thermal stress more than negates any primary producer to herbivore increase from more available carbon dioxide.<ref>Goldenberg, Silvan U, et al. (2017) \"Boosted food web productivity through ocean acidification collapses under warming.\" Global Change Biology.</ref><ref>Pistevos, Jennifer CA, et al. (2015) \"Ocean acidification and global warming impair shark hunting behaviour and growth.\" Scientific reports 5: 16293.</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Microorganisms==\n[[File:Microorganisms and climate change.png|thumb|right|upright=2| {{center|Microorganisms and climate change in marine and terrestrial biomes <ref name=Cavicchioli2019 />}}]]\n{{see also|Marine microorganism}}\n\nIn marine environments, microbial [[primary production]] contributes substantially to [[Carbon sequestration|CO<sub>2</sub> sequestration]]. Marine microorganisms also recycle nutrients for use in the [[marine food web]] and in the process release CO<sub>2</sub> to the atmosphere. Microbial biomass and other organic matter (remnants of plants and animals) are converted to fossil fuels over millions of years. By contrast, burning of [[fossil fuel]]s liberates greenhouse gases in a small fraction of that time. As a result, the [[carbon cycle]] is out of balance, and atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> levels will continue to rise as long as fossil fuels continue to be burnt.<ref name=Cavicchioli2019>Cavicchioli, R., Ripple, W.J., Timmis, K.N., Azam, F., Bakken, L.R., Baylis, M., Behrenfeld, M.J., Boetius, A., Boyd, P.W., Classen, A.T. and Crowther, T.W. (2019) \"Scientists\u2019 warning to humanity: microorganisms and climate change\". ''Nature Reviews Microbiology'', '''17''': 569\u2013586. {{doi|10.1038/s41579-019-0222-5}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Drivers of change==\n[[File:Drivers of change in marine ecosystems.png|thumb|360px| {{center|Drivers of change in marine ecosystems <ref name=\u00d6sterblom2017>\u00d6sterblom, H., Crona, B.I., Folke, C., Nystr\u00f6m, M. and Troell, M. (2017) \"Marine ecosystem science on an intertwined planet\". ''Ecosystems'', '''20'''(1): 54\u201361. {{doi|10.1007/s10021-016-9998-6}}</ref>}}]]\n\nChanges in marine ecosystem dynamics are influenced by socioeconomic activities (for example, fishing, pollution) and human-induced biophysical change (for example, temperature, ocean acidification) and can interact and severely impact marine ecosystem dynamics and the ecosystem services they generate to society. Understanding these direct\u2014or proximate\u2014interactions is an important step towards sustainable use of marine ecosystems. However, proximate interactions are embedded in a much broader socioeconomic context where, for example, economy through trade and finance, human migration and technological advances, operate and interact at a global scale, influencing proximate relationships.<ref name=\u00d6sterblom2017 />\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Shifting baselines==\n[[Shifting baselines]] arise in research on marine ecosystems because changes must be measured against some previous reference point (baseline), which in turn may represent significant changes from an even earlier state of the ecosystem.<ref name=Pauly1995>Pauly, Daniel (1995) [http://legacy.seaaroundus.s3.amazonaws.com/doc/Researcher+Publications/dpauly/PDF/1995/Journal+Articles/Anecdotes%26ShiftingBaselineSyndromeFisheries.pdf \"Anecdotes and the shifting baseline syndrome of fisheries\"]. ''Trends in ecology & evolution'', '''10'''(10): 430.</ref> For example, radically depleted fisheries have been evaluated by researchers who used the state of the fishery at the start of their careers as the baseline, rather than the fishery in its unexploited or untouched state. Areas that swarmed with a particular species hundreds of years ago may have experienced long term decline, but it is the level a few decades previously that is used as the reference point for current populations. In this way large declines in ecosystems or species over long periods of time were, and are, masked. There is a loss of perception of change that occurs when each generation redefines what is natural or untouched.<ref name=Pauly1995 />\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=26em}}\n* [[Anthropocene]]\n* [[Climate change and ecosystems]]\n* [[Climate change in the Arctic]]\n* [[Effects of climate change on terrestrial animals]]\n* [[Effects of global warming on marine mammals]]\n* [[Global warming in Antarctica]]\n* [[Marine debris]]\n* [[Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate]]\n* [[Threatened rays]]\n* [[Threatened sharks]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Human impact on the environment|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Human impact on the environment]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Global cumulative human impact on the ocean.png|thumb|upright=1.8| {{center|Global cumulative human impact on the ocean <ref name=Halpern2019>Halpern, B.S., Frazier, M., Afflerbach, J. et&nbsp;al. (2019) \"Recent pace of change in human impact on the world\u2019s ocean.\" ''Nature Scientific Reports'', '''9''': 11609. {{doi|10.1038/s41598-019-47201-9}}</ref><ref>Halpern, B.S., Walbridge, S., Selkoe, K.A., Kappel, C.V., Micheli, F., D'agrosa, C., Bruno, J.F., Casey, K.S., Ebert, C., Fox, H.E. and Fujita, R. (2008) \"A global map of human impact on marine ecosystems\". ''Science'', '''319'''(5865): 948\u2013952. {{doi|10.1126/science.1149345}}</ref>}}]]\n{{marine life sidebar}}\n\nHuman activities affect [[marine life]] and [[marine habitat]]s through [[overfishing]], [[habitat loss]], the introduction of [[invasive species]], [[Marine pollution|ocean pollution]], [[ocean acidification]] and [[ocean warming]]. These impact [[marine ecosystem]]s and [[Marine food web|food webs]] and may result in consequences as yet unrecognised for the [[biodiversity]] and continuation of marine life forms.<ref>[https://www.geomar.de/en/research/human-impacts-on-marine-ecosystems/ Human impacts on marine ecosystems] GEOMAR Helmholtz Centre for Ocean Research. Retrieved 22 October 2019.</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[IPCC]] (2019), since 1950 \"many marine species across various groups have undergone shifts in geographical range and seasonal activities in response to ocean warming, sea ice change and biogeochemical changes, such as oxygen loss, to their habitats.\"<ref>{{Cite report| title = Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate (SROCC) |work=IPCC| access-date = 25 March 2020 |date = 25 September 2019| url = https://www.ipcc.ch/report/srocc |pages=2 }}</ref>\n\nIt has been estimated only 13% of the ocean area remains as [[wilderness]], mostly in open ocean areas rather than along the coast.<ref>Jones, K.R., Klein, C.J., Halpern, B.S., Venter, O., Grantham, H., Kuempel, C.D., Shumway, N., Friedlander, A.M., Possingham, H.P. and Watson, J.E. (2018) \"The location and protection status of Earth\u2019s diminishing marine wilderness\". ''Current Biology'', '''28'''(15): 2506\u20132512. {{doi|10.1016/j.cub.2018.06.010}}</ref>\n\n==Overfishing==\n[[File:Fishing down the food web.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5| {{center|[[Fishing down the foodweb]]<br />Overfishing of high trophic fish like [[tuna]] can result in<br />them being replaced by low trophic organisms, like [[jellyfish]]}}]]\n{{see also|Overfishing|Environmental impact of fishing}}\n\n[[Overfishing]] is occurring in one third of world fish stocks, according to a 2018 report by the [[Food and Agriculture Organization]] of the United Nations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fao.org/state-of-fisheries-aquaculture/en/|title=SOFIA 2018 - State of Fisheries and Aquaculture in the world 2018|last=fao.org|work=www.fao.org|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> In addition, industry observers believe [[illegal, unreported and unregulated fishing]] occurs in most fisheries, and accounts for up to 30% of total catches in some important fisheries.<ref>World Wildlife Fund. \"[http://www.panda.org/about_wwf/what_we_do/marine/problems/problems_fishing/illegal_fishing/index.cfm Fishing problems: Illegal fishing]\" {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411060604/http://www.panda.org/about_wwf/what_we_do/marine/problems/problems_fishing/illegal_fishing/index.cfm |date=2008-04-11 }}</ref> In a phenomenon called [[fishing down the foodweb]], the [[mean trophic level]] of world fisheries has declined because of [[overfishing]] high [[trophic level]] fish.<ref>Pauly, Daniel and Watson, Reg (2009) [http://www.seaaroundus.org/researcher//dpauly/PDF/2009/Books%26Chapters/SpatialDynamicsOfFisheries.pdf \"Spatial Dynamics of Marine Fisheries\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611044204/http://www.seaaroundus.org/researcher/dpauly/PDF/2009/Books%26Chapters/SpatialDynamicsOfFisheries.pdf |date=2012-06-11 }} ''In:'' Simon A. Levin (ed.) ''The Princeton Guide to Ecology''. Pages 501\u2013509.</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n |align = left\n |width = 388px\n |title = \n |quote = \"It is almost as though we use our military to fight the animals in the ocean. We are gradually winning this war to exterminate them.\"\n |author = \u2013 [[Daniel Pauly]], pioneer on human impacts on global fisheries\n |source = <ref>{{cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tf1EgeHDxpA|title=Fisheries on the brink\n |authorlink=Daniel Pauly|last=Pauly|first=Daniel|type=YouTube video|accessdate=2012-05-01}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Habitat loss==\n[[File:Cumulative human impacts on marine ecosystems.png|thumb|upright=1.5| Relationship between annual trend and current cumulative impacts for different marine ecosystems.<ref name=Halpern2019 />]]\n\n[[Coastal ecosystem]]s are being particularly damaged by humans.<ref name=Waycott2009>Waycott, M., Duarte, C.M., Carruthers, T.J., Orth, R.J., Dennison, W.C., Olyarnik, S., Calladine, A., Fourqurean, J.W., Heck, K.L., Hughes, A.R. and Kendrick, G.A. (2009) [https://www.pnas.org/content/106/30/12377.full \"Accelerating loss of seagrasses across the globe threatens coastal ecosystems\".] ''Proceedings of the national academy of sciences'', '''106'''(30): 12377\u201312381. {{doi|10.1073/pnas.0905620106}}</ref> [[Habitat loss]] is occurring in seagrass meadows, mangrove forests, coral reefs and kelp forests, all of which are in global decline due to human disturbances.\n\n[[Seagrass meadow]]s have lost {{convert|30000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} during recent decades. Seagrass [[ecosystem service]]s, currently worth about $US1.9 trillion per year, include [[nutrient cycling]], the provision of food and habitats for many marine animals, including the endangered [[dugong]]s, [[manatee]] and [[green turtle]]s, and major facilitations for [[coral reef fish]].<ref name=Waycott2009 />\n\n[[Coral reef]]s are among the more productive and diverse ecosystems on the planet, but one fifth of them have been lost in recent years due to anthropogenic disturbances.<ref name=Wilkinson>Wilkinson, Clive (2008) [http://www.icriforum.org/sites/default/files/Status%20Coral%20%20Reefs%20of%20World%202008%20%20Executive%20Summary_0.pdf Status of Coral Reefs of the World: Executive Summary]. Global Coral Reef Monitoring Network.</ref>  Coral reefs are [[microbial]]ly driven ecosystems that rely on [[marine microorganism]]s to retain and recycle nutrients in order to thrive in [[oligotrophic]] waters. However these same microorganisms can also trigger feedback loops that intensify declines in coral reefs, with cascading effects across [[Marine biogeochemical cycles| biogeochemical cycles]] and [[marine food web]]s. A better understanding is needed of the complex microbial interactions within coral reefs if reef conservation is to have a chance of success in the future.<ref>Vanwonterghem, I. and Webster, N.S. (2020) \"Coral reef microorganisms in a changing climate\". ''Iscience'', '''23'''(4). {{doi|10.1016/j.isci.2020.100972}}.</ref>\n\nOne fifth of the world's [[mangrove forest]]s have also been lost since 1980.<ref name=\"nature.org\">{{cite web|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100717013054/http://www.nature.org/pressroom/press/press4573.html|archive-date= 2010-07-17|url=http://www.nature.org/pressroom/press/press4573.html |title= 2010a. \"\"World Atlas of Mangroves\" Highlights the Importance of and Threats to Mangroves: Mangroves among World's Most Valuable Ecosystems.\" Press release. Arlington, Virginia |publisher=The Nature Conservancy|accessdate=2014-01-25|url-status= dead}}</ref> The most pressing threat to [[kelp forest]]s may be the overfishing of coastal ecosystems, which by removing higher trophic levels facilitates their shift to depauperate [[urchin barren]]s.<ref name=\"Sala1998\">Sala, E., C.F. Bourdouresque and M. Harmelin-Vivien. 1998. Fishing, trophic cascades, and the structure of algal assemblages: evaluation of an old but untested paradigm. Oikos 82: 425-439.</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Invasive species==\n[[File:Ship pumping ballast water.jpg|thumb|A cargo ship pumps ballast water over the side.]]\n\nAn [[invasive species]] is a species not native to a particular location which can spread to a degree that causes damage to the environment, human economy or human health.<ref>{{Citation|title=Ecosystem Consequences of Biological Invasions |author=Joan G. Ehrenfeld |journal=Annual Review of Ecology, Evolution, and Systematics |year=2010 |volume=41 |pages=59\u201380 |doi=10.1146/annurev-ecolsys-102209-144650 }}</ref> In 2008, Molnar et&nbsp;al. documented the pathways of hundreds of marine invasive species and found shipping was the dominant mechanism for the transfer of invasive species in the ocean. The two main maritime mechanisms of transporting marine organisms to other ocean environments are via [[hull fouling]] and the transfer of [[ballast water]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Molnar|first=Jennifer L|last2=Gamboa|first2=Rebecca L|last3=Revenga|first3=Carmen|last4=Spalding|first4=Mark D|date=2008|title=Assessing the global threat of invasive species to marine biodiversity|journal=Frontiers in Ecology and the Environment|volume=6|issue=9|pages=485\u2013492|doi=10.1890/070064|issn=1540-9295}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Comb jelly.tif|thumb|left| {{center|''Mnemiopsis leidyi''}}]]\n\n[[Ballast water]] taken up at sea and released in port is a major source of unwanted exotic marine life. The [[invasive species|invasive]] freshwater zebra mussels, native to the Black, Caspian, and Azov seas, were probably transported to the Great Lakes via ballast water from a transoceanic vessel.<ref>[http://www.wsg.washington.edu/mas/pdfs/leastwanted.pdf Aquatic invasive species. A Guide to Least-Wanted Aquatic Organisms of the Pacific Northwest] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725040002/http://www.wsg.washington.edu/mas/pdfs/leastwanted.pdf |date=25 July 2008}}. 2001. University of Washington</ref> Meinesz believes that one of the worst cases of a single invasive species causing harm to an ecosystem can be attributed to a seemingly harmless [[jellyfish]]. ''[[Mnemiopsis leidyi]]'', a species of comb jellyfish that spread so it now inhabits estuaries in many parts of the world, was first introduced in 1982, and thought to have been transported to the [[Black Sea]] in a ship's ballast water. The population of the jellyfish grew exponentially and, by 1988, it was wreaking havoc upon the local [[fishing industry]]. \"The [[anchovy]] catch fell from 204,000 tons in 1984 to 200 tons in 1993; [[sprat]] from 24,600 tons in 1984 to 12,000 tons in 1993; horse [[mackerel]] from 4,000 tons in 1984 to zero in 1993.\"<ref name=\"Meinesz\">Meinesz, A. (2003) [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/algae/impact.html Deep Sea Invasion: The Impact of Invasive Species] PBS: NOVA. Retrieved 26 November 2009</ref> Now that the jellyfish have exhausted the [[zooplankton]], including fish larvae, their numbers have fallen dramatically, yet they continue to maintain a stranglehold on the [[ecosystem]].\n\n[[Invasive species]] can take over once occupied areas, facilitate the spread of new diseases, introduce new [[genetics|genetic]] material, alter underwater seascapes, and jeopardize the ability of [[native species]] to obtain food. Invasive species are responsible for about $138&nbsp;billion annually in lost revenue and management costs in the US alone.<ref name=pimental>{{cite journal |doi= 10.1016/j.ecolecon.2004.10.002 |title= Update on the environmental and economic costs associated with alien-invasive species in the United States |journal= Ecological Economics |volume= 52 |issue= 3 |pages= 273\u2013288 |year= 2005 |last1= Pimentel |first1= D. |last2= Zuniga |first2= R. |last3= Morrison |first3= D.}}</ref>\n\n==Marine pollution==\n[[Marine pollution]] results from the entry into the ocean of [[industrial waste|industrial]], [[Agricultural pollution|agricultural]], and [[municipal solid waste|residential]] [[wastes]].<ref>{{cite web |title= What is the biggest source of pollution in the ocean?|url= http://oceanservice.noaa.gov/facts/pollution.html|website= oceanservice.noaa.gov|accessdate= 2015-11-22|author= US Department of Commerce, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration}}</ref> Pathways for this pollution include agricultural [[surface runoff|runoff]] into rivers and wind-blown [[debris]] and dust. The [[Asian brown cloud]], a layer of air pollution that covers much of South Asia and the Indian Ocean for several months every year, also hangs over the Bay of Bengal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/NaturalHazards/shownh.php3?img_id=13341 |title=EO Natural Hazards: Smog over the Bay of Bengal |website=NASA Earth Observatory |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026204458/http://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/NaturalHazards/shownh.php3?img_id=13341 |archive-date=26 October 2007 |access-date=21 January 2007}}</ref> Because of this cloud, satellites attempting to track ocean acidification and other ocean health indicators in the Bay have difficulty obtaining accurate measurements.<ref>[https://www.firstpost.com/tech/science/ocean-acidification-in-bay-of-bengal-is-now-being-monitored-by-global-satellite-network-7787131.html Ocean acidification in Bay of Bengal is now being monitored] ''[[Firstpost]]'', 16 December 2019.</ref>\n\n===Nutrient pollution===\n[[Nutrient pollution]] is a primary cause of [[eutrophication]] of surface waters, in which excess nutrients, usually [[nitrate]]s or [[phosphate]]s, stimulate algae growth.\n\n===Toxic chemicals===\n{{see also|xenobiotic}}\n\nToxic chemicals can adhere to tiny particles which are then taken up by [[plankton]] and [[benthos|benthic animals]], most of which are either [[deposit feeder]]s or [[filter feeder]]s. In this way, toxins are [[biomagnification|concentrated upward]] within ocean [[food chain]]s. Many particles combine chemically in a manner which depletes oxygen, causing [[estuary|estuaries]] to become [[hypoxia (environmental)|anoxic]]. [[Pesticide]]s and [[toxic metal]]s are similarly incorporated into marine food webs, harming the biological health of marine life. Many [[compound feed|animal feeds]] have a high [[fish meal]] or [[fish hydrolysate]] content. In this way, marine toxins are transferred back to farmed land animals, and then to humans.\n\n[[Phytoplankton]] concentrations have increased over the last century in coastal waters, and more recently have declined in the open ocean. Increases in nutrient runoff from land may explain the increases in coastal phytoplankton, while warming surface temperatures in the open ocean may have strengthened stratification in the water column, reducing the flow of nutrients from the deep that open ocean phytoplankton find useful.<ref>Boyce, D.G. and [[Boris Worm|Worm, B.]] (2015) \"Patterns and ecological implications of historical marine phytoplankton change\". ''Marine Ecology Progress Series'', '''534''':251\u2013272. {{doi|10.3354/meps11411}}</ref>\n\n===Plastic pollution===\n<!--In 2015, between 93 and 236 thousand metric tons of [[Plastic pollution|plastic]] were estimated to be in the world\u2019s oceans.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1088/1748-9326/10/12/124006 |title=A global inventory of small floating plastic debris |journal=Environmental Research Letters |volume=10 |issue=12 |pages=124006 |year=2015 |last1=Van Sebille |first1=Erik |last2=Wilcox |first2=Chris |last3=Lebreton |first3=Laurent |last4=Maximenko |first4=Nikolai |last5=Hardesty |first5=Britta Denise |last6=Van Franeker |first6=Jan A. |last7=Eriksen |first7=Marcus |last8=Siegel |first8=David |last9=Galgani |first9=Francois |last10=Law |first10=Kara Lavender }}</ref> --> \nEstimates suggest something like 9 million tonnes of plastic is added to the ocean every year. This plastic may need 450 years or more to biograde. Once in the ocean, plastics are shredded by marine [[amphipod]]s into [[microplastics]]. There are now beaches where 15 percent of the sand are grains of microplastic. In the oceans themselves, microplastics float in surface waters amongst the plankton where they are ingested by plankton eaters.<ref>Parker, Laura (2018) [https://www.nationalgeographic.com/magazine/2018/06/plastic-planet-waste-pollution-trash-crisis/ \"We made plastic. We depend on it. Now we're drowning in it\".] ''National Geographic''.</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=180px style=float:left;>\nFile:Microplastics in sediment from the Rhine.jpg| Microplastics among sand and glass spheres in sediment from the [[Rhine]]. The white bar represents 1&nbsp;mm.\nFile:Pacific-garbage-patch-map 2010 noaamdp.jpg| Vast [[Great Pacific garbage patch|plastic garbage patches]] have accumulated at the centre of [[ocean gyre]]s.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://marinedebris.noaa.gov/movement/great-pacific-garbage-patch |title=Great Pacific Garbage Patch |website= Marine Debris Division \u2013 Office of Response and Restoration |publisher=NOAA |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140417124654/https://marinedebris.noaa.gov/movement/great-pacific-garbage-patch |archivedate=17 April 2014 |df=dmy-all|date=2013-07-11 }}</ref>\nFile:Ocean plasic count density.gif| Model results for the count density of small planktonic plastic particles.<ref>Eriksen, M., Lebreton, L.C., Carson, H.S., Thiel, M., Moore, C.J., Borerro, J.C., Galgani, F., Ryan, P.G. and Reisser, J. (2014) [http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0111913 \"Plastic pollution in the world's oceans: more than 5 trillion plastic pieces weighing over 250,000 tons afloat at sea\"]. ''PLOS ONE'', '''9''' (12): e111913. {{doi|10.1371/journal.pone.0111913.g002}}</ref><br /> Red: more dense &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Green: less dense\n</gallery>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Noise pollution===\n{{See also|Marine pollution#Underwater noise|Marine mammals and sonar}}\n\nUnderwater noise pollution due to human activities is also prevalent in the sea.<ref name=Williams2015>Williams, R., Wright, A.J., Ashe, E., Blight, L.K., Bruintjes, R., Canessa, R., Clark, C.W., Cullis-Suzuki, S., Dakin, D.T., Erbe, C. and Hammond, P.S. (2015) [https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S096456911500160X \"Impacts of anthropogenic noise on marine life: Publication patterns, new discoveries, and future directions in research and management\".] ''Ocean & Coastal Management'', '''115''': 17\u201324. {{doi|10.1016/j.ocecoaman.2015.05.021}}</ref> Cargo ships generate high levels of noise due to propellers and diesel engines.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Radiated noise characteristics of a modern cargo ship|journal=The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America |volume=107| issue=1| pages=118\u2013129 |doi=10.1121/1.428344 |pmid=10641625 |year=2000 | last1=Arveson | first1=Paul T|last2=Vendittis |first2=David J |bibcode=2000ASAJ..107..118A }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Measurements of radiated underwater noise from modern merchant ships relevant to noise impacts on marine mammals |journal=The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America | volume=129 |issue=4 |page=2368| doi=10.1121/1.3587665 | year=2011 | last1=McKenna | first1=Megan F | last2=Ross | first2=Donald| last3=Wiggins |first3=Sean M |last4=Hildebrand |first4=John A |bibcode=2011ASAJ..129.2368M }}</ref> This noise pollution significantly raises the low-frequency ambient noise levels above those caused by wind.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Acoustic Ambient Noise in the Ocean: Spectra and Sources|journal=The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America |volume=34 |issue=12 |pages=1936\u20131956 |doi=10.1121/1.1909155 |year=1962 |last=Wenz |first= Gordon M |bibcode=1962ASAJ...34.1936W }}</ref> Animals such as whales that depend on sound for communication can be affected adversely.  Even marine invertebrates, such as crabs (''[[Carcinus maenas]]''), have been shown to be negatively affected by ship noise.<ref name=DeepSNcrabs>{{cite web |author=McClain, Craig |title=Loud Noise Makes Crabs Even More Crabby |publisher=Deep Sea News |url=http://deepseanews.com/2013/04/load-noise-makes-crabs-edgy/ |accessdate=2013-04-04 |date=2013-04-03 }}</ref><ref name=\"WaleSimpson2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Wale|first1=M. A.|last2=Simpson|first2=S. D.|last3=Radford|first3=A. N.|title=Size-dependent physiological responses of shore crabs to single and repeated playback of ship noise|journal=Biology Letters|volume=9|issue=2|year=2013|pages=20121194|issn=1744-9561|doi=10.1098/rsbl.2012.1194|pmid=23445945|pmc=3639773}}</ref>\n\n==Ocean acidification==\n[[File:WOA05 GLODAP del pH AYool.png|thumb|right|upright=1.5| Estimated change in sea water [[pH]] caused by human created [[carbon dioxide|{{chem|CO|2}}]] from the start of the industrial revolution to the end of the twentieth century]]\n{{see also|Ocean acidification#Possible impacts}}\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | image1    = Coccolithus pelagicus.jpg\n | width1    = 168\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = {{center|[[Coccolithophore]]}}\n | image2    = Red sea urchin 3.jpg\n | width2    = 182\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = {{center|[[Sea urchin]]}}\n | footer            = Increases in acidity makes it difficult for microorganisms like coccolithophores, and [[shellfish]] like sea urchins, to build their carbonate shells\n | footer_align      = center\n}}\n\n[[Ocean acidification]] is the increasing acidification of the oceans, caused mainly by the uptake of [[carbon dioxide]] from the [[Earth's atmosphere|atmosphere]].<ref name=\"cald03\">{{Cite journal |last=Caldeira |first=K. |author2=Wickett, M. E. |year=2003 |title=Anthropogenic carbon and ocean pH |journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |volume=425 |issue=6956 |pages=365 |doi=10.1038/425365a |pmid=14508477 |bibcode=2001AGUFMOS11C0385C |ref=harv|url= https://zenodo.org/record/1233227}}</ref> The rise in atmospheric carbon dioxide due to the burning of fossil fuels leads to more  carbon dioxide dissolving in the ocean. When carbon dioxide dissolves in water it forms hydrogen and carbonate ions. This in turn increases the [[ocean acidification|acidity of the ocean]] and makes survival increasingly harder for microorganisms, shellfish and other marine organisms that depend on [[calcium carbonate]] to form their shells.<ref>{{harv|Trujillo|Thurman|2008|p=151}}{{full citation needed|date=December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIncreasing acidity also has potential for other harm to marine organisms, such as depressing metabolic rates and immune responses in some organisms, and causing [[coral bleaching]].<ref name=\"bleaching\">{{cite journal |first=KRN |last=Anthony |display-authors=et al |title=Ocean acidification causes bleaching and productivity loss in coral reef builders |journal= Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |year=2008 |pages=17442\u201317446 |doi=10.1073/pnas.0804478105 |pmid=18988740 |volume=105 |issue=45 |bibcode=2008PNAS..10517442A |pmc=2580748}}</ref> Ocean acidification has increased 26% since the beginning of the industrial era.<ref>IPCC (2019) Summary for Policymakers. In: [https://report.ipcc.ch/srocc/pdf/SROCC_FinalDraft_FullReport.pdf ''IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate''], Chapter 1, page 14. [H.O. P\u00f6rtner, D.C. Roberts, V. Masson-Delmotte, P. Zhai, M. Tignor, E. Poloczanska, K. Mintenbeck, M. Nicolai, A. Okem, J. Petzold, B. Rama, N. Weyer (eds.)]. Final draft: 24 September 2019.</ref> It has been compared to [[anthropogenic climate change]] and called the \"evil twin of [[global warming]]\"<ref name=\"HPost\">{{cite web |work=[[Huffington Post]] |date=9 July 2012 |title=Ocean Acidification Is Climate Change's 'Equally Evil Twin,' NOAA Chief Says |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/09/ocean-acidification-reefs-climate-change_n_1658081.html |accessdate=2012-07-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120712003629/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/09/ocean-acidification-reefs-climate-change_n_1658081.html |archivedate=12 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and \"the other {{CO2}} problem\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Doney|first=S.C.|last2=Fabry|first2=V.J.|last3=Feely|first3=R.A.|last4=Kleypas|first4=J.A.|year=2009|title=Ocean Acidification: The Other {{CO2}} Problem|journal=Annual Review of Marine Science|volume=1 |issue= |pages=169\u2013192 |pmid= 21141034 |bibcode= 2009ARMS....1..169D| url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/3df7/eebe38b6c8cbc6e4bca5035a339d832a570c.pdf?_ga=2.224706074.1056012774.1577577758-308431455.1577577758|doi= 10.1146/annurev.marine.010908.163834}}</ref>\n\nAragonite is a form of calcium carbonate many marine animals use to build carbonate skeletons and shells. The lower the aragonite [[Ocean acidification#Saturation state|saturation level]], the more difficult it is for the organisms to build and maintain their skeletons and shells. The map below shows changes in the aragonite saturation level of ocean surface waters between 1880 and 2012.<ref>{{cite web| title=Changes in Aragonite Saturation of the World's Oceans, 1880\u20132015| url=https://www.epa.gov/climate-indicators/climate-change-indicators-ocean-acidity|author=Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution| date=August 2016| website= }}<br />{{cite journal|last=Feely|first=R.A.|first2=S.C.|last2=Doney|first3=S.R.|last3=Cooley|year=2009|title=Ocean acidification: Present conditions and future changes in a high-{{CO2}} world|url=https://darchive.mblwhoilibrary.org/bitstream/handle/1912/3180/22-4_feely.pdf?sequence=1|work=Oceanography|volume=22|issue=4|pages=36\u201347|doi=10.5670/oceanog.2009.95|hdl=1912/3180|via=Woods Hole Open Access Server}}<br />{{cite web| title=Climate Change Indicators in the United States, 2012, 2nd ed: Ocean Acidity: Figure 2. Changes in Aragonite Saturation of the World's Oceans, 1880-2012  | publisher=US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) | url=http://www.epa.gov/climatechange/science/indicators/oceans/acidity.html#fragment-2 }}</ref>\n\nTo pick one example, [[pteropod]]s are a group of widely distributed swimming [[sea snail]]s. For pteropods to create shells they require [[aragonite]] which is produced through carbonate ions and dissolved calcium. Pteropods are severely affected because increasing acidification levels have steadily decreased the amount of water supersaturated with carbonate which is needed for the aragonite creation.<ref name=\"biogeosciences\">{{cite web | url=http://www.biogeosciences.net/8/919/2011/bg-8-919-2011.pdf | title=Impact of ocean acidification and elevated temperatures on early juveniles of the polar shelled pteropod Limacina helicina : mortality, shell degradation, and shell growth | publisher=Biogeosciences | work=Report |date=15 April 2011 | accessdate=14 November 2013 |author1=Lischka, S. |author2=B\u00fcdenbender J. |author3=Boxhammer T. |author4=Riebesell U. | pages=919\u2013932}}</ref>\n\nWhen the shell of a pteropod was immersed in water with a pH level the ocean is projected to reach by the year 2100, the shell almost completely dissolved within six weeks.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Limacina helicina shell dissolution as an indicator of declining habitat suitability owing to ocean acidification in the California Current Ecosystem|journal = Proc. R. Soc. B|date = 2014|issn = 0962-8452|pmc = 4024287|pmid = 24789895|pages = 20140123|volume = 281|issue = 1785|doi = 10.1098/rspb.2014.0123|first = N.|last = Bednar\u0161ek|first2 = R. A.|last2 = Feely|first3 = J. C. P.|last3 = Reum|first4 = B.|last4 = Peterson|first5 = J.|last5 = Menkel|first6 = S. R.|last6 = Alin|first7 = B.|last7 = Hales}}</ref> Likewise [[coral]]s,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=D'Olivo|first=Juan P.|last2=Ellwood|first2=George|last3=DeCarlo|first3=Thomas M.|last4=McCulloch|first4=Malcolm T.|date=2019-11-15|title=Deconvolving the long-term impacts of ocean acidification and warming on coral biomineralisation|journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters|volume=526|pages=115785|doi=10.1016/j.epsl.2019.115785|issn=0012-821X|doi-access=free}}</ref> [[coralline algae]],<ref name=\"kuffner\">{{Cite journal | last=Kuffner | first=I. B. |author2=Andersson, A. J.|author3=Jokiel, P. L.|author4=Rodgers, K. S. |author5=Mackenzie, F. T. | year=2007 | title=Decreased abundance of crustose coralline algae due to ocean acidification | journal=[[Nature Geoscience]] | volume=1 |issue=2 |pages=114\u2013117 |doi=10.1038/ngeo100 |bibcode=2008NatGe...1..114K | ref=harv| url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/7e00dfd0d003c947045bf58aef07c024adc409e6 }}</ref> coccolithophores,<ref name=\"delille05\">{{Cite journal | last=Delille | first=B.|author2=Harlay, J.|author3=Zondervan, I.|author4= Jacquet, S.|author5=Chou, L.|author6=Wollast, R.|author7=Bellerby, R.G.J.|author8= Frankignoulle, M.|author9=Borges, A.V.|author10=Riebesell, U. |author11=Gattuso, J.-P. | year=2005 | title=Response of primary production and calcification to changes of p{{co2}} during experimental blooms of the coccolithophorid ''Emiliania huxleyi'' | url=http://www.obs-vlfr.fr/~gattuso/jpg_papers_list.php | journal=Global Biogeochemical Cycles | volume=19 |doi=10.1029/2004GB002318 | pages=GB2023 | bibcode=2005GBioC..19.2023D | issue=2 | ref=harv}}</ref> [[foraminifera]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Phillips |first=Graham |author2=Chris Branagan |title=Ocean Acidification \u2013 The BIG global warming story |date=2007 |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |url=http://www.abc.net.au/catalyst/stories/s2029333.htm |work =ABC TV Science: Catalyst |accessdate=2007-09-18  }}</ref> as well as [[shellfish]] generally,<ref name=\"gaz07\">{{Cite journal |last=Gazeau |first=F. |author2=Quiblier, C. |author3=Jansen, J. M. |author4=Gattuso, J.-P. |author5= Middelburg, J. J. |author6=Heip, C. H. R. |year=2007 |title=Impact of elevated {{chem|CO|2}} on shellfish calcification |url=http://www.obs-vlfr.fr/~gattuso/jpg_papers_list.php |journal=[[Geophysical Research Letters]] |volume=34 |issue=7 |pages=L07603 |doi=10.1029/2006GL028554 |bibcode=2007GeoRL..3407603G |ref=harv|hdl=20.500.11755/a8941c6a-6d0b-43d5-ba0d-157a7aa05668 }}</ref> all experience reduced calcification or enhanced dissolution as an effect of ocean acidification.\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=170px style=\"float:left;\">\nFile:Changes in aragonite saturation of the world's oceans, 1880-2012 (US EPA).png|{{center|Decreases in aragonite saturation make it more difficult for marine organisms like pteropods to build [[Seashell|calcium shells]]}}\nFile:Effect of Ocean Acidification on Calcification.svg|Shells of pteropods dissolve in increasingly acidic conditions caused by increased amounts of atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub>\n</gallery>\n\n[[File:Impacts of ocean acidification (NOAA EVL).webm|thumb|355px| Video summarizing impacts of ocean acidification \u2013 Source: [[NOAA]]]]\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | image1    = Fis01026 (27555118153).jpg\n | width1    = 170\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = {{center|Unhealthy pteropod showing effects of ocean acidification}}\n | image2    = FMIB 52630 Ophiopholis aculeata.jpeg\n | width2    = 230\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = {{center|Ocean acidification causes brittle stars to lose muscle mass}}\n | footer            = &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; [[Pteropod]]s and [[brittle star]]s form the base of Arctic food webs\n | footer_align      = center\n}}\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n[[Pteropoda|Pteropods]] and [[brittle star]]s together form the base of the Arctic [[food web]]s and both are seriously damaged by acidification. Pteropods shells dissolve with increasing acidification and brittle stars lose muscle mass when re-growing appendages.<ref>{{cite web|title=Effects of Ocean Acidification on Marine Species & Ecosystems|url=http://oceana.org/en/our-work/climate-energy/ocean-acidification/learn-act/effects-of-ocean-acidification-on-marine-species-ecosystems|work=Report|publisher=OCEANA|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> Additionally the brittle star's eggs die within a few days when exposed to expected conditions resulting from Arctic acidification.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cicero.uio.no/webnews/index_e.aspx?id=11909 | title=Comprehensive study of Arctic Ocean acidification | publisher=CICERO | work=Study | accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref> Acidification threatens to destroy Arctic food webs from the base up. Arctic waters are changing rapidly and are advanced in the process of becoming undersaturated with aragonite.<ref name=\"biogeosciences\" /> Arctic food webs are considered simple, meaning there are few steps in the food chain from small organisms to larger predators. For example, pteropods are \"a key prey item of a number of higher predators \u2013 larger plankton, fish, seabirds, whales\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Antarctic marine wildlife is under threat, study finds|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/20461646|publisher=BBC Nature|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Silicates==\nThe rise in agriculture of the past 400 years has increased the exposure rocks and soils, which has resulted in increased rates of silicate weathering. In turn, the leaching of [[Amorphous solid|amorphous]] silica stocks from soils has also increased, delivering higher concentrations of dissolved silica in rivers.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite journal|last=Gaillardet |first=J.|last2=Dupr\u00e9|first2=B. |last3=Louvat |first3=P.|last4=All\u00e8gre |first4=C.J. |date=July 1999 |title=Global silicate weathering and CO2 consumption rates deduced from the chemistry of large rivers|journal=Chemical Geology|volume=159|issue=1\u20134|pages=3\u201330|doi=10.1016/s0009-2541(99)00031-5|issn=0009-2541|bibcode=1999ChGeo.159....3G}}</ref> Conversely, increased damming has led to a reduction in silica supply to the ocean due to uptake by freshwater diatoms behind dams. The dominance of non-siliceous [[phytoplankton]] due to anthropogenic nitrogen and phosphorus loading and enhanced silica [[dissolution (chemistry)|dissolution]] in warmer waters has the potential to limit silicon ocean sediment export in the future.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn 2019 a group of scientists suggested acidification is reducing [[diatom]] silica production in the [[Southern Ocean]].<ref>[https://phys.org/news/2019-08-threat-ocean-acidification-emerges-southern.html New threat from ocean acidification emerges in the Southern Ocean], ''Phys.org'', 26 August 2019.</ref><ref>Petrou, K., Baker, K.G., Nielsen, D.A. et&nbsp;al.  (2019) \"Acidification diminishes diatom silica production in the Southern Ocean\". ''Nature: Climate Change'', '''9''': 781\u2013786. {{doi|10.1038/s41558-019-0557-y}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 170\n | footer            = Changes in [[Orthosilicic acid#Oceanic silicic acid|ocean silicic acid]] can make it difficult for the [[marine microorganism]]s that construct silica shells\n | footer_align      = center\n | footer_background = \n | background color  = \n | image1    = Stephanopyxis grunowii.jpg\n | alt1      = \n | caption1  = {{center|[[Diatom]]}}\n | image2    = Calocycloma sp. - Radiolarian (32163186535).jpg\n | alt2      = \n | caption2  = {{center|[[Radiolarian]]}}\n}}\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=190px style=\"float:right;\">\nFile:WOA09 sea-surf H4SIO4 AYool.png| Concentration of [[silicic acid]] in the upper [[pelagic zone]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nodc.noaa.gov/OC5/WOA09/pr_woa09.html|title=World Ocean Atlas 2009|first=US Department of Commerce, NOAA National Centers for Environmental|last=Information|date=|website=www.nodc.noaa.gov|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref> showing high levels in the Southern Ocean\nFile:Marine Silica Cycle.png| Generalized [[Silica cycle#Marine silica cycling|marine silica cycle]], adapted from [[:fr:Paul Tr\u00e9guer|Treguer]] et&nbsp;al., 1995<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tr\u00e9guer|first=Paul|last2=Nelson|first2=David M.|last3=Bennekom|first3=Aleido J. Van|last4=DeMaster|first4=David J.|last5=Leynaert|first5=Aude|last6=Qu\u00e9guiner|first6=Bernard|date=1995-04-21|title=The Silica Balance in the World Ocean: A Reestimate|journal=Science|language=en|volume=268|issue=5209|pages=375\u2013379|doi=10.1126/science.268.5209.375|issn=0036-8075|pmid=17746543|bibcode=1995Sci...268..375T}}</ref>\n</gallery>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Nitrogen\u2013carbon interactions==\n[[File:Nitrogen\u2013carbon\u2013climate interactions.jpg|thumb|upright=2| Nitrogen\u2013carbon\u2013climate interactions. Shown are the main interacting drivers during the Anthropocene. Signs indicate an increase (+) or a decrease (\u2212) in the factor shown; (?) indicate an unknown impact. Colors of the arrow indicate direct anthropogenic impacts (red) or natural interactions (blue, many of which also modified by human influence). Strength of the interaction is expressed by the arrow thickness.<ref>Cardini, U., Bednarz, V.N., Foster, R.A. and Wild, C. (2014) \"Benthic N2 fixation in coral reefs and the potential effects of human\u2010induced environmental change\". ''Ecology and evolution'', '''4'''(9): 1706\u20131727. {{doi|10.1002/ece3.1050}} [[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License].</ref><ref>Adapted from: Gruber, N., and J. N. Galloway (2008) \"An Earth\u2010system perspective of the global nitrogen cycle\". ''Nature'', 451:293\u2013296. {{doi|10.1038/nature06592}}.</ref>]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Ocean warming==\n[[File:Global Temperature Anomaly 1880-2010 (Fig.A).gif|thumb|upright=1.5| {{center|Global mean land-ocean temperature change from 1880 to 2011, relative to the 1951\u20131980 mean.<br />Source: [http://data.giss.nasa.gov/gistemp/ NASA GISS]}}]]\n{{see also|Effects of global warming on oceans|Ocean heat content}}\n\nMost heat energy from global warming goes into the ocean, and not into the atmosphere or warming up the land.<ref name=IPCC2007 /><ref name=ss /> Scientists realized over 30 years ago the ocean was a key fingerprint of human impact on [[climate change]] and \"the best opportunity for major improvement in our understanding of climate sensitivity is probably monitoring of internal ocean temperature\".<ref>Hansen, J., Fung, I., Lacis, A., Rind, D., Lebedeff, S., Ruedy, R., Russell, G. and Stone, P. (1988) \"Global climate changes as forecast by Goddard Institute for Space Studies three\u2010dimensional model\". ''Journal of geophysical research: Atmospheres'', '''93'''(D8): 9341\u20139364. {{doi|10.1029/JD093iD08p09341}}</ref>\n\nMarine organisms are moving to cooler parts of the ocean as global warming proceeds. For example, a group of 105 marine fish and invertebrate species were monitored along the US Northeast coast and in the eastern Bering Sea. During the period from 1982 to 2015, the average center of biomass for the group shifted northward about 10 miles as well moving about 20 feet deeper.<ref>Data source: NOAA and Rutgers University (2016) [https://oceanadapt.rutgers.edu/ ''OceanAdapt'']</ref><ref name=Pinsky2013>Pinsky, M.L., Worm, B., Fogarty, M.J., Sarmiento, J.L. and Levin, S.A. (2013) \"Marine taxa track local climate velocities\". ''Science'', '''341'''(6151): 1239\u20131242. {{doi|10.1126/science.1239352}}</ref>\n\n[[File:WhereIsTheHeatOfGlobalWarming.jpg|left|thumb| {{center|Most heat energy from global warming goes into the ocean <ref name=IPCC2007>IPCC (2007) [https://archive.ipcc.ch/publications_and_data/ar4/wg1/en/ch5s5-2-2.html Ocean Heat Content] Fourth Assessment Report.</ref>}}]]\n[[File:GlobalWarmingOceanHeatContent.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5| Global heat accumulation data, from Nuccitelli et al. (2012) <ref>Nuccitelli, D., Way, R., Painting, R., Church, J. and Cook, J. (2012) [https://skepticalscience.com/docs/Comment_on_DK12.pdf \"Comment on 'Ocean heat content and Earth\u02bcs radiation imbalance. II. Relation to climate shifts'\"]. ''Physics Letters A'', '''376'''(45): 3466\u20133468. {{doi|10.1016/j.physleta.2012.10.010}}</ref><ref name=ss>[https://skepticalscience.com/graphics.php?g=65 Nuccitelli et al 2012 Total Heat Content] ''Skeptical Science''. Accessed 30 December 2019.</ref>]]\n\nThere is evidence increasing ocean temperatures are taking a toll on marine ecosystem. For example, a study on [[phytoplankton]] changes in the [[Indian Ocean]] indicates a decline of up to 20% in marine phytoplankton during the past six decades.<ref name=\"onlinelibrary.wiley.com\">{{cite journal |last1=Roxy |first1=M.K. |title=A reduction in marine primary productivity driven by rapid warming over the tropical Indian Ocean | year = 2016 | journal = Geophysical Research Letters | volume = 43 | issue = 2 |pages=826\u2013833 | ref = {{Harvid|Roxy|2016}} | doi=10.1002/2015GL066979|bibcode=2016GeoRL..43..826R |url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01259414/file/Roxy_2016_A_reduction_in.pdf }}</ref> During summer, the western Indian Ocean is home to one of the largest concentrations of marine phytoplankton blooms in the world. Increased warming in the Indian Ocean enhances ocean stratification, which prevents nutrient mixing in the [[euphotic zone]] where ample light is available for photosynthesis. Thus, primary production is constrained and the region's entire food web is disrupted. If rapid warming continues, the Indian Ocean could transform into an ecological desert and cease being productive.<ref name=\"onlinelibrary.wiley.com\"/>\n\n{{clear right}}\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=130px style=\"float:right;\">\nFile:Antarctic krill (Euphausia superba).jpg| Ocean warming is changing the distribution of the keystone species [[Antarctic krill]] <ref name=pewtrusts2019 /><ref name=Rogers2019 />\nFile:Trematomus bernacchii.jpg| In the Antarctic, limited-range shallow-water species, like this [[emerald rockcod]], are under threat.<ref name=pewtrusts2019>[https://www.pewtrusts.org/en/research-and-analysis/articles/2019/10/25/climate-change-could-threaten-many-antarctic-marine-species Climate Change Could Threaten Many Antarctic Marine Species] ''Pew'', 25 October 2019.</ref><ref name=Rogers2019>Rogers, A.D., Frinault, B.A.V., Barnes, D.K.A., Bindoff, N.L., Downie, R., Ducklow, H.W., Friedlaender, A.S., Hart, T., Hill, S.L., Hofmann, E.E. and Linse, K. (2019) \"Antarctic futures: an assessment of climate-driven changes in ecosystem structure, function, and service provisioning in the Southern Ocean\". ''Annual review of marine science'', '''12''': 87\u2013120. {{doi|10.1146/annurev-marine-010419-011028}}</ref>\n</gallery>\n\nThe [[Antarctic oscillation]] (also called the ''Southern Annular Mode'') is a belt of [[Westerlies|westerly winds]] or low pressure surrounding [[Antarctica]] which moves north or south according to which phase it is in.<ref>Australian Bureau of Meteorology - The Southern Annular Mode. Accessed 25/10/2013. http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/enso/history/ln-2010-12/SAM-what.shtml</ref> In its positive phase, the westerly wind belt that drives the [[Antarctic Circumpolar Current]] intensifies and contracts towards [[Antarctica]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Thompson|first=David W. J.|last2=Solomon|first2=Susan|last3=Kushner|first3=Paul J.|last4=England|first4=Matthew H.|last5=Grise|first5=Kevin M.|last6=Karoly|first6=David J.|date=2011-10-23|title=Signatures of the Antarctic ozone hole in Southern Hemisphere surface climate change|journal=Nature Geoscience|language=En|volume=4|issue=11|pages=741\u2013749|doi=10.1038/ngeo1296|issn=1752-0894}}</ref> while its negative phase the belt moves towards the Equator. Winds associated with the Antarctic oscillation cause oceanic [[upwelling]] of warm circumpolar deep water along the Antarctic continental shelf.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hayakawa|first=Hideaki|last2=Shibuya|first2=Kazuo|last3=Aoyama|first3=Yuichi|last4=Nogi|first4=Yoshifumi|last5=Doi|first5=Koichiro|date=2012|title=Ocean bottom pressure variability in the Antarctic Divergence Zone off L\u00fctzow-Holm Bay, East Antarctica|journal=Deep Sea Research Part I: Oceanographic Research Papers|volume=60|pages=22\u201331|doi=10.1016/j.dsr.2011.09.005|issn=0967-0637}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Spence|first=Paul|last2=Griffies|first2=Stephen M.|last3=England|first3=Matthew H.|last4=Hogg|first4=Andrew McC.|last5=Saenko|first5=Oleg A.|last6=Jourdain|first6=Nicolas C.|date=2014-07-12|title=Rapid subsurface warming and circulation changes of Antarctic coastal waters by poleward shifting winds|journal=Geophysical Research Letters|language=en|volume=41|issue=13|pages=4601\u20134610|doi=10.1002/2014gl060613|issn=0094-8276|url=https://openresearch-repository.anu.edu.au/bitstream/1885/56321/2/01_Spence_Rapid_subsurface_warming_and_2014.pdf|hdl=1885/56321}}</ref> This has been linked to [[ice shelf]] [[basal melt]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Greene|first=Chad A.|last2=Blankenship|first2=Donald D.|last3=Gwyther|first3=David E.|last4=Silvano|first4=Alessandro|last5=Wijk|first5=Esmee van|date=2017-11-01|title=Wind causes Totten Ice Shelf melt and acceleration|journal=Science Advances|language=en|volume=3|issue=11|pages=e1701681|doi=10.1126/sciadv.1701681|pmid=29109976|issn=2375-2548|pmc=5665591}}</ref> representing a possible wind-driven mechanism that could destabilize large portions of the Antarctic Ice Sheet.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Anderson|first=R. F.|last2=Ali|first2=S.|last3=Bradtmiller|first3=L. I.|last4=Nielsen|first4=S. H. H.|last5=Fleisher|first5=M. Q.|last6=Anderson|first6=B. E.|last7=Burckle|first7=L. H.|date=2009-03-13|title=Wind-Driven Upwelling in the Southern Ocean and the Deglacial Rise in Atmospheric CO2|journal=Science|language=en|volume=323|issue=5920|pages=1443\u20131448|doi=10.1126/science.1167441|issn=0036-8075|pmid=19286547}}</ref> The Antarctic oscillation is currently in the most extreme positive phase that has occurred for over a thousand years. Recently this positive phase has been further intensifying, and this has been attributed to increasing [[greenhouse gas]] levels and later stratospheric ozone depletion.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/paleo-search/study/16197|accessdate = 5 January 2020|title = 1000-year Southern Annular Mode Reconstruction|publisher = NOAA: [[National Climatic Data Center]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Abram |first=Nerilie|url=http://www.nature.com/nclimate/journal/v4/n7/full/nclimate2235.html |title=Evolution of the Southern Annular Mode during the past millennium |work=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |date=2014-05-11 |accessdate=2014-09-13 }}</ref> These large-scale alterations in the physical environment are \"driving change through all levels of Antarctic marine food webs\".<ref name=pewtrusts2019 /><ref name=Rogers2019 /> Ocean warming is also changing the distribution of [[Antarctic krill]].<ref name=pewtrusts2019 /><ref name=Rogers2019 /> Antarctic krill is the [[keystone species]] of the [[Antarctic]] ecosystem beyond the coastal shelf, and is an important food source for [[marine mammal]]s and [[Sea bird|birds]].<ref>{{cite book |editor1=Guido di Prisco |editor2=Cinzia Verde |series=Adaptation and Evolution in Marine Environments |volume=1 |title=The Impacts of Global Change on Biodiversity |publisher=Springer Science & Business Media |year=2012 |isbn=9783642273513 |chapter=Sea-ice interactions with polar fish: focus on the Antarctic silverfish life history |author=Mario Vacchi |author2=Philippe Koubbi |author3=Laura Ghigliotti |author4=Eva Pisano |pages=51\u201373<!-- at p. 63 --> |doi=10.1007/978-3-642-27352-0_4}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\nThe [[IPCC]] (2019) says marine organisms are being affected globally by ocean warming with direct impacts on human communities, fisheries, and food production.<ref>{{Cite report| series = Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate (SROCC) |title=Chapter 5: Changing Ocean, Marine Ecosystems, and Dependent Communities|work=IPCC| access-date = 25 March 2020 |date = 25 September 2019| url = https://report.ipcc.ch/srocc/pdf/SROCC_FinalDraft_Chapter5.pdf |format=PDF |pages=5\u20136}}</ref> It is likely there will be a 15% decrease in the number of marine animals and a decrease of 21% to 24% in fisheries catches by the end of the 21st century because of climate change.<ref>{{Cite web| title = 'We're All in Big Trouble': Climate Panel Sees a Dire Future |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] via the Associated Press | access-date = 25 March 2020 |date = 25 September 2019| url = https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2019/09/25/science/ap-us-sci-climate-report.html?partner=IFTTT}}</ref>\n\n==Rising sea levels==\n[[File:Sea level change 1993 to 2018.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5| Between 1993 and 2018, the mean sea level has risen across most of the world ocean (blue colors).<ref>Lindsey, Rebecca (2019) [https://www.climate.gov/news-features/understanding-climate/climate-change-global-sea-level Climate Change: Global Sea Level] ''NOAA Climate'', 19 November 2019.</ref>]]\n\nCoastal ecosystems are facing further changes because of [[rising sea level]]s. Some ecosystems can move inland with the high-water mark, but others are prevented from migrating due to natural or artificial barriers. This coastal narrowing, called [[wiktionary:coastal squeeze|coastal squeeze]] if human-made barriers are involved, can result in the [[loss of habitat]]s such as [[mudflat]]s and [[marsh]]es.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://datazone.birdlife.org/sea-level-rise-poses-a-major-threat-to-coastal-ecosystems-and-the-biota-they-support|title=Sea level rise poses a major threat to coastal ecosystems and the biota they support|date=2015|website=birdlife.org|publisher=Birdlife International}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pontee |first1=Nigel |title=Defining coastal squeeze: A discussion |journal=Ocean & Coastal Management |date=November 2013 |volume=84 |pages=204\u2013207 |doi=10.1016/j.ocecoaman.2013.07.010 }}</ref> [[Mangroves]] and [[tidal marsh]]es adjust to rising sea levels by building vertically using accumulated [[sediment]] and [[organic matter]]. If sea level rise is too rapid, they will not be able to keep up and will instead be submerged.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Krauss |first1=Ken W. |last2=McKee |first2=Karen L. |last3=Lovelock |first3=Catherine E. |last4=Cahoon |first4=Donald R. |last5=Saintilan |first5=Neil |last6=Reef |first6=Ruth |last7=Chen |first7=Luzhen |title=How mangrove forests adjust to rising sea level |journal=New Phytologist |date=April 2014 |volume=202 |issue=1 |pages=19\u201334 |doi=10.1111/nph.12605 |pmid=24251960 |url=https://digitalcommons.unl.edu/usgsstaffpub/986 }}</ref> \n\n[[File:Sea Level Change 1880 to 2015.png|thumb|left| {{center|Sea level change, 1880 to 2015 <ref>[http://www.cmar.csiro.au/sealevel/sl_data_cmar.html CSIRO 2015 update] to data originally published in: Church, J.A., and N.J. White (2011) \"Sea-level rise from the late 19th to the early 21st century\". ''Surv. Geophys.'', '''32''': 585\u2013602.</ref><ref>NOAA Laboratory for Satellite Altimetry (2016) [https://www.star.nesdis.noaa.gov/sod/lsa/SeaLevelRise/LSA_SLR_timeseries_global.php Global sea level time series]. Accessed: June 2016.</ref>}}]]\n\nCoral, important for bird and fish life, also needs to grow vertically to remain close to the sea surface in order to get enough energy from sunlight. So far it has been able to keep up, but might not be able to do so in the future.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Climate Change 2014: Impacts, Adaptation, and Vulnerability.|last=Wong|first=Poh Poh|last2=Losado|first2=I.J.|last3=Gattuso|first3=J.-P.|last4=Hinkel|first4=Jochen|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2014|isbn=|location=New York|pages=|chapter=Coastal Systems and Low-Lying Areas|chapter-url=http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/assessment-report/ar5/wg2/WGIIAR5-Chap5_FINAL.pdf}}</ref> These ecosystems protect against storm surges, waves and tsunamis. Losing them makes the effects of sea level rise worse.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Crosby |first1=Sarah C. |last2=Sax |first2=Dov F. |last3=Palmer |first3=Megan E. |last4=Booth |first4=Harriet S. |last5=Deegan |first5=Linda A. |last6=Bertness |first6=Mark D. |last7=Leslie |first7=Heather M. |title=Salt marsh persistence is threatened by predicted sea-level rise |journal=Estuarine, Coastal and Shelf Science |date=November 2016 |volume=181 |pages=93\u201399 |doi=10.1016/j.ecss.2016.08.018 |bibcode=2016ECSS..181...93C |doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nature.org/media/oceansandcoasts/mangroves-for-coastal-defence.pdf|title=Mangroves for coastal defence. Guidelines for coastal managers & policy makers|author1=Spalding M.|author2=McIvor A.|date=2014|publisher=[[Wetlands International]] and [[The Nature Conservancy]]|author3=Tonneijck F.H.|author4=Tol S.|author5=van Eijk P.}}</ref> Human activities, such as dam building, can prevent natural adaptation processes by restricting sediment supplies to wetlands, resulting in the loss of [[tidal marsh]]es.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Weston |first1=Nathaniel B. |title=Declining Sediments and Rising Seas: an Unfortunate Convergence for Tidal Wetlands |journal=Estuaries and Coasts |date=16 July 2013 |volume=37 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201323 |doi=10.1007/s12237-013-9654-8 }}</ref>  When seawater moves inland, the [[coastal flooding]] can cause problems with existing terrestrial ecosystems, such as contaminating their soils.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/global-warming/sea-level-rise/|title=Sea Level Rise|date=January 13, 2017|website=National Geographic}}</ref> The [[Bramble Cay melomys]] is the first known land mammal to go extinct as a result of sea level rise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/news/2016/06/extinct-bramble-cay-melomys|title=Extinct: Bramble Cay melomys|last=Smith|first=Lauren|date=2016-06-15|website=Australian Geographic|access-date=2016-06-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/environment/climate-change/our-little-brown-rat-first-climate-change-caused-mammal-extinction-20190219-p50yry.html|title='Our little brown rat': first climate change-caused mammal extinction|last=Hannam|first=Peter|date=2019-02-19|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Ocean circulation and salinity==\n[[File:Overturning circulation of the global ocean.jpg|thumb|360px| {{center|[[Thermohaline circulation]], the ocean conveyor belt}}]]\n[[File:Aquarius flat 2048x1024.ogv|thumb|360px| {{center|Surface salinity changes measured by the [[Aquarius (SAC-D instrument)|NASA Aquarius]] satellite instrument from December 2011 to December 2012<br />Blue: low salinity &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Red: high salinity}}]]\n\nOcean salinity is a measure of how much dissolved [[Sea salt|salt]] is in the ocean. The salts come from erosion and transport of dissolved salts from the land. The surface salinity of the ocean is a key variable in the climate system when studying the global [[water cycle]], [[ocean\u2013atmosphere exchange]]s and [[ocean circulation]], all vital components transporting heat, momentum, carbon and nutrients around the world.<ref name=ESA>[https://phys.org/news/2019-12-salinity-reveal-impact-climate-variability.html New maps of salinity reveal the impact of climate variability on oceans] European Space Agency, 2 December 2019, ''PHYS.ORG''.</ref> Cold water is more dense than warm water and salty water is more dense than freshwater. This means the density of ocean water changes as its temperature and salinity changes. These changes in density are the main source of the power that drives the ocean circulation.<ref name=ESA />\n\nSurface ocean salinity measurements taken since the 1950s indicate an intensification of the global water cycle with high saline areas becoming more saline and low saline areas becoming more less saline.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/27/world/study-hints-at-greater-threat-of-extreme-weather.html |title=Study Indicates a Greater Threat of Extreme Weather |first=Justin |last=Gillis |date=April 26, 2012 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=2012-04-27 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426225622/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/27/world/study-hints-at-greater-threat-of-extreme-weather.html |archivedate=2012-04-26 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/aquarius/news/data-first-year.html |title=NASA's Aquarius Sees Salty Shifts |last=Vinas |first=Maria-Jose |date=June 6, 2013 |publisher=NASA |access-date=2018-01-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516200108/https://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/aquarius/news/data-first-year.html |archivedate=2017-05-16}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Ocean deoxygenation==\n[[File:Nitrogen cycle OMZ.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|{{center|[[Nitrogen cycle]] and the [[oxygen minimum zone]]}}]]\n\n[[Ocean deoxygenation]] is an additional stressor on marine life. Ocean deoxygenation is the expansion of [[oxygen minimum zone]]s in the oceans as a consequence of [[carbon emissions|burning fossil fuels]]. The change has been fairly rapid and poses a threat to fish and other types of marine life, as well as to people who depend on marine life for nutrition or livelihood.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/jan/04/oceans-suffocating-dead-zones-oxygen-starved Oceans suffocating as huge dead zones quadruple since 1950, scientists warn] The Guardian, 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/ocean-s-oxygen-starts-running-low/ Ocean's Oxygen Starts Running Low]</ref><ref>[https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/2015GB005310 Finding forced trends in oceanic oxygen]</ref><ref>[https://www.carbonbrief.org/guest-post-how-global-warming-is-causing-ocean-oxygen-levels-to-fall How global warming is causing ocean oxygen levels to fall]</ref> Ocean deoxygenation poses implications for [[Primary production|ocean productivity]], nutrient cycling, [[carbon cycling]], and [[marine habitats]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/dec/07/oceans-losing-oxygen-at-unprecedented-rate-experts-warn|title=Oceans losing oxygen at unprecedented rate, experts warn|last=Harvey|first=Fiona|date=2019-12-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>Laffoley, D. and Baxter, J. M. (eds.) (2019) [https://www.iucn.org/content/ocean-deoxygenation-everyones-problem Ocean deoxygenation : everyone\u2019s problem], IUCN Report.</ref>\n\nOcean warming exacerbates ocean deoxygenation and further stresses marine organisms, limiting nutrient availability by increasing [[ocean stratification]] through density and solubility effects while at the same time increasing metabolic demand.<ref>Bednar\u0161ek, N., Harvey, C.J., Kaplan, I.C., Feely, R.A. and Mo\u017eina, J. (2016) \"Pteropods on the edge: Cumulative effects of ocean acidification, warming, and deoxygenation\". ''Progress in Oceanography'', '''145''': 1\u201324. {{doi|10.1016/j.pocean.2016.04.002}}</ref><ref>Keeling, Ralph F., and Hernan E. Garcia (2002) \"The change in oceanic O2 inventory associated with recent global warming.\" ''Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences'', '''99'''(12): 7848\u20137853. {{doi|10.1073/pnas.122154899}}</ref> According to the IPCC 2019 [[Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate]], the viability of species is being disrupted throughout the [[ocean food web]] due to changes in ocean chemistry. As the ocean warms, [[Mixed layer|mixing between water layers]] decreases, resulting in less oxygen and nutrients being available for [[marine life]].<ref>{{Cite press release |series=Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate (SROCC) |title=Press Release |work=IPCC| access-date = 25 March 2020 |date = 25 September 2019| url = https://www.ipcc.ch/site/assets/uploads/sites/3/2019/09/SROCC_PressRelease_EN.pdf |format=PDF |pages=3}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Multiple stressors==\n[[File:Ecological Processes Coral Reefs.jpg|thumb|360px| {{center|Multiple stressors acting on [[Environmental issues with coral reefs|coral reefs]] <ref>Pendleton, L.H., Hoegh-Guldberg, O., Langdon, C. and Comte, A. (2016) \"Multiple stressors and ecological complexity require a new approach to coral reef research\". ''Frontiers in Marine Science'', '''3''': 36. {{doi|10.3389/fmars.2016.00036}}</ref>}}]]\n\nIf more than one stressor is present the effects can be amplified.<ref>Breitburg, D.L. and Riedel, G.F. (2005) [https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=J-2JcCC_Yn0C&pg=PA167&dq=%22Multiple+stressors+in+marine+systems%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjHmarigfbmAhXF6nMBHY-kAE0Q6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=%22Multiple%20stressors%20in%20marine%20systems%22&f=false \"Multiple stressors in marine systems\"]. In: M. E. Soul\u00e9, ''Marine conservation biology: the science of maintaining the sea's biodiversity'', Island Press, pages 167\u2013182. {{ISBN|9781597267717}}</ref><ref>Bopp, L., Resplandy, L., Orr, J.C., Doney, S.C., Dunne, J.P., Gehlen, M., Halloran, P., Heinze, C., Ilyina, T., Seferian, R. and Tjiputra, J. (2013) \"Multiple stressors of ocean ecosystems in the 21st century: projections with CMIP5 models\". ''Biogeosciences'', '''10''': 6225\u20136245. {{doi|10.5194/bg-10-6225-2013}}</ref> For example, the combination of ocean acidification and an elevation of ocean temperature can have a compounded effect on marine life far exceeding the individual harmful impact of either.<ref>Kroeker, et al. (June  2013) \"Impacts of ocean acidification on marine organisms: quantifying sensitivities and interaction with warming.\" Glob Chang Biol. 19(6): 1884\u20131896</ref><ref name=Harvey2013>Harvey B.P., Gwynn\u2010Jones D. and Moore P.J. (2013) \"Meta\u2010analysis reveals complex marine biological responses to the interactive effects of ocean acidification and warming\". ''Ecology and evolution'', '''3'''(4): 1016\u20131030. {{doi|10.1002/ece3.516}}</ref><ref>Nagelkerken Global alteration of ocean ecosystem functioning due to increasing human CO2 emissions, PNAS vol. 112 no. 43, 2015</ref>\n\nThe direction and magnitude of the effects of ocean acidification, warming and deoxygenation on the ocean has been quantified by [[meta-analyses]],<ref name=Harvey2013 /><ref>Gruber, Nicolas. \"Warming up, turning sour, losing breath: ocean biogeochemistry under global change.\" Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London A: Mathematical, Physical and Engineering Sciences 369.1943 (2011): 1980\u20131996.</ref><ref>Anthony, et al. (May 2011) \"Ocean acidification and warming will lower coral reef resilience.\" Global Change biology, Volume 17, Issue 5, Pages 1798\u20131808</ref> and has been further tested by [[mesocosm]] studies. The mesocosm studies simulated the interaction of these stressors and found a catastrophic effect on the marine food web, namely, that the increases in consumption from thermal stress more than negates any primary producer to herbivore increase from more available carbon dioxide.<ref>Goldenberg, Silvan U, et al. (2017) \"Boosted food web productivity through ocean acidification collapses under warming.\" Global Change Biology.</ref><ref>Pistevos, Jennifer CA, et al. (2015) \"Ocean acidification and global warming impair shark hunting behaviour and growth.\" Scientific reports 5: 16293.</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Microorganisms==\n[[File:Microorganisms and climate change.png|thumb|right|upright=2| {{center|Microorganisms and climate change in marine and terrestrial biomes <ref name=Cavicchioli2019 />}}]]\n{{see also|Marine microorganism}}\n\nIn marine environments, microbial [[primary production]] contributes substantially to [[Carbon sequestration|CO<sub>2</sub> sequestration]]. Marine microorganisms also recycle nutrients for use in the [[marine food web]] and in the process release CO<sub>2</sub> to the atmosphere. Microbial biomass and other organic matter (remnants of plants and animals) are converted to fossil fuels over millions of years. By contrast, burning of [[fossil fuel]]s liberates greenhouse gases in a small fraction of that time. As a result, the [[carbon cycle]] is out of balance, and atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> levels will continue to rise as long as fossil fuels continue to be burnt.<ref name=Cavicchioli2019>Cavicchioli, R., Ripple, W.J., Timmis, K.N., Azam, F., Bakken, L.R., Baylis, M., Behrenfeld, M.J., Boetius, A., Boyd, P.W., Classen, A.T. and Crowther, T.W. (2019) \"Scientists\u2019 warning to humanity: microorganisms and climate change\". ''Nature Reviews Microbiology'', '''17''': 569\u2013586. {{doi|10.1038/s41579-019-0222-5}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Drivers of change==\n[[File:Drivers of change in marine ecosystems.png|thumb|360px| {{center|Drivers of change in marine ecosystems <ref name=\u00d6sterblom2017>\u00d6sterblom, H., Crona, B.I., Folke, C., Nystr\u00f6m, M. and Troell, M. (2017) \"Marine ecosystem science on an intertwined planet\". ''Ecosystems'', '''20'''(1): 54\u201361. {{doi|10.1007/s10021-016-9998-6}}</ref>}}]]\n\nChanges in marine ecosystem dynamics are influenced by socioeconomic activities (for example, fishing, pollution) and human-induced biophysical change (for example, temperature, ocean acidification) and can interact and severely impact marine ecosystem dynamics and the ecosystem services they generate to society. Understanding these direct\u2014or proximate\u2014interactions is an important step towards sustainable use of marine ecosystems. However, proximate interactions are embedded in a much broader socioeconomic context where, for example, economy through trade and finance, human migration and technological advances, operate and interact at a global scale, influencing proximate relationships.<ref name=\u00d6sterblom2017 />\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Shifting baselines==\n[[Shifting baselines]] arise in research on marine ecosystems because changes must be measured against some previous reference point (baseline), which in turn may represent significant changes from an even earlier state of the ecosystem.<ref name=Pauly1995>Pauly, Daniel (1995) [http://legacy.seaaroundus.s3.amazonaws.com/doc/Researcher+Publications/dpauly/PDF/1995/Journal+Articles/Anecdotes%26ShiftingBaselineSyndromeFisheries.pdf \"Anecdotes and the shifting baseline syndrome of fisheries\"]. ''Trends in ecology & evolution'', '''10'''(10): 430.</ref> For example, radically depleted fisheries have been evaluated by researchers who used the state of the fishery at the start of their careers as the baseline, rather than the fishery in its unexploited or untouched state. Areas that swarmed with a particular species hundreds of years ago may have experienced long term decline, but it is the level a few decades previously that is used as the reference point for current populations. In this way large declines in ecosystems or species over long periods of time were, and are, masked. There is a loss of perception of change that occurs when each generation redefines what is natural or untouched.<ref name=Pauly1995 />\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=26em}}\n* [[Anthropocene]]\n* [[Climate change and ecosystems]]\n* [[Climate change in the Arctic]]\n* [[Effects of climate change on terrestrial animals]]\n* [[Effects of global warming on marine mammals]]\n* [[Global warming in Antarctica]]\n* [[Marine debris]]\n* [[Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate]]\n* [[Threatened rays]]\n* [[Threatened sharks]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Human impact on the environment|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Human impact on the environment]]\n", "name_user": "Epipelagic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHabitat loss:reorder", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_impact_on_marine_life"}
