row as a stronger athlete. [https://www.strength-and-power-for-volleyball.com/beach-volleyball.html]{{Dominican-Republic-stub}}{{Volleyball-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SierraCad", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dominican_Republic_National_Beach_Volleyball_Tour"}
{"title_page": "Sixways Stadium", "text_new": "{{short description|Sports venue in Worchester, England}}\n{{Distinguish|Sixfields Stadium}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name     = Sixways Stadium\n| nickname         = Sixways\n| image            = Sixways SlickSystems East Stand.jpg\n| caption          = The East Stand to the east of the stadium\n| location         = Warriors Way, Worcester WR3 8ZE<ref name=about/>\n| coordinates      = {{coord|52|12|56|N|2|09|45|W|region:GB_type:landmark_source:dewiki|display=it}}\n| opened           = 1998\n| renovated        = 2008<ref name=about/>\n| surface          = Limonta Max S Turf\n| tenants          = [[Worcester Warriors]]\n| seating_capacity = 11,499<ref name=about/>\n}}\n'''Sixways Stadium''' is a stadium in [[Worcester, England]].  It is currently used mostly for [[rugby union]] matches and is the home stadium of [[Worcester Warriors]]. The stadium is able to hold 11,499 with parking for 1,000 cars, Sixways has 60 modern meeting and event rooms .<ref name=about>{{cite web | url=http://www.warriors.co.uk/club/about.php | title=About Sixways Stadium | publisher=[[Worcester Warriors]] | accessdate=31 July 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705133124/http://www.warriors.co.uk/club/about.php | archivedate=5 July 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The ground opened 1975 and is located off junction 6 of the [[M5 motorway]], which splits into six directions, hence the name Sixways. The Stadium commenced building on the site of the old 3rd team pitch and club house after a lottery grant in 1998.\n\nOn 7 April 2016 it was announced that Sixways' pitch would be converted to the latest technology [[artificial grass]] ahead of the 2016&ndash;17 season. Sixways would become the third premiership venue with an artificial pitch after [[Barnet Copthall|Allianz Park]] and [[Kingston Park (stadium)|Kingston Park]] but the first to feature organic infill rather than rubber crumb.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worcesternews.co.uk/sport/wrfc/news/14411062.Worcester_Warriors_to_install_synthetic_pitch_for_next_season/|title=Worcester Warriors to install synthetic pitch for next season|website=Worcester Warriors|publisher=Worcester News|last1=Berkely|first1=Geoff|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== East Stand ==\nThe main focal point of Sixways Stadium is the magnificent East Stand which was completed in 2008 and has become one of the iconic images of Worcester on arrival in the city from the M5.\n\nThe multimillion-pound development on the east side of the stadium complex includes The PitchView Restaurant, The Business Club, The Duckworth Suite, The Worcester Suite, The Hindlip Suite and many boxes which are utilised every day of the year. Below the stand is the Slick Systems Supporters bar area for fans to enjoy on matchdays and many food outlets and programme booths.\n\nThe entrance to the East Stand is through the main glass fronted club reception which is also home to the Sixways Store and Warriors Ticket Office which are open throughout the week.\n\n== West Stand ==\nThe popular West Stand at Sixways Stadium has become a key gathering point for fans on matchdays as the most established stand at the home of the Warriors. The West Stand houses the Clubhouse Bar which offers a wide selection of draught and bottled beer. There is also a separate food counter serving hot snacks and in front of the bar is a large standing area to take in all the action.\n\nThe Sixways Premier Suites Upper and Lower are located to the south end of the stand and offer a large bar area and dance floor with a live band after every game. A lively and friendly sociable atmosphere is guaranteed to greet both home and away supporters after the action!\n\nAbove the Clubhouse Bar on the second floor is the International Bar which is full of rugby memorabilia past and present - and offers a fantastic view of all the action! Opposite is the Hallmark Bar which hosts an exclusive bar and dining area open to West Stand Debenture holders.\n\nThe West Stand is also home to the indoor training centre, changing rooms and rugby department offices which become the main training area for the Warriors during the week.\n\n== South Stand ==\nStanding proud behind the posts at Sixways Stadium, the South Stand is a busy and lively place to watch the action unfold on a big Warriors match day. The stand hosts 30 hospitality boxes for supporters to take in all the action over two floors with spacious bar areas to the rear.\n\nThe South Stand Terrace, in the middle of the stand, is a busy bar area where supporters can meet and enjoy food and drink before, during and after the kick-off at Warriors.\n\n== North Stand ==\nThe all-seater North Stand gives supporters the chance to get close up to the action with easy access to bars to the left and right of the stand on match days. Popular with groups, the stand also hosts many of our Family Season Tickets. One of the most easily accessible areas of the stadium and with reasonably priced tickets, this stand often attracts many newcomers to the game eager to enjoy a Warriors fixture. Plans have been approved to increase the North Stand at Sixways Stadium to make it the same size as the Slick Systems Stand in years to come and complete an impressive looking front to the complex on arrival.\n\n==Finals==\nThe stadium hosted the [[2009\u201310 LV Cup]] final on 21 March 2010 between [[Northampton Saints]] and [[Gloucester Rugby|Gloucester]]. Northampton won 30\u201324.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/8571457.stm | title=Northampton 30-24 Gloucester | publisher=[[BBC]] | date=21 March 2010 | accessdate=31 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nSixways hosted the [[2011\u201312 LV Cup]] final on 18 March 2012 between [[Leicester Tigers]] and [[Northampton Saints]]. Leicester won 26\u201314.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.premiershiprugby.com/matchcentre/fixtures/1361.php | title=Leicester Tigers 26 - 14 Northampton Saints | publisher=premiershiprugby.com | date=18 March 2012 | accessdate=31 July 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107124338/http://www.premiershiprugby.com/matchcentre/fixtures/1361.php | archivedate=7 January 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe stadium also hosted the [[2012\u201313 LV Cup]] final on 17 March 2013.  [[Harlequin F.C.|Harlequins]] defeated [[Sale Sharks]] 32\u201314 in front of 8,100 spectators<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.premiershiprugby.com/matchcentre/fixtures/23547.php | title=Harlequins 32 - 14 Sale Sharks | publisher=premiershiprugby.com | date=17 March 2013 | accessdate=31 July 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924081242/http://www.premiershiprugby.com/matchcentre/fixtures/23547.php | archivedate=24 September 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and gained a place in the [[2013\u201314 Heineken Cup]] as a result.\n\nThe stadium has also hosted the [[Britbowl]], the championship game of British [[American Football]] twice, in 2010 and 2016.  [[London Blitz (American football)|London Blitz]] played in both finals, beating [[Coventry Jets]] 34-20 in 2010 and losing to [[London Warriors]] 36-15 in 2016.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170705133124/http://www.warriors.co.uk/club/about.php About Sixways Stadium]\n* [http://www.sixwaysstadium.co.uk/ Events & Conferencing]\n\n{{English Premiership (rugby union) venues}}\n\n[[Category:Rugby union stadiums in England]]\n[[Category:Worcester Warriors]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Worcestershire]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1975]]\n[[Category:American football venues in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Sports venue in Worchester, England}}\n{{Distinguish|Sixfields Stadium}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name = Sixways Stadium\n| nickname = Sixways\n| image = [[File:Sixways SlickSystems East Stand.jpg|300px]]\n| caption = View of the East Stand to the east of the Stadium.\n| location = Warriors Way, Worcester WR3 8ZE<ref name=about/>\n| coordinates = {{coord|52|12|56|N|2|09|45|W|region:GB_type:landmark_source:dewiki|display=it}}\n| Stadium building commenced = 1998\n| Ground opened = 1975\n| renovated = 2008<ref name=about/>\n| surface = Limonta Max S Turf\n| tenants = [[Worcester Warriors]]\n| seating_capacity = 11,499<ref name=about/>\n}}\n'''Sixways Stadium''' is a [[stadium]] in [[Worcester]], [[England]].  It is currently used mostly for [[rugby union]] matches and is the home stadium of [[Worcester Warriors]]. The stadium is able to hold 11,499 with parking for 1,000 cars, Sixways has 60 modern meeting and event rooms .<ref name=about>{{cite web | url=http://www.warriors.co.uk/club/about.php | title=About Sixways Stadium | publisher=[[Worcester Warriors]] | accessdate=31 July 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705133124/http://www.warriors.co.uk/club/about.php | archivedate=5 July 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The ground opened 1975 and is located off junction 6 of the [[M5 motorway]], which splits into six directions, hence the name Sixways. The Stadium commenced building on the site of the old 3rd team pitch and club house after a lottery grant in 1998.\n\nOn 7 April 2016 it was announced that Sixways' pitch would be converted to the latest technology [[artificial grass]] ahead of the 2016&ndash;17 season. Sixways would become the third premiership venue with an artificial pitch after [[Barnet Copthall|Allianz Park]] and [[Kingston Park (stadium)|Kingston Park]] but the first to feature organic infill rather than rubber crumb.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worcesternews.co.uk/sport/wrfc/news/14411062.Worcester_Warriors_to_install_synthetic_pitch_for_next_season/|title=Worcester Warriors to install synthetic pitch for next season|website=Worcester Warriors|publisher=Worcester News|last1=Berkely|first1=Geoff|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== East Stand ==\nThe main focal point of Sixways Stadium is the magnificent East Stand which was completed in 2008 and has become one of the iconic images of Worcester on arrival in the city from the M5.\n\nThe multimillion-pound development on the east side of the stadium complex includes The PitchView Restaurant, The Business Club, The Duckworth Suite, The Worcester Suite, The Hindlip Suite and many boxes which are utilised every day of the year. Below the stand is the Slick Systems Supporters bar area for fans to enjoy on matchdays and many food outlets and programme booths.\n\nThe entrance to the East Stand is through the main glass fronted club reception which is also home to the Sixways Store and Warriors Ticket Office which are open throughout the week.\n\n== West Stand ==\nThe popular West Stand at Sixways Stadium has become a key gathering point for fans on matchdays as the most established stand at the home of the Warriors. The West Stand houses the Clubhouse Bar which offers a wide selection of draught and bottled beer. There is also a separate food counter serving hot snacks and in front of the bar is a large standing area to take in all the action.\n\nThe Sixways Premier Suites Upper and Lower are located to the south end of the stand and offer a large bar area and dance floor with a live band after every game. A lively and friendly sociable atmosphere is guaranteed to greet both home and away supporters after the action!\n\nAbove the Clubhouse Bar on the second floor is the International Bar which is full of rugby memorabilia past and present - and offers a fantastic view of all the action! Opposite is the Hallmark Bar which hosts an exclusive bar and dining area open to West Stand Debenture holders.\n\nThe West Stand is also home to the indoor training centre, changing rooms and rugby department offices which become the main training area for the Warriors during the week.\n\n== South Stand ==\nStanding proud behind the posts at Sixways Stadium, the South Stand is a busy and lively place to watch the action unfold on a big Warriors match day. The stand hosts 30 hospitality boxes for supporters to take in all the action over two floors with spacious bar areas to the rear.\n\nThe South Stand Terrace, in the middle of the stand, is a busy bar area where supporters can meet and enjoy food and drink before, during and after the kick-off at Warriors.\n\n== North Stand ==\nThe all-seater North Stand gives supporters the chance to get close up to the action with easy access to bars to the left and right of the stand on match days. Popular with groups, the stand also hosts many of our Family Season Tickets. One of the most easily accessible areas of the stadium and with reasonably priced tickets, this stand often attracts many newcomers to the game eager to enjoy a Warriors fixture. Plans have been approved to increase the North Stand at Sixways Stadium to make it the same size as the Slick Systems Stand in years to come and complete an impressive looking front to the complex on arrival.\n\n==Finals==\nThe stadium hosted the [[2009\u201310 LV Cup]] final on 21 March 2010 between [[Northampton Saints]] and [[Gloucester Rugby|Gloucester]]. Northampton won 30\u201324.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/8571457.stm | title=Northampton 30-24 Gloucester | publisher=[[BBC]] | date=21 March 2010 | accessdate=31 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nSixways hosted the [[2011\u201312 LV Cup]] final on 18 March 2012 between [[Leicester Tigers]] and [[Northampton Saints]]. Leicester won 26\u201314.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.premiershiprugby.com/matchcentre/fixtures/1361.php | title=Leicester Tigers 26 - 14 Northampton Saints | publisher=premiershiprugby.com | date=18 March 2012 | accessdate=31 July 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107124338/http://www.premiershiprugby.com/matchcentre/fixtures/1361.php | archivedate=7 January 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe stadium also hosted the [[2012\u201313 LV Cup]] final on 17 March 2013.  [[Harlequin F.C.|Harlequins]] defeated [[Sale Sharks]] 32\u201314 in front of 8,100 spectators<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.premiershiprugby.com/matchcentre/fixtures/23547.php | title=Harlequins 32 - 14 Sale Sharks | publisher=premiershiprugby.com | date=17 March 2013 | accessdate=31 July 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924081242/http://www.premiershiprugby.com/matchcentre/fixtures/23547.php | archivedate=24 September 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and gained a place in the [[2013\u201314 Heineken Cup]] as a result.\n\nThe stadium has also hosted the [[Britbowl]], the championship game of British [[American Football]] twice, in 2010 and 2016.  [[London Blitz (American football)|London Blitz]] played in both finals, beating [[Coventry Jets]] 34-20 in 2010 and losing to [[London Warriors]] 36-15 in 2016.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170705133124/http://www.warriors.co.uk/club/about.php About Sixways Stadium]\n* [http://www.sixwaysstadium.co.uk/ Events & Conferencing]\n\n{{English Premiership (rugby union) venues}}\n\n[[Category:Rugby union stadiums in England]]\n[[Category:Worcester Warriors]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Worcestershire]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1975]]\n[[Category:American football venues in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sixways_Stadium"}
